reer\n| 72 || 72 || 32.2 || .427 || .327 || .713 || 7.8 || 6.0 || 1.1 || .3 || 21.2\n{{S-end}}\n\n==NBA records and accomplishments==\n*First teenager to record a 30-point triple-double (35 points, 12 rebounds, 10 assists).<ref>https://thesmokingcuban.com/2019/02/28/dallas-mavericks-2019-luka-doncic-achievements-before-20/4/</ref>\n*Second player in NBA history to post 2,000+ points, 750+ rebounds and 500+ assists in their first 100 career games (alongside [[Oscar Robertson]]).<ref>https://twitter.com/MavsPR/status/1211513815810134016</ref>\n*NBA record of 20 straight games with at least 20 points, 5 rebounds, and 5 assists. Previously held by [[Michael Jordan]] with 18 consecutive games.<ref>https://www.talkbasket.net/60560-luka-doncic-breaks-michael-jordans-record</ref>\n*Youngest player in NBA history to record three triple-doubles.<ref>{{cite web |title=NBA: Doncic nets triple-double in Mavs' win over Hornets |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/02/07/19/nba-doncic-nets-triple-double-in-mavs-win-over-hornets |website=news.abs-cbn.com |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*Only player in NBA history to record two triple-doubles before the age of 20.<ref>https://spainsnews.com/luka-doncic-breaks-another-record-in-the-nba/</ref>\n*Don\u010di\u0107 has four of the five triple-doubles recorded by teenagers in NBA history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic has 4 of the 5 triple-doubles recorded by teenagers in NBA history |url=https://clutchpoints.com/mavs-news-luka-doncic-has-4-of-the-5-triple-doubles-recorded-by-teenagers-in-nba-history/ |website=clutchpoints.com |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*Youngest player to have 35-point triple-doubles in succession, breaking [[Oscar Robertson]]'s record.<ref> youngest player to have 35-point triple-doubles in succession, breaking Oscar Robertson's record</ref>\n*First player in NBA history to record 30+ points, 12+ rebounds, and 15+ assists in a game with 30 minutes or fewer played.\n*First player in NBA history to record multiple 30-point triple-doubles in games with 30 minutes or fewer played.<ref>https://heavy.com/sports/2019/12/mavericks-luka-doncic-warriors-nba/</ref>\n*At 19 years and 327 days old he recorded his first-ever triple-double, just ten days older than the youngest player ever, [[Markelle Fultz]].<ref>https://thesmokingcuban.com/2019/02/28/dallas-mavericks-2019-luka-doncic-achievements-before-20/3/</ref>\n* Fifth player in NBA history to average at least 20 points, 5 rebounds and 5 assists in his rookie year, joining [[Oscar Robertson]] ([[1960\u201361 NBA season|1960\u201361]]), Michael Jordan ([[1984\u201385 NBA season|1984\u201385]]), [[LeBron James]] ([[2003\u201304 NBA season|2003\u201304]]), and [[Tyreke Evans]] ([[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic: A Rookie Year in Context|url=https://hashtagbasketball.com/dallas-mavericks/content/luka-doncic-rookie-year-context|website=Hashtag Basketball|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* Youngest player in NBA history with 20 points, 15 rebounds and 15 assists in a game<ref>https://twitter.com/SportsCenter/status/1217681265618571265</ref>\n*Don\u010di\u0107 broke [[Jason Kidd]]'s Mavericks franchise record (21) of most triple doubles with 22 in just 122 NBA games.<ref>https://www.aa.com.tr/en/sports/luka-doncic-sets-triple-double-record-in-mavericks-win/1755424</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDon\u010di\u0107 can speak four languages: Slovenian, Serbian, English, and Spanish.<ref name=\"linked\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Michael |title=After being part of the draft's biggest splash, Luka Doncic, Trae Young now linked forever |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/part-drafts-biggest-splash-luka-doncic-trae-young-now-linked-forever-151154289.html |work=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |date=June 22, 2018}}</ref> He learned Spanish after joining Real Madrid.<ref name=\"turns18\">{{cite web |last1=Bueno |first1=Edu |title=Doncic turns 18 |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2017/02/doncic-turns-18 |publisher=[[Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, while playing at Real Madrid, Don\u010di\u0107 signed a two-year deal with [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic, de Mavericks, firma acuerdo de calzado con marca Jordan |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/basquetbol/nota/_/id/6460500/luka-doncic-de-mavericks-firma-acuerdo-de-calzado-con-marca-jordan |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=12 January 2020 |language=Spanish |date=26 December 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, it was announced that Don\u010di\u0107 had signed a multi-year endorsement deal with [[Air Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Officially Agrees To A Shoe Deal With Jordan Brand |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doylerader/2019/12/26/luka-doncic-jordan-brand-shoe-deal-official/#56e89c1f3055 |work=Forbes|accessdate=30 December 2019|first=Doyle|last=Rader|date=26 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks star Luka Doncic signs endorsement deal with Jordan Brand: Three things to know |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/mavericks-star-luka-doncic-signs-endorsement-deal-with-jordan-brand-three-things-to-know/ |website=cbssports.com |accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Sports}}\n* [[List of youngest EuroLeague players since the 2000\u201301 season|List of youngest EuroLeague players]]\n* [[List of European basketball players in the United States]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{basketballstats|nba=luka_doncic|bbr=d/doncilu01}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151215220709/http://acb.com/jugador.php?id=460 Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at acb.com {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://basketball.eurobasket.com/player/Luka-Doncic/Spain/Real_Madrid/333799 Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at eurobasket.com\n*[http://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?pcode=005929 Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at euroleague.net\n*[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/q/luka%20doncic/pid//_//players.html Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at fiba.com\n*[http://www.realmadrid.com/en/basketball/team/luka-doncic Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at realmadrid.com\n\n{{Dallas Mavericks current roster}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{2018 NBA Draft}}\n{{NBA Rookies of the Year}}\n{{Slovenia Squad EuroBasket 2017}}\n{{Real Madrid Baloncesto 2017\u201318 EuroLeague champions}}\n{{Euroleague 2010\u201320 All-Decade}}\n{{Euroleague MVP Award}}\n{{Euroleague Final Four MVP Award}}\n{{Euroleague Rising Star Award}}\n{{ACB MVP Award}}\n{{ACB Best Young Player Award}}\n{{Euroleague NGT MVP}}\n{{Slovenian Sportsman of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doncic, Luka}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Hawks draft picks]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks players]]\n[[Category:FIBA EuroBasket-winning players]]\n[[Category:Liga ACB players]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association players from Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Baloncesto players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Slovenian expatriate basketball people in Spain]]\n[[Category:Slovenian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Slovenian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Slovenian people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ljubljana]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Slovenian basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Luka Don\u010di\u0107\n| image = Luka Don\u010di\u0107 7 Real Madrid Baloncesto Euroleague 20171012.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Don\u010di\u0107 with [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] in 2017\n| number = 77\n| position = [[Guard (basketball)|Guard]] / [[Small forward]]\n| team = Dallas Mavericks\n| league = [[NBA]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 7\n| weight_lbs = 230\n| nationality = Slovenian\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1999|2|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Ljubljana]], Slovenia\n| career_start = 2015\n| career_end = \n| draft_year = 2018\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 3\n| draft_team = [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n| years1 = 2015\u20132018\n| team1 = [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2018|start}}\u2013present\n| team2 = [[Dallas Mavericks]]\n| highlights = \n* [[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|2020}})\n* [[NBA Rookie of the Year]] ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[EuroLeague 2010\u201320 All-Decade Team]] (2020)\n* [[EuroLeague]] champion ([[2017\u201318 EuroLeague|2018]])\n* [[EuroLeague MVP]] ([[2017\u201318 EuroLeague|2018]])\n* [[EuroLeague Final Four MVP]] ([[2018 EuroLeague Final Four|2018]])\n* [[All-EuroLeague Team|All-EuroLeague First Team]] ([[2017\u201318 EuroLeague|2018]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[EuroLeague Rising Star]] ([[2016\u201317 EuroLeague|2017]], [[2017\u201318 EuroLeague|2018]])\n* [[Euroscar|Euroscar Player of the Year]] (2019)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Liga ACB]] champion ([[2014\u201315 ACB season|2015]], [[2015\u201316 ACB season|2016]], [[2017\u201318 ACB season|2018]])\n* [[ACB Most Valuable Player Award|Liga ACB MVP]] ([[2017\u201318 ACB season|2018]])\n* [[All-Liga ACB Team|All-Liga ACB First Team]] ([[2017\u201318 ACB season|2018]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[ACB Best Young Player Award|ACB Best Young Player]] ([[2016\u201317 ACB season|2017]], [[2017\u201318 ACB season|2018]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[ACB Best Young Player Award|ACB All-Young Players Team]] ([[2015\u201316 ACB season|2016]]\u2013[[2017\u201318 ACB season|2018]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Spanish Basketball King's Cup|Spanish King's Cup]] winner ([[2016 Copa del Rey de Baloncesto|2016]], [[2017 Copa del Rey de Baloncesto|2017]])\n* [[Sports Illustrated Sportsperson of the Year|''Sports Illustrated''  Breakout of the Year]] (2019)\n* [[FIBA Intercontinental Cup]] champion ([[2015 FIBA Intercontinental Cup|2015]])\n* [[Euroleague Basketball Next Generation Tournament|EB Next Generation Tournament]] champion ([[2014\u201315 Euroleague Basketball Next Generation Tournament|2015]])\n* [[Euroleague Basketball Next Generation Tournament#Finals|EB Next Generation Tournament MVP]] ([[2014\u201315 Euroleague Basketball Next Generation Tournament|2015]])\n* Minicopa del Rey MVP (2013)\n| nba_profile = luka_doncic\n| bbr = doncilu01\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|SLO}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket 2017|2017 Turkey]]|}}\n}}\n'''Luka Don\u010di\u0107''' ({{IPA-sl|\u02c8l\u00f9\u02d0ka \u02c8d\u00f2\u02d0nt\u0283it\u0283|lang}}; born February 28, 1999) is a Slovenian professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Dallas Mavericks]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Slovenia national basketball team|Slovenian national team]].\n\nBorn in [[Ljubljana]], Don\u010di\u0107 shone as a youth player for [[KK Olimpija|Union Olimpija]], before joining the youth academy of the Spanish club, [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]]. He debuted for their senior team in 2015, at age 16, becoming the youngest in club history. Two years later, he led Madrid to the [[2018 EuroLeague Final Four|2018 EuroLeague title]], winning the [[EuroLeague MVP]] as well as the [[EuroLeague Final Four MVP|Final Four MVP]]. Don\u010di\u0107 was also named the [[ACB Most Valuable Player Award|ACB Most Valuable Player]], and won back-to-back [[EuroLeague Rising Star]] and [[ACB Best Young Player Award|ACB Best Young Player]] awards. He was selected to the [[EuroLeague 2010\u201320 All-Decade Team]].\n\nIn 2018, Don\u010di\u0107 declared for the [[2018 NBA draft|NBA draft]] and joined the Dallas Mavericks in the United States.{{refn|group=note|Don\u010di\u0107 was selected by the [[Atlanta Hawks]] with the 3rd pick in the 2018 NBA Draft, but was acquired by the Mavericks in a [[Trade (sports)|draft-day trade]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Amick |last=Sam |title=Mavs, Hawks trade Trae Young, Luka Doncic in draft-night deal |work=USA Today |date=June 21, 2018 |url=https://usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/draft/2018/06/21/2018-nba-draft-trae-young-luka-doncic-swapped-trade/723919002/ |accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic traded to Dallas Mavericks after Atlanta Hawks draft him with No. 3 pick in 2018 NBA Draft |publisher=CBS Sports |date=June 21, 2018 |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/luka-doncic-traded-to-dallas-mavericks-after-atlanta-hawks-draft-him-with-no-3-pick-in-2018-nba-draft/ |accessdate=October 5, 2018}}</ref>}} He was selected unanimously to the [[NBA All-Rookie Team|NBA All-Rookie First Team]] and won [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]] for the [[2018\u201319 NBA season|2018\u201319 season]]. In his sophomore season, he was selected to his first [[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]] game.\n\nA Slovenian international, Don\u010di\u0107 made his senior debut for Slovenia in 2016 at only 17 years of age; he would later be named to the [[FIBA EuroBasket All-Tournament Team#2017 EuroBasket|All-Tournament Team]] after helping his country win its first [[EuroBasket]] title in [[EuroBasket 2017|2017]].\n\n==Early life==\nDon\u010di\u0107 was born in [[Ljubljana]], Slovenia, to Mirjam Poterbin, owner of beauty salons,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stein |first1=Marc |title=Luka Doncic Is a Sore Loser. He Is Also a Sensation. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/27/sports/luka-doncic-dallas-mavericks.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=March 3, 2019 |date=February 27, 2019}}</ref> and [[Sa\u0161a Don\u010di\u0107]], a basketball coach and former basketball player.<ref name=slam/><ref name=\"enaa\">{{cite news | url= http://lifestyle.enaa.com/ljudje/nusa-senk-zmesala-kosarkarja-sasa-doncica.html | title = Nu\u0161a \u0160enk zme\u0161ala ko\u0161arkarja Sa\u0161a Don\u010di\u010da |trans-title=Nusa Senk captivated basketball player Sasa Doncic | publisher = lifestyle.enaa.com | date = September 18, 2008 | accessdate = February 2, 2017 | language = Slovenian }}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107's mother is Slovenian and his father is Slovenian of Serbian descent.<ref name=\"b92_sasa\">{{cite news | url= http://www.b92.net/sport/kosarka/vesti.php?yyyy=2017&mm=03&dd=10&nav_id=1238747 | title = Don\u010di\u0107: Luka Zvezda\u0161? Nasledio je to od mene |trans-title=Doncic: Luka a fan of Crvena Zvezda? He inherited that from me | publisher = [[B92]] | date = March 10, 2017 | accessdate = October 25, 2017 | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Staji\u0107 |first1=Sa\u0161a M. |title=Ekskluzivno, Sa\u0161a Don\u010di\u0107: Otac najve\u0107eg talenta u Evropi zna ne\u0161to \u0161to \u0107e odu\u0161eviti svakog Srbina! |url=https://www.espreso.rs/sport/eurobasket/181975/eksluzivno-sasa-doncic-otac-najveceg-talenta-u-evropi-zna-nesto-sto-ce-oduseviti-svakog-srbina-video |publisher=Espreso |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |language=Serbian |date=September 14, 2017}}</ref> His parents filed for divorce in 2008, with custody and legal guardianship being granted to his mother.<ref name=\"enaa\"/><ref name=\"ekipa1\">{{cite news | url= http://ekipa24.si/clanek/kosarka/reprezentancna-kosarka/567d5e0813259/spanski-potni-list | title = \u0160panski potni list? |trans-title=Spanish passport? |last1=Zavr\u0161nik|first1=Jurij| publisher = [[Ekipa (Slovenia)|Ekipa]] | date =December 25, 2015| accessdate =February 2, 2017| language = Slovenian }}</ref>\n\nAccording to his family, Don\u010di\u0107 first touched a basketball when he was seven months old, and by age one, he was frequently playing with a miniature hoop in his room.<ref name=slam/><ref name=schmitz/> He played a variety of sports in his childhood, including [[association football|football]], which he later quit after growing too tall.<ref name=\"motherseyes\">{{cite web |last1=Aravantinos |first1=Dionysis |title=Luka Doncic through his mother's eyes! |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/trademarks/601550/story-week-luka-doncic-mothers-eyes/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=June 6, 2018 |date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> At age seven, he began playing organized basketball at primary school in Ljubljana.<ref name=schmitz>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/20668236/there-never-nba-draft-prospect-slovenia-luka-doncic |title=There's never been an NBA draft prospect like Luka Doncic |first=Mike |last=Schmitz |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=September 18, 2017 |accessdate=September 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"borntoplay\">{{cite web|last1=West|first1=Andy|title=Conversation with Luka Doncic: 'I was born to play basketball'|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/899lwl554gpgofk6/conversation-with-luka-doncic-i-was-born-to-play-basketball|publisher=[[EuroLeague]]|accessdate=April 21, 2018|date=October 11, 2017}}</ref> His opponents at the time were up to ten years old, as Don\u010di\u0107 reflected: \"I was always training and playing with older kids who had much more experience than me. Many of them were bigger and faster than me too, so I had to beat them with my brain.\"<ref name=borntoplay/> He admired Greek basketball player [[Vassilis Spanoulis]] from his early teenage years, stating that he was \"enchanted\" by him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic: \"I got enchanted by Spanoulis\" |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/euroleague/561446/doncic-got-enchanted-spanoulis/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |date=November 25, 2017}}</ref> He wore the number 7 at Real Madrid in honor of Spanoulis.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=March 14, 2018 |title=Luka Doncic: The Future Is Now |series=The Insider EuroLeague Documentary Series  |trans-title= |medium=Video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HVIl9zTTgFA |access-date=January 3, 2019 |minutes=22 |publisher=[[EuroLeague]]}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 also grew up admiring American basketball player, [[LeBron James]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cash |first1=Meredith |title=Luka Doncic waited outside the Lakers' locker room after game for a jersey from his idol, LeBron James |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/luka-doncic-waited-postgame-for-idol-lebron-james-jersey-2018-11 |publisher=Business Insider |accessdate=16 December 2019 |date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Youth career==\n;Union Olimpija\nWhen Don\u010di\u0107 was eight, his father started playing for his hometown club [[KK Olimpija|Union Olimpija]], and Olimpija Basketball School coach Grega Brezovec invited Luka to practice with players of his age.<ref name=schmitz/><ref name=\"scottdavis\">{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=Scott|title=Potential No. 1 NBA draft pick was so good at age 8 that coaches moved him up an age group after watching him play for 16 minutes|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/luka-doncic-too-good-slovenia-team-age-8-2017-9|work=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate=April 21, 2018|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 was initially expected to practice with players his age, but only 16 minutes into his first training session, the coaching staff moved him up to the 11-year-old group. Starting in the next session, he primarily practiced with Olimpija's under-14 team, but due to league rules, he only played for the club's under-12 selection team, coming off the bench against opponents three or four years older than him.<ref name=schmitz/><ref name=borntoplay/> Despite his exclusion from under-14 games at the time, Don\u010di\u0107 often asked to attend practice, even when his coach asked him to stay home.<ref name=schmitz/>\n\nRepresenting Olimpija at the under-14 Vasas Intesa Sanpaolo Cup in [[Budapest]] in September 2011, Don\u010di\u0107 was named [[most valuable player]] (MVP) despite finishing as runners-up to [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Barcelona wins in Hungary; Doncic MVP|url=http://www.eurohopes.com/news/5575/barcelona_wins_in_hungary;_doncic_mvp|publisher=EuroHopes|accessdate=April 21, 2018|date=September 27, 2011}}</ref> In February 2012, he was [[loan (sports)|loaned]] to Spanish club [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] for the [[:es:Minicopa Endesa|Minicopa Endesa]], an under-14 Spanish club competition.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Duque|first1=Nacho|title=Luka Doncic, la perla que hace so\u00f1ar al Madrid|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/02/08/baloncesto/acb/1360337892.html|website=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|accessdate=April 21, 2018|language=Spanish|date=February 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"minicopa\">{{cite web|last1=Alcaraz|first1=Ruben|title=Doncic, new millenium [sic] is close 02/23/2012|url=http://www.eurohopes.com/news/5660/doncic,_new_millenium_is_close|publisher=EuroHopes|accessdate=April 21, 2018|date=February 23, 2012}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107, who was among the youngest players on his team, averaged 13.0 points, 4.0 rebounds, 2.8 assists and 3.3 steals per game to win tournament MVP honours, leading Real Madrid to a second-place finish.<ref name=minicopa/> In April 2012, he took part in the under-13 Lido di Roma Tournament for Olimpija, finishing as MVP and leading scorer with 34.5 points per game. In the semi-final round of the event against Victoria Fermo, he posted 29 points and 15 rebounds, and in a title-clinching win over Lazio, he erupted for 54 points, 11 rebounds, and 10 assists.<ref name=schmitz/><ref name=lido>{{cite web|title=Doncic, now in Rome (54)|url=http://www.eurohopes.com/news/5691/doncic,_now_in_rome_54|publisher=EuroHopes|accessdate=April 21, 2018|date=April 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Real Madrid\n[[File:Luka Doncic, Jorge Parra, Domagoj Proleta y Pablo Poyatos (13919153208) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Don\u010di\u0107 is interviewed after a youth game with [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] in May 2014.]]\nIn September 2012, at 13 years of age, Don\u010di\u0107 signed a five-year contract with Real Madrid, immediately standing out on the under-16 team with coach Paco Redondo.<ref name=borntoplay/><ref name=signs>{{cite web|first1=Nacho| last1 = Duque| url=http://www.marca.com/2013/02/11/baloncesto/nba/noticias/1360576177.html|title=Doncic, el prodigio de 13 a\u00f1os del Madrid|work=Marca|location=Spain|language=Spanish|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> He moved to [[Madrid]], living with football and basketball prospects.<ref name=slam/> In February 2013, Don\u010di\u0107 led Real Madrid to a Minicopa Endesa win, averaging 24.5 points, 13 rebounds, 4 assists, and 6 steals per game. In the final game of the tournament, he contributed 25 points, 16 rebounds, and 5 steals to defeat FC Barcelona and win MVP honours.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duque |first1=Nacho |title=Doncic, el prodigio de 13 a\u00f1os del Madrid: \"Cuando juego siento lo mismo que cuando sue\u00f1o\" |url=http://www.marca.com/2013/02/11/baloncesto/nba/noticias/1360576177.html |website=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |date=February 11, 2013}}</ref> In March, Don\u010di\u0107 earned MVP accolades of the under-16 Spain Championship, scoring 25 points in a championship game win over the [[CB Gran Canaria|Gran Canaria]] youth team.<ref name=\"spainchampion\">{{cite web |last1=Novillo |first1=Esteban |title=La estrellas que vienen del baloncesto espa\u00f1ol se presentan al mundo |url=http://www.marca.com/blogs/cuna-de-talentos/2013/03/28/la-estrellas-que-vienen-del-baloncesto.html |website=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |accessdate=June 9, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=March 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2014\u201315 season, Don\u010di\u0107 mainly played with Real Madrid's under-18 team and [[Real Madrid Baloncesto B|reserve team]]. With the reserve team, he averaged 13.5 points, 5.9 rebounds, and 3.1 assists, helping them win Group B of the [[2014\u201315 Liga EBA season|Liga EBA]], the [[amateur sports|amateur]] fourth-division of [[Spanish basketball league system|Spanish basketball]].<ref name=eurobasketeba>{{cite web |title=EBA 2014\u201315 Basketball |url=http://www.eurobasket.com/Spain/basketball-League-EBA_2014-2015.asp |publisher=[[Eurobasket.com]] |accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Real Madrid II |url=http://basketball.eurobasket.com/team/Spain/Real-Madrid-II/2338?Page=3&Stats=2015 |publisher=[[Eurobasket.com]] |accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref> By the end of the season, he earned all-league honourable mention accolades from the basketball website [[Eurobasket.com]].<ref name=eurobasketeba/> In January 2015, Don\u010di\u0107 won the under-18 [[2014\u201315 Euroleague Basketball Next Generation Tournament#Torneig de B\u00e0squet Junior Ciutat de L'Hospitalet|Ciutat de L'Hospitalet Tournament]] and was selected to the All-Tournament Team, despite being two years younger than the rest of the team.<ref name=\"FIBA Article\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.com/news/slovenian-luka-doncic-already-a-big-name-at-just-16|title=Slovenian Luka Doncic already a big name at just 16|date=April 23, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2018|publisher=FIBA|last=Hein|first=David}}</ref> At the event, on January 6, against the youth team of his former club Union Olimpija, he posted a [[double (basketball)|double-double]] of 13 points, 13 rebounds, 4 assists, and 4 steals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jan 6, 2015: Union Olimpija Junior Team vs. Real Madrid Junior Team |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/international/boxscore/2015-01-06/Union-Olimpija-Junior-Team-at-Real-Madrid-Junior-Team/205522 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> In May 2015, he also won the under-18 [[2014\u201315 Euroleague Basketball Next Generation Tournament|Next Generation Tournament]], for which he was selected MVP after helping defeat defending champions [[KK Crvena zvezda (youth)|Crvena zvezda Belgrade]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adidasngt.com/u18/news/latest/i/5yliexchngndhh9q/real-madrid-s-young-star-doncic-named-angt-mvp|title=Real Madrid's young star Doncic named ANGT MVP|publisher=AdidasNGT|date=May 17, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Real Madrid===\n====Early years (2015\u201316)====\nOn April 30, 2015, Don\u010di\u0107 made his professional debut for Real Madrid in the [[Liga ACB]] against [[Baloncesto M\u00e1laga|Unicaja]], making his only three-point attempt in under 2 minutes of playing time.<ref name=\"youngestplayer\">{{cite web |title=Doncic, youngest player to make debut for Real Madrid |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2015/04/doncic-youngest-player-to-make-debut-for-real-madrid |publisher=[[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |date=April 30, 2015}}</ref> At 16 years, 2 months, and 2 days of age, he became the youngest player to ever play for Real Madrid in the ACB and the third-youngest debutant in league history, behind only [[Ricky Rubio]] and \u00c1ngel Rebolo.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic, el m\u00e1s joven en debutar con el Real Madrid |url=https://as.com/baloncesto/2015/04/30/acb/1430427303_369647.html |website=[[Diario AS]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=May 1, 2015}}</ref> He played 5 games in the [[2014\u201315 ACB season]], averaging 1.6 points and 1.2 rebounds in 4.8 minutes per game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Game Logs |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Luka-Doncic/GameLogs/54148/International/2015/4 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2015\u201316 season, Don\u010di\u0107 became a regular member of Real Madrid's senior team. He played against the [[Boston Celtics]] in an NBA preseason game on October 8, 2015, collecting 4 rebounds, 1 assist, and 1 block.<ref name=\"prince\">{{cite web |last1=Pick |first1=David |title=All Hail Luka Doncic, Europe's 16-Year-Old Hoops Prince |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2588799-all-hail-luca-doncic-europes-16-year-old-hoops-prince |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |date=November 13, 2015}}</ref> On October 16, at age 16, he debuted in the EuroLeague, scoring 2 points in a loss to [[BC Khimki|Khimki]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=D\u00edaz |first1=Nacho |title=84\u201370: Real Madrid lose to Khimki in Euroleague opener |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2015/10/84-70-real-madrid-lose-to-khimki-in-euroleague-opener |publisher=[[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |date=October 16, 2015}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 became the 21st player ever to debut in the EuroLeague before turning 17.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hein |first1=David |title=Cedevita's U16 hero Musa makes his mark in Euroleague with historic debut |url=http://www.heinnews.com/basketball/nba/cedevitas-u16-hero-musa-makes-his-mark-in-euroleague-with-historic-debut/ |publisher=heinnews |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> On October 18, he recorded 10 points and 4 rebounds in a 94\u201361 win over [[San Sebasti\u00e1n Gipuzkoa BC|Gipuzkoa]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Oct 18, 2015 \u2013 Real Madrid 94, Delteco GBC 61 |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/international/boxscore/2015-10-18/Real-Madrid-at-Delteco-GBC/223275 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |date=October 18, 2015}}</ref> On November 29, Don\u010di\u0107 posted a season-high 15 points, 6 rebounds, and 4 assists against [[Bilbao Basket|Bilbao]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reyes |first1=Luis Alberto |title=Doncic reclama su sitio (92\u201399) |url=http://www.24segundosenblanco.es/2015/11/doncic-reclama-su-sitio-92-99/ |publisher=24segundosenblanco |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=November 29, 2015}}</ref> With the performance, he set a new ACB record for most points and highest [[Performance Index Rating]] (PIR) in a game for players under age 17.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic's highlights against Valencia |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/acb/322938/luka-doncics-highlights-valencia/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 16, 2018 |date=October 7, 2016}}</ref> He scored 12 points and grabbed 5 rebounds on January 7, 2016, against [[PBC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] in the EuroLeague.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Magnotti |first1=Trevor |title=Luka Doncic is the truth |url=https://fansided.com/2016/12/08/luka-doncic-european-2018-nba-draft/ |publisher=[[FanSided]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018 |date=December 8, 2016}}</ref> After a Real Madrid [[Time-out (sport)|time-out]] in the second quarter of the game, Don\u010di\u0107 made three consecutive three-pointers, recording 9 points in a 2-minute span.<ref>{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Andy |title=Luka Doncic showing enormous potential |url=https://sport360.com/article/other/us-sports/166569/inside-story-real-madrids-basketball-boy-wonder-luka-doncic-showing-enormous-potential |publisher=Sport360 |date=January 3, 2016 |accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref> Through 39 games in the [[2015\u201316 ACB season]], he averaged 4.5 points, 2.6 rebounds, and 1.7 assists.<ref name=realgm>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Player Profile |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Luka-Doncic/Summary/54148 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref> In 12 EuroLeague games, he recorded 3.5 points, 2.3 rebounds, and 2 assists per game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Game Logs |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/player/Luka-Doncic/GameLogs/54148/International/2016/1 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Rise to prominence (2016\u201317)====\n[[File:Luka Don\u010di\u0107.jpg|thumb|Don\u010di\u0107 shoots a free throw for Real Madrid in January 2017.]]\nDon\u010di\u0107 made his 2016\u201317 season debut on September 30, 2016, against Unicaja, recording 6 points and 4 assists in 19 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sep 30, 2016 \u2013 Unicaja 90, Real Madrid 101 |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/international/boxscore/2016-09-30/Unicaja-Malaga-at-Real-Madrid/242351 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018 |date=September 30, 2016}}</ref> He collected 3 points, 5 rebounds, and 4 assists in an NBA preseason win on October 3, 2016 over the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Thunder vs. Real Madrid \u2013 Box Score |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=400897113 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date=October 3, 2016}}</ref> On December 4, he posted a double-double of 23 points and 11 assists, both season-highs, in a 92\u201376 win over [[Baloncesto Fuenlabrada|Montakit Fuenlabrada]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=D\u00edaz |first1=Nacho |title=92\u201376: Doncic sensational against Montakit Fuenlabrada |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2016/12/92-76-doncic-sensational-against-montakit-fuenlabrada |publisher=[[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018 |date=December 4, 2016}}</ref> The game earned him his first ACB player of the week honors.<ref name=\"mvpweek\">{{cite web |last1=Stroggylakis |first1=Antonis |title=Luka Doncic is MVP of the Week in Spain |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/acb/430794/luka-doncic-mvp-week-spain/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 16, 2018 |date=April 9, 2017}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 scored a team-high 17 points in a EuroLeague victory over [[BC \u017dalgiris|\u017dalgiris Kaunas]] on December 8, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic da la victoria al Real Madrid en el \u00faltimo minuto |url=http://www.rtve.es/deportes/20161208/doncic-da-victoria-real-madrid-ultimo-minuto/1451707.shtml |publisher=[[RTVE]] |accessdate=October 16, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=December 8, 2016}}</ref> After recording 16 points, 6 rebounds, 5 assists, and 3 steals in a 95\u201372 win over [[Brose Bamberg]] on December 22, he was named [[EuroLeague MVP of the Round|MVP of the Round]] in the EuroLeague, becoming the youngest player to ever do so.<ref>{{cite web |title=Round 13 Co-MVPs: Luka Doncic and Mike James |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/7hnibo6ccfhnk7k9/round-13-co-mvps-luka-doncic-and-mike-james |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018 |date=December 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"unanimous\">{{cite web |title=Rising Star Trophy: Madrid's Doncic is unanimous winner |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/7ssonijxmjl9vexx |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 18, 2018 |date=May 10, 2017}}</ref> He earned the same honor on January 14, 2017, after posting 10 points, 11 rebounds, and 8 assists to help beat [[Maccabi Tel Aviv B.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Regular Season Round 17 MVP: Luka Doncic, Real Madrid |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/7ji5ruia83h9ucp3/regular-season-round-17-mvp-luka-doncic-real-madrid |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018 |date=January 14, 2017}}</ref> On February 9, Don\u010di\u0107 recorded 5 points, 7 rebounds, and 11 assists to defeat [[BC UNICS|UNICS Kazan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Maestro Doncic, road victory for Real Madrid over Unics Kazan |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/euroleague/398283/maestro-doncic-road-victory-real-madrid-unics-kazan/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 18, 2018 |date=February 9, 2017}}</ref> He scored a season-high 23 points on February 18, in the [[2017 Copa del Rey de Baloncesto|Spanish King's Cup]] versus [[Saski Baskonia|Baskonia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Baskonia 99, Real Madrid 103 |url=http://www.acb.com/fichas/CREY81005.php |publisher=[[Liga ACB]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=February 18, 2017}}</ref> After scoring 13 points and grabbing 8 rebounds in the [[2017 EuroLeague Playoffs]] against [[Dar\u00fc\u015f\u015fafaka S.K.|Dar\u00fc\u015f\u015fafaka]] on April 26, he shared MVP of the Round accolades with two other players.<ref>{{cite web |title=Playoffs Game 3 tri-MVPs: Dunston, Ayon and Doncic |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/7rrdm98plh6lm8bt |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 18, 2018 |date=April 27, 2017}}</ref> Two days later, he won the award outright, posting 11 points, 5 rebounds, and 7 assists to lead Real Madrid to a [[2017 EuroLeague Final Four|EuroLeague Final Four]] berth.<ref>{{cite web |title=Playoffs Game 4 MVP: Luka Doncic, Real Madrid |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/7rwjsoenryho3niw |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 18, 2018 |date=April 29, 2017}}</ref> Through 42 ACB games in the season, Don\u010di\u0107 averaged 7.5 points, 4.4 rebounds, and 3 assists, and through 35 EuroLeague contests, he averaged 7.8 points, 4.5 rebounds, and 4.2 assists per game.<ref name=realgm/> He was named [[EuroLeague Rising Star]] by unanimous vote and also claimed the [[ACB Best Young Player Award]].<ref name=unanimous/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Blum |first1=Matt |title=Meet Luka Doncic: The Next Great European Prospect |url=http://thesportsquotient.com/nba/2017/9/21/meet-luka-doncic-the-next-great-european-prospect |publisher=The Sports Quotient |accessdate=October 18, 2018 |date=September 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019041023/http://thesportsquotient.com/nba/2017/9/21/meet-luka-doncic-the-next-great-european-prospect |archive-date=October 19, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====MVP season (2017\u201318)====\nDon\u010di\u0107 assumed a greater role for Real Madrid entering the 2017\u201318 season, after the team's star player [[Sergio Llull]] suffered a [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|torn ACL]] during [[EuroBasket 2017]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kalbrosky |first1=Bryan |title=Top NBA prospect Luka Doncic to see bigger role after Rockets' draftee Sergio Llull is injured |url=https://hoopshype.com/2017/08/10/top-nba-prospect-luka-doncic-to-see-bigger-role-after-rockets-draftee-sergio-llull-is-injured/ |publisher=HoopsHype |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=August 10, 2017}}</ref> In his season debut on October 1, 2017, he recorded 8 points, 6 rebounds, and 4 assists in a 94\u201388 victory over [[BC Andorra|MoraBanc Andorra]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Oct 1, 2017 \u2013 MoraBanc Andorra 88, Real Madrid 94 |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/international/boxscore/2017-10-01/MoraBanc-Andorra-at-Real-Madrid/273185 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=October 1, 2017}}</ref> In his first EuroLeague game of the season, on October 12, Don\u010di\u0107 scored a career-high 27 points to help defeat [[Anadolu Efes S.K.|Anadolu Efes]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic nets his highest points total with Real Madrid |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2017/10/doncic-nets-his-highest-points-total-with-real-madrid |publisher=[[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=October 12, 2017}}</ref> In his next game, he nearly recorded a triple-double against [[Valencia Basket|Valencia]], with 16 points, 10 assists, and 7 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic's near triple-double performance vs Valencia |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/acb/534210/doncics-near-triple-double-performance-vs-valencia/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=October 16, 2017}}</ref> On October 24, Don\u010di\u0107 was named EuroLeague MVP of the Round after erupting for 27 points, 8 rebounds, 5 assists, and 3 steals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Round 3 MVP: Luka Doncic, Real Madrid |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/8aga66tcihey9cqq/round-3-mvp-luka-doncic-real-madrid |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=October 26, 2017}}</ref> He was named MVP of the Round again two days later, eclipsing his career-best with 28 points in an 87\u201366 win over \u017dalgiris Kaunas. Don\u010di\u0107 also grabbed 9 rebounds and had 4 assists in the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Round 4 MVP: Luka Doncic, Real Madrid |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/8al85pqyvecsiwi3 |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> At the end of October, he earned [[EuroLeague MVP of the Month]] honors, becoming the youngest player to ever win the award.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkish Airlines EuroLeague MVP for October: Luka Doncic, Real Madrid |url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/8aqi43ypxb5l69kn/turkish-airlines-euroleague-mvp-for-october-luka-doncic-real-madrid |publisher=[[EuroLeague]] |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=October 30, 2017}}</ref> On December 8, he set a career-high in scoring, with 33 points, 6 rebounds, and 4 assists against [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos Piraeus]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stroggilakis |first1=Antonis |title=Doncic: \"\u0399 don\u2019t care for my career high because we lost\" |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/euroleague/570196/doncic-dont-care-career-high-lost/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 19, 2018 |date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 led Real Madrid to a 79\u201377 victory over defending EuroLeague champion [[Fenerbah\u00e7e Basketball|Fenerbah\u00e7e Do\u011fu\u015f]] on December 28, contributing 20 points, 10 assists, and 8 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic flirts with triple-double, Real beats the champs |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/euroleague/583905/doncic-flirts-triple-double-real-beats-champs/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Following a 24-point outburst in 22 minutes versus [[CB Estudiantes|Movistar Estudiantes]] on December 31, he was selected as Player of the Round in the ACB.<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic, player of round 14 in the Endesa League |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2017/12/doncic-player-of-round-14-in-the-endesa-league |publisher=[[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> He was later named ACB Player of the Month for December, becoming the award's youngest recipient ever.<ref>{{cite news|title=Luka Doncic, MVP Movistar de Diciembre|url=http://www.acb.com/redaccion.php?id=137417|accessdate=January 1, 2018|work=acb.com|date=January 1, 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 160\n| image1 = Luka Don\u010di\u0107 7 Real Madrid Baloncesto Euroleague 20171012 (2).jpg\n| width1 = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 =\n| image3 = Josh Adams 14 Anadolu Efes Euroleague 20171012 (2).jpg\n| width3 =\n| alt3 = \n| caption3 =\n| header = Don\u010di\u0107 versus [[Anadolu Efes S.K.|Anadolu Efes]] in 2017\n| header_align = <!-- left/right/center -->\n| header_background = \n| footer = (left) with Real Madrid; (right) guarded by [[Josh Adams (basketball)|Josh Adams]]\n| footer_align = <!-- left/right/center -->\n| footer_background = \n| background color = \n}}\nOn February 9, 2018, Don\u010di\u0107 led his team with 27 points in a losing effort to Olympiacos, 80\u201379.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bueno |first1=Edu |title=79\u201380: Madrid had the last play to down Olympiacos |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2018/02/79-80-madrid-had-the-last-play-to-down-olympiacos |publisher=[[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> He had another strong performance on February 17, versus [[CB 1939 Canarias|Iberostar Tenerife]] in the [[2018 Copa del Rey de Baloncesto|2018 Spanish King's Cup]], posting 17 points, 7 rebounds, 5 assists, and 4 steals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Feb 17, 2018 \u2013 Real Madrid 77, Iberostar Tenerife 59 |url=https://basketball.realgm.com/international/boxscore/2018-02-17/Real-Madrid-at-Iberostar-Tenerife/298045 |publisher=[[RealGM]] |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |date=February 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Garc\u00eda |first1=Dioni |title=Doncic conduce al Madrid a la final de Copa |url=https://www.laopiniondemurcia.es/deportes/2018/02/17/iberostar-tenerife-real-madrid-directo/898962.html |website=La Opini\u00f3n de Murcia |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |language=Spanish |date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> On March 30, 2018, Don\u010di\u0107 scored 24 points, grabbed 9 rebounds, and made a game-winning three-pointer with under a second left in regulation to beat Crvena zvezda Belgrade, 82\u201379.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gartland |first1=Dan |title=Potential No. 1 Draft Pick Luka Doncic Hits Ankle-Breaking Step-Back Buzzer-Beater |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2018/03/30/luka-doncic-real-madrid-nba-draft-prospect-buzzer-beater-video |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> On May 9, he recorded 17 points, 10 rebounds, and 10 assists in 22 minutes against [[CB Sevilla|Real Betis Energ\u00eda Plus]], for the first triple-double in the ACB since the [[2006\u201307 ACB season|2006\u201307 season]] and the seventh in league history.<ref name=\"tripledouble\">{{cite web |last1=Stroggylakis |first1=Antonis |title=Luka Doncic notches first career triple-double |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/acb/672135/luka-doncic-notches-first-career-triple-double/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 22, 2018 |date=May 9, 2018}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 finished with 16 points, 7 rebounds, and 2 assists on May 18, in a 92\u201383 win over CSKA Moscow in the EuroLeague semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2018/5/18/17369976/luka-doncic-stats-euroleague-final-four-pick-draft|title=Luka Doncic looks like a No. 1 pick in EuroLeague semi-final win|last=Ellentuck|first=Matt|publisher=SB Nation|date=May 18, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> On May 20, he guided Real Madrid to a [[2018 EuroLeague Final Four|EuroLeague finals]] victory over Fenerbah\u00e7e Do\u011fu\u015f.<ref name=\"EuroLeague18Champ\">{{cite news|title=Real Madrid is 2018 EuroLeague champion|url=http://www.euroleague.net/main/results/showgame?gamecode=260&seasoncode=E2017#!report|accessdate=May 20, 2018|work=euroleague.net|date=May 20, 2018}}</ref> He was subsequently named [[EuroLeague Final Four MVP]] after scoring 15 points.<ref name=\"EuroLeagueMVPF4\">{{cite news|title=Doncic chosen Final Four MVP|url=http://www.euroleague.net/final-four/belgrade-2018/news/i/8r3oqram9e8uuqvt/doncic-chosen-final-four-mvp|accessdate=May 20, 2018|work=euroleague.net|date=May 20, 2018}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 won the [[EuroLeague MVP]] award, being its youngest winner, after averaging 16 points, 4.9 rebounds, and 4.3 assists per game over 33 EuroLeague games and leading the league in PIR.<ref name=\"EuroLeague2018MVP\">{{cite news|title=2017\u201318 Turkish Airlines EuroLeague MVP: Luka Doncic, Real Madrid|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/8qwovagussoccaq6|work=[[EuroLeague]]|date=May 19, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> He also repeated as the EuroLeague Rising Star, becoming the third back-to-back winner of the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/8q3k4gyd7iac7dnc/2017-18-turkish-airlines-euroleague-rising-star-luka-doncic-real-madrid|title=2017\u201318 Turkish Airlines EuroLeague Rising Star: Luka Doncic, Real Madrid C.F.|work=Euroleague.net|accessdate= May 8, 2018}}</ref> In addition, Don\u010di\u0107 earned the ACB Best Young Player and [[ACB Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] accolades, after helping his team defeat Kirolbet Baskonia in the [[2018 ACB Playoffs#Finals|league finals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Luka Doncic, MVP Movistar de la Liga Endesa 2017\u201318|url=http://www.acb.com/redaccion.php?id=140829|accessdate=May 26, 2018|work=ACB.com|date=May 24, 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref> On June 29, 2018, he parted ways with Real Madrid.<ref>{{cite news |title=Doncic: the kid who became a star at Real Madrid |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2018/06/doncic-the-kid-who-became-a-star-at-real-madrid |work=Real Madrid C.F. \u2013 Web Oficial |date=June 29, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Luka Doncic's farewell letter: two dreams  |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2018/06/luka-doncics-farewell-letter-two-dreams |accessdate=June 30, 2018 |work=Real Madrid C.F. \u2013 Web Oficial |date=June 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== EuroLeague 2010\u201320 All-Decade Team ===\nIn November 2019, Don\u010di\u0107 was nominated to the [[EuroLeague Basketball 2010\u201320 All-Decade Team|EuroLeague 2010\u201320 All-Decade Team]].<ref>{{cite web |title=All-Decade Nominee: Luka Doncic |url=https://www.euroleague.net/news/i/a7nfxe77oaifqhse/all-decade-nominee-luka-doncic |website=euroleague.net |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> On March 2020, he was selected to the 2010\u201320 All-Decade Team.<ref>{{cite web |title=2010-20 All-Decade Team: Luka Doncic |url=https://www.euroleague.net/news/i/aha8l4exn7k7tka6/2010-20-all-decade-team-luka-doncic |website=euroleague.net |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=NBA star Don\u010di\u0107 makes it into EuroLeague all-decade team |url=http://www.sloveniatimes.com/nba-star-doncic-makes-it-into-euroleague-all-decade-team |website=sloveniatimes.com |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Dallas Mavericks===\n====Rookie season (2018\u201319)====\nOn June 21, 2018, Don\u010di\u0107 was selected with the third overall pick by the [[Atlanta Hawks]] in the [[2018 NBA draft]]. He was then traded to the [[Dallas Mavericks]] in exchange for the draft rights to [[Trae Young]] and a protected future first round pick in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/23867178/2018-nba-draft-dallas-mavericks-acquire-luke-doncic-send-draft-rights-trae-young-atlanta-hawks|title=Luka Doncic headed to Mavs, Trae Young to Hawks after teams swap picks|date= June 21, 2018|access-date=June 21, 2018|publisher=ESPN|last=MacMahon|first=Tim}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-acquire-draft-rights-to-third-overall-pick-luka-doncic/|title=Mavericks acquire draft rights to third-overall pick Luka Doncic|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=June 21, 2018|publisher=[[Dallas Mavericks]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708143351/https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-acquire-draft-rights-to-third-overall-pick-luka-doncic/|archive-date=July 8, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> After the draft, Mavericks head coach [[Rick Carlisle]] said, \"At one point, we thought there might be a slight chance Don\u010di\u0107 could fall to us, but a couple of days ago it was pretty clear that there was no way that was going to happen. He's just too good. We get a guy we think is franchise foundation piece.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zillgitt |first1=Jeff |title=Mavericks believe European sensation Luka Doncic can be a cornerstone like Dirk Nowitzki |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/2018/06/22/mavericks-luka-doncic-dirk-nowitzki-cornerstone/726564002/ |website=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=June 25, 2018 |date=June 22, 2018}}</ref> He signed his rookie contract with the Mavericks on July 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mavericks sign third overall pick Luka Doncic|url=https://www.mavs.com/mavericks-sign-third-overall-pick-luka-doncic/|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=July 9, 2018}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 did not play at the [[2018 NBA Summer League]] due to his late buyout from Real Madrid.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Price |first1=David |title=Mavs did the right thing in not allowing Luka Doncic to play summer league ball |url=https://www.mavs.com/mavs-did-the-right-thing-in-not-allowing-luka-doncic-to-play-summer-league-ball/ |publisher=National Basketball Association |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |date=July 12, 2018}}</ref> Before the [[2018\u201319 NBA season|2018\u201319 season]], [[ESPN]] considered him to be the favorite to win the [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Summer Forecast: 2018\u201319 NBA Rookie of the Year |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/24245975/nba-rookie-year-predictions-espn-summer-forecast |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=September 30, 2018 |date=August 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDon\u010di\u0107 made his regular season debut on October 17, 2018, recording 10 points, 8 rebounds and 4 assists, in a 121\u2013100 loss to the [[Phoenix Suns]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=401070216|title=Booker's late onslaught lifts Suns past Mavs 121\u2013100|publisher=National Basketball Association|date=October 17, 2018|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> On October 20, Don\u010di\u0107 recorded 26 points and 6 rebounds in a 140\u2013136 win over the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacMahon |first1=Tim |title=Dennis Smith and Luka Doncic show Dallas a sign of the future |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/25039525/dennis-smith-jr-luka-doncic-show-dallas-mavericks-sign-future-minnesota-timberwolves-nba |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |date=October 21, 2018}}</ref> He became the youngest 20-point scorer in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Karalla |first1=Bobby |title=The Fast Break: Mavs vs. Wolves |url=https://www.mavs.com/the-fast-break-mavs-vs-wolves/ |publisher=[[Dallas Mavericks]] |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |date=October 21, 2018}}</ref> On October 29, Don\u010di\u0107 posted 31 points and 8 rebounds in a 113\u2013108 loss to the [[San Antonio Spurs]], for his first 30-point game in the NBA.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks' Luka Doncic: Explodes for 31 points in OT loss |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/basketball/news/mavericks-luka-doncic-explodes-for-31-points-in-ot-loss/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |date=October 30, 2018}}</ref> He recorded his first NBA double-double on November 19, with 15 points and 10 rebounds in a 98\u201388 loss to the [[Memphis Grizzlies]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks' Luka Doncic: Has double-double in loss |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/basketball/news/mavericks-luka-doncic-has-double-double-in-loss/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=December 3, 2018 |date=November 19, 2018}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 was named [[NBA Rookie of the Month Award|NBA Rookie of the Month]] in the [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] for November 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mavs' Luka Doncic named Western Conference Rookie of the Month |url=https://sportsday.dallasnews.com/dallas-mavericks/mavericks/2018/12/03/mavs-luka-doncic-named-western-conference-rookie-month |website=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=December 3, 2018 |date=December 3, 2018}}</ref> On December 8, Don\u010di\u0107 scored 21 points in a 107\u2013104 win over the [[Houston Rockets]]. After initial struggles, he produced a personal 11\u20130 run in the final minutes of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nathan |first1=Alec |title=Luka Doncic Goes on Dazzling 11\u20130 Run by Himself, Drops 21 in Win vs. Rockets |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2809913-luka-doncic-goes-on-dazzling-11-0-run-by-himself-drops-21-in-win-vs-rockets |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |accessdate=December 9, 2018 |date=December 9, 2018}}</ref> On December 28, Don\u010di\u0107 scored 34 points and became the youngest NBA player to make 7 three-pointers in a game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic drops 34 in loss to Pelicans |url=http://www.espn.com/video/clip?id=25635853&ex_cid=espnapi_public |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 1, 2019 |date=December 28, 2018}}</ref> He was named Western Conference Rookie of the Month for December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doncic wins monthly honor, and would be an All-Star starter if the voting ended today|url=https://www.mavs.com/doncic-named-western-conference-rookie-of-the-month-for-the-second-month-in-a-row/|website=Mavs.com|accessdate=January 3, 2019|date=January 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104175558/https://www.mavs.com/doncic-named-western-conference-rookie-of-the-month-for-the-second-month-in-a-row/|archive-date=January 4, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> On January 21, Don\u010di\u0107 recorded his first NBA triple-double with 18 points, 11 rebounds and 10 assists in a 116\u2013106 loss to the [[Milwaukee Bucks]], which made him the second-youngest player in NBA history to accomplish the feat at 19 years and 327 days old, behind only [[Markelle Fultz]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks' Luka Doncic: Posts first career triple-double |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/basketball/news/mavericks-luka-doncic-posts-first-career-triple-double/ |website=cbssports.com |accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks' Luka Doncic Becomes 2nd-Youngest NBA Player to Record Triple-Double |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2816923-mavericks-luka-doncic-becomes-2nd-youngest-nba-player-to-record-triple-double |website=bleacherreport.com |accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> On January 27, Don\u010di\u0107 scored a season-high 35 points and recorded his second NBA triple-double adding 12 rebounds and 10 assists in a 123\u2013120 loss to the [[Toronto Raptors]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Becomes First Teenager in NBA History to Record 30-Point Triple Double |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2019/01/27/Luka-Doncic-first-teen-30-point-triple-double-raptors-mavericks |website=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> He became the first teenager in NBA history with a 30-point triple-double and with multiple triple-doubles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic scores 35, is first teen with 30-point triple-double |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/25866566/luka-doncic-scores-35-first-teen-30-point-triple-double |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic becomes first NBA player with multiple triple-doubles as teenager |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/doncic-becomes-first-nba-player-042815711.html?guccounter=1 |publisher=Yahoo! |accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref> Two days later, Don\u010di\u0107 was named a confirmed participant for the World Team in the [[2019 NBA All-Star Game|2019]] [[Rising Stars Challenge]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Doncic, Simmons headline Mtn Dew Ice Rising Stars rosters |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/01/29/2019-mtn-dew-ice-rising-stars-roster-official-release |publisher=National Basketball Association |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> Despite being second in fan voting, behind only [[LeBron James]], and ranked 8th in total voting score, Don\u010di\u0107 wasn't selected for the Western Conference All-Stars in the [[2019 NBA All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite web |title=NBA All-Star Game 2019: LeBron, Giannis, Luka Doncic Lead 3rd Voting Results |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2816254-nba-all-star-game-2019-lebron-giannis-luka-doncic-lead-3rd-voting-results |website=bleacherreport.com |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mavs rookie Luka Doncic not named an NBA All-Star starter |url=https://247sports.com/nba/mavericks/Article/Despite-being-2nd-in-West-fan-voting-Mavs-Luka-Doncic-misses-being-an-All-Star-starter-by-narrow-margin-128260735/ |website=247sports.com |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=@JoshEberley on Western Conference Voting Results |url=https://twitter.com/JoshEberley/status/1088592344952201216/photo/1 |publisher=Twitter |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic fails to make the 2019 All-Star game |url=https://www.mavsmoneyball.com/2019/1/31/18206145/luka-doncic-not-voted-to-all-star-game |website=mavsmoneyball.com |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, Don\u010di\u0107 recorded his third triple-double with 19 points, 10 rebounds and 11 assists in a 99\u201393 win over the [[Charlotte Hornets]], which made him the youngest player in NBA history to record three triple-doubles.<ref>{{cite web |title=NBA: Doncic nets triple-double in Mavs' win over Hornets |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/02/07/19/nba-doncic-nets-triple-double-in-mavs-win-over-hornets |website=news.abs-cbn.com |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> He edges [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Hall of Famer]] [[Magic Johnson]] by 117 days.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic picks up third triple-double in his last seven games |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/luka-doncic-picks-third-triple-double-last-seven-games-060955785.html?guccounter=1 |publisher=Yahoo! |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> On February 25, Don\u010di\u0107 recorded his fourth triple-double with 28 points, 10 rebounds and 10 assists in a 121\u2013112 loss to the [[Los Angeles Clippers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic has his 4th triple-double in loss to Clippers |url=https://www.foxsports.com/southwest/story/luka-doncic-has-his-4th-triple-double-in-loss-to-clippers-022619 |publisher=Fox Sports |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 has four of the five triple-doubles recorded by teenagers in NBA history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic has 4 of the 5 triple-doubles recorded by teenagers in NBA history |url=https://clutchpoints.com/mavs-news-luka-doncic-has-4-of-the-5-triple-doubles-recorded-by-teenagers-in-nba-history/ |website=clutchpoints.com |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 was named Western Conference Rookie of the Month for January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Luka Doncic wins his fourth straight Rookie of the Month award|url=https://www.mavs.com/luka-doncic-wins-his-fourth-straight-rookie-of-the-month-award/|website=Mavs.com|accessdate=March 1, 2019}}</ref> His eight triple-doubles ranked fourth on the season behind [[Russell Westbrook]] (34), [[Nikola Joki\u0107]] (12) and [[Ben Simmons]] (10), as well as tied with LeBron James.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stats: Players General Traditional |url=https://stats.nba.com/players/traditional/?sort=TD3&dir=-1&Season=2018-19&SeasonType=Regular%20Season |publisher=National Basketball Association |accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 became just the fifth player in NBA history to average at least 20 points, 5 rebounds and 5 assists in his rookie year, joining [[Oscar Robertson]] ([[1960\u201361 NBA season|1960\u201361]]), [[Michael Jordan]] ([[1984\u201385 NBA season|1984\u201385]]), LeBron James ([[2003\u201304 NBA season|2003\u201304]]), and [[Tyreke Evans]] ([[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic: A Rookie Year in Context|url=https://hashtagbasketball.com/dallas-mavericks/content/luka-doncic-rookie-year-context|website=Hashtag Basketball|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref> In May, Don\u010di\u0107 was selected unanimously to the [[NBA All-Rookie Team|All-Rookie First Team]], and in June he received the [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Young, Doncic lead 2018\u201319 All-Rookie First Team |url=https://www.nba.com/2018-19-all-rookie-teams-official-release |publisher=National Basketball Association |accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Wins 2019 NBA Rookie of the Year over Trae Young, DeAndre Ayton |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2832020-luka-doncic-wins-2019-nba-rookie-of-the-year-over-trae-young-deandre-ayton |website=bleacherreport.com}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 became the second European player, after [[Pau Gasol]], who won the award and the sixth overall winner not born in the United States.\n\n====First All-Star selection (2019\u201320)====\nDon\u010di\u0107 made his first triple-double of the season on October 25, 2019, posting 25 points, 10 rebounds, and 10 assists to help the Mavericks defeat the [[New Orleans Pelicans]], 123\u2013116.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dallas Mavericks: Luka Doncic has ninth triple-double in win over Pelicans |url=https://thesmokingcuban.com/2019/10/26/dallas-mavericks-2019-luka-doncic-game-2-pelicans/ |website=thesmokingcuban.com |accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref> In two consecutive games, on November 1-3, he not only recorded two triple-doubles but matched a career-high 15 assists in both games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic posts record 31/15/13 triple-double vs. Lakers |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/nba-news/960054/luka-doncic-posts-record-31-15-13-triple-double-vs-lakers/ |website=eurohoops.net |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Six stats to know from Luka Doncic's historic triple-double against the Cleveland Cavaliers |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/au/nba/news/six-stats-to-know-from-luka-doncics-historic-triple-double-against-the-cleveland-cavaliers/5xm41suon1x91nfxcx1ny2y91 |website=sportingnews.com |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> On November 8, Don\u010di\u0107 scored a career-high 38 points and recorded his twelfth NBA triple-double by adding 14 rebounds and 10 assists during a 106\u2013102 loss to the [[New York Knicks]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic thrives with triple-double and career high |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/nba-news/963970/luka-doncic-thrives-with-triple-double-and-career-high/ |website=eurohoops.net |accessdate=November 15, 2019}}</ref> Ten days later, in a 117\u2013110 win over the [[San Antonio Spurs]], Don\u010di\u0107 recorded a career-high 42 points and his sixth triple-double of the season by adding 11 rebounds and 12 assists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic becomes 2nd youngest to post 40-point triple-double |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/11/18/luka-doncic-2nd-youngest-post-40-point-triple-double |website=nba.com |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> He made NBA history in a 142\u201394 win over the [[Golden State Warriors]] on November 20 when he posted 35 points, 10 rebounds, and 11 assists; thus becoming the youngest player to have 35-point triple-doubles in succession, breaking [[Oscar Robertson]]'s record, and only the fourth player to record it since the 1983\u201384 season, joining [[Michael Jordan]], [[James Harden]], and [[Russell Westbrook]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic dominates for yet another monster triple-double |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/11/20/luka-doncic-dominates-warriors-latest-monster-triple-double |website=nba.com |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks' Luka Doncic posts 35-point triple-double in 25 minutes |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28126914/mavericks-luka-doncic-posts-35-point-triple-double-25-minutes |website=espn.com |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref> In November, Don\u010di\u0107 was named the NBA Western Conference [[2019\u201320 NBA season#Players of the Week|Player of the Week]] for Week 5 (November 18\u201324); which was his first NBA Player of the Week award.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic, Spencer Dinwiddie named NBA Players of the Week |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/11/25/nba-players-week-5-spencer-dinwiddie-luka-doncic |website=nba.com |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic earns first career Player of the Week award |url=https://www.mavs.com/luka-doncic-earns-first-career-player-of-the-week-award/ |website=mavs.com |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> On 3 December, he won his first NBA Player of the Month award when he was named the NBA Western Conference [[2019\u201320 NBA season#Players of the Month|Player of the Month]] for October and November; becoming the youngest Western Conference Player of the Month winner since the league began issuing the award by conference in the 2001\u201302 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Named Western Conference Player of the Month |url=https://www.foxsports.com/southwest/story/luka-doncic-named-western-conference-player-of-the-month-120319 |publisher=Fox Sports |accessdate=3 December 2019 |date=3 December 2019}}</ref> In December, he was also named ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' 2019 Breakout of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks' Luka Doncic Wins Sports Illustrated's Breakout of the Year Award |url=https://www.si.com/sportsperson/2019/12/04/luka-doncic-dallas-mavericks-sports-illustrated-breakout-award |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> On December 8, 2019, Don\u010di\u0107 surpassed the record for the most consecutive games with at least 20 points, 5 rebounds, and 5 assists since the ABA-NBA merger in 1976. Michael Jordan previously held the record with 18 consecutive games in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |title= Luka Doncic passes Michael Jordan with 19th straight game of 20-5-5 |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/12/08/doncic-passes-jordan-20-5-5 |website=nba.com |accessdate=December 11, 2019 }}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 made his tenth season triple-double on January 4, 2020, posting 39 points, 12 rebounds, and 10 assists in a 123\u2013120 loss to the [[Charlotte Hornets]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Watch Luka Doncic\u2019s NBA-leading 10th triple-double, but Mavs still fall to Hornets in OT |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/watch-luka-doncic-nba-leading-151335381.html|website=yahoo.com |accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 NBA season|2019\u201320 season]], Don\u010di\u0107 was selected to his first [[2020 NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Game]] as a Western Conference starter.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sekou |last=Smith |title=Captains LeBron James, Giannis Antetokounmpo headline starters for NBA All-Star 2020 |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/01/23/2020-all-star-starters-and-captains-announced |website=NBA.com |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> He became the youngest European player to start in an All-Star game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Don\u010di\u0107 named starter for 2020 NBA All-star game |url=https://www.mavs.com/luka-all-star-2020-press-release/ |publisher=mavs.com |accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> On 4 March, Don\u010di\u0107 recorded his 22nd career triple-double, passing Jason Kidd for the most in franchise history, as he registered 30 points, 17 rebounds and 10 assists in a 127\u2013123 overtime victory over the [[New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Second-year Luka Doncic sets Mavericks\u2019 career triple-double record (video)|url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2020/03/05/second-year-luka-doncic-sets-mavericks-career-triple-double-record-video/|publisher=mavs.com |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\n===Junior national team===\n[[File:EuroBasket 2017 Finland vs Slovenia 29.jpg|thumb|Don\u010di\u0107 (front) during [[EuroBasket 2017]]]]\nDon\u010di\u0107 was set to play at the Division B tournament of the [[2014 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] but was forced to withdraw from the tournament with a knee injury. In December 2014, he took part in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] tournament in [[Sz\u00e9kesfeh\u00e9rv\u00e1r]], Hungary, averaging 35.3 points and 7.6 rebounds per game, while shooting 81 percent on two-pointers and 57 percent on [[three-point field goal|three-pointers]].<ref name=\"FIBA Article\" />\n\n===Senior national team===\nOn September 22, 2016, Don\u010di\u0107 announced that he would represent the senior men's [[Slovenia national basketball team|Slovenian national team]] for the rest of his career.<ref>{{cite web|title=LUKA DON\u010cI\u0106: \"Hvala \u0160paniji, Slovenija je moja izbira!\"|url=http://www.kosarka.si/luka-doncic-hvala-spaniji-slovenija-je-moja-izbira/|website=kosarka.si|accessdate=September 22, 2016|language=sl-SL|date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> He had previously been linked with a number of other national teams, including [[Serbia men's national basketball team|Serbia]] and [[Spain men's national basketball team|Spain]].<ref name=\"rtv-intervju\">{{cite news | url= http://www.rtvslo.si/sport/kosarka/doncic-na-evropskem-prvenstvu-gremo-po-medaljo/413818 | title = Don\u010di\u0107: Na evropskem prvenstvu gremo po medaljo |trans-title=Doncic: At the Eurobasket we are aiming for a medal  | publisher = [[RTV Slovenija]] | date = January 30, 2017 | accessdate = February 2, 2017 | language = Slovenian }}</ref> His national team [[roommate]] became [[Goran Dragi\u0107]], who he met at age 7 and has been cited as his mentor and friend.<ref name=\"dragic\">{{cite web |last1=Schmitz |first1=Mike |title=How Goran Dragic went from national hero to first-time All-Star |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/22444031/how-miami-heat-guard-goran-dragic-went-national-hero-first-nba-all-star |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |date=February 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDon\u010di\u0107 was a member of the Slovenian squad for EuroBasket 2017, where his country won its first gold medal, after going undefeated (9\u20130) in the tournament.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/news/slovenia-overcome-injuries-to-claim-historic-title|title=Slovenia overcome injuries to claim historic title in Dragic's swansong|date=September 17, 2017|publisher=FIBA.basketball|accessdate=September 19, 2017}}</ref> In Slovenia's 103\u201397 win over [[Latvia national basketball team|Latvia]] in the quarterfinals, he scored 27 points and grabbed 9 rebounds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/1209/Slovenia-Latvia|title=Slovenia v Latvia|date=September 12, 2017|publisher=FIBA.basketball|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> He recorded 11 points, 12 rebounds and 8 assists, in the 92\u201372 semi-final win over Spain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/1409/Spain-Slovenia#tab=boxscore_statistics|title=Spain v Slovenia|publisher=FIBA.basketball|date=September 14, 2017|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> In the final, which Slovenia won by a score of 93\u201385 over Serbia, he had 8 points and 7 rebounds, before falling out of the game, due to an injury, in the game's third quarter.<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/1709/Slovenia-Serbia#%7Ctab=boxscore_statistics |title= Slovenia v Serbia |date= September 19, 2017 |publisher= FIBA.basketball|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 was also named to the competition's [[FIBA EuroBasket All-Tournament Team|All-Tournament Team]], joining teammate Goran Dragi\u0107, who was also voted the [[EuroBasket MVP]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/news/title-hero-dragic-caps-off-fairy-tale-finish-with-mvp-honors |title= Title hero Dragic caps off fairy tale finish with MVP honors |date= September 17, 2017 |publisher= FIBA.basketball|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Player profile==\n{{quote box\n|quote=\"[Don\u010di\u0107 is] incredible with the ball for a big guy. He's unbelievable in [[pick and roll]] play. His court vision is already unbelievable. I couldn't believe what I saw from a 19/20-year-old. He's a good shooter when he has time and I think he's going to be great for [the [[Dallas Mavericks]]] for a long, long time... I could shoot a little bit but I never had the court vision... the savviness that he brings to the game... He's going to pick defenses apart and it's going to be fun to watch.\"\n|source=\u2014 Mavericks star and teammate [[Dirk Nowitzki]] on Don\u010di\u0107 before the 2018\u201319 NBA season.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Spencer |title=Dirk Nowitzki Says Teenage Luka Doncic Was Better Than He Was as a Teenager |url=https://www.complex.com/sports/2018/09/dirk-nowitzki-says-teenage-luka-doncic-better-than-him-as-teenager |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=October 6, 2018 |date=September 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|width=30em\n|align=right}}\nDon\u010di\u0107 has frequently been described as a \"position-less guard\" with attributes of a [[point guard]], [[shooting guard]], and [[small forward]].<ref name=\"kings\">{{cite web |last1=Ramirez |first1=Jordan |title=Get to Know: Luka Doncic |url=https://www.nba.com/kings/blog/get-know-luka-doncic |publisher=[[National Basketball Association]] |accessdate=June 10, 2018 |date=May 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Phillips |first1=Ryan |title=5 Things To Know About Luka Doncic |url=https://thebiglead.com/2018/06/21/luka-doncic-2018-nba-draft-five-things/ |publisher=The Big Lead |accessdate=October 5, 2018 |date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> Standing {{convert|6|ft|7|in|m|2}} and weighing {{convert|230|lbs|kg|1}},<ref>{{cite web|title=Luka Doncic|publisher=National Basketball Association|url=https://www.nba.com/players/luka/doncic/1629029|accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref> he has been praised for his exceptional size and strength for the [[guard (basketball)|guard]] position.<ref name=\"austingreen\">{{cite news |last1=Green |first1=Austin |title=What you need to know about Luka Doncic, the most polished European teen prospect ever |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/2018-nba-draft-what-you-need-to-know-about-luka-doncic-the-most-polished-european-teen-prospect-ever/ |work=[[CBSSports.com|CBS Sports]] |accessdate=June 10, 2018 |date=June 5, 2018}}</ref> Dallas Mavericks executive [[Donnie Nelson]] lauded his \"[[point forward]] ability,\"<ref name=\"sefko\">{{cite web |last1=Sefko |first1=Eddie |title=Did the Mavericks draft a '6\u20137 Steve Nash' in Luka Doncic? |url=https://sportsday.dallasnews.com/dallas-mavericks/mavericks/2018/07/07/meet-theslovenian-teenager-mavs-draft-radar-drawing-nash-andporzingis-comparisons |website=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=October 5, 2018 |date=July 7, 2018}}</ref> and sports website [[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] labeled him a \"legitimate point guard with the size of a [[Small ball (basketball)|small-ball]] [[power forward (basketball)|power forward]].\"<ref name=\"wonderyears\">{{cite web |last1=Tjarks |first1=Jonathan |title=The Mavericks\u2019 Wonder Years Are Here |url=https://www.theringer.com/nba/2018/6/22/17494086/luka-doncic-dallas-mavericks-nba-draft |publisher=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |accessdate=October 5, 2018 |date=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince his early years with Real Madrid, Don\u010di\u0107 was tabbed as one of Europe's premier talents, with Spanish newspaper ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' giving him the nickname \"El Ni\u00f1o Maravilla\" (Wonder Boy).<ref name=\"FIBA Article\"/> Entering the 2018 NBA draft, he was widely seen as one of the best and most accomplished European prospects of his generation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tjarks |first1=Jonathan |title=Luka Doncic Might Be the Best European NBA Prospect of the 21st Century |url=https://www.theringer.com/2017/7/20/16077958/nba-draft-luka-doncic-real-madrid-f534e7428bf6 |publisher=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |date=July 20, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]]'' magazine considered Don\u010di\u0107 the \"best international prospect ever,\"<ref name=\"slam\">{{cite web |last1=Laird |first1=Sam |title=Luka Doncic is the Best International Prospect Ever |url=https://www.slamonline.com/nba/luka-doncic-slam-cover/ |website=[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]] |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |date=May 15, 2018}}</ref> and sports website [[SB Nation]] called him \"most accomplished NBA prospect in decades.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ellentuck |first1=Matt |title=Luka Doncic is the most accomplished NBA prospect in decades. Congratulations, Mavericks fans |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2018/6/21/17480374/nba-draft-2018-teamname-luka-doncic |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> An anonymous NBA veteran scouting executive said that his game was \"leap years above anyone\" else in his draft class.<ref name=leapyears>{{cite web |last1=Wasserman |first1=Jonathan |title=NBA Exec Says Luka Doncic 'Leap Years Above Anyone' After EuroBasket Brilliance |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2732792-nba-exec-says-luka-doncic-leap-years-above-anyone-after-eurobasket-brilliance#slide2 |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |accessdate=June 10, 2018 |date=September 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDon\u010di\u0107 is versatile on the offensive end, displaying proficiency in shooting three-pointers and mid-range [[Jump shot (basketball)|jump shots]] as well as [[Basketball moves#Tear drop|floaters]] and shots in the post.<ref name=hawks>{{cite web |title=Will Luka Doncic Take The NBA By Storm? |url=http://www.nba.com/hawks/draft-profile-luka-doncic |publisher=[[National Basketball Association]] |accessdate=June 10, 2018 |date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> His basketball IQ, intangibles, and skills have been considered his primary assets, and he is seen as an elite facilitator, especially on the [[pick and roll]].<ref name=leapyears/> NBA and EuroLeague coach [[Ettore Messina]] called him \"phenomenal, especially mentally\" for his age.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zachari |first1=Antigoni |title=Ettore Messina: \"Luka Doncic is phenomenal, especially mentally\" |url=https://www.eurohoops.net/en/nba-news/734293/ettore-messina-luka-doncic-is-phenomenal-especially-mentally/ |publisher=EuroHoops |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |date=September 6, 2018}}</ref> His lack of lateral quickness to stay in front most NBA point guards and wings has been labeled as one of his main flaws as a player.<ref name=fraschilla/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Austin |title=Luka Doncic scouting report: What to know about 2018 NBA Draft's top European prospect |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/luka-doncic-scouting-report-what-to-know-about-2018-nba-drafts-top-european-prospect/ |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |accessdate=October 5, 2018 |date=June 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Woo |first1=Jeremy |title=Luka Doncic: Europe's Next Big Thing |url=https://www.si.com/nba/2017/08/10/luka-doncic-nba-draft-slovenia-real-madrid-eurobasket |website=[[Sports Illustrated]] |accessdate=October 5, 2018 |date=August 10, 2017}}</ref> Dallas Mavericks head coach [[Rick Carlisle]] refuted some of the worries regarding Don\u010di\u0107's athleticism, stating that \"for a 19-year-old, he's got a really unusual combination of size, speed, and deceptive quickness.\"<ref>https://www.eurohoops.net/en/nba-news/767584/rick-carlisle-on-what-has-impressed-him-the-most-about-luka-doncic/</ref> By his sophomore year, Lukas' ability to accelerate off a pick and blow by defenders to get to the basket is seen as one of his strengths.<ref>https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/numbers-dont-lie-luka-doncics-historic-sophomore-season-is-second-to-none-in-the-nbas-modern-era/</ref>\n\nPrior to his draft, basketball journalist and scout, Austin Green, compared Don\u010di\u0107 to NBA players [[Paul Pierce]] and [[Joe Johnson (basketball)|Joe Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/hawks/draft-profile-luka-doncic |title=Draft Profile: Will Luka Doncic Take The NBA By Storm? |publisher=National Basketball Association |date=June 8, 2018|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> Don\u010di\u0107 compared himself to [[Ben Simmons]] due to his versatility.<ref name=\"kimes\">{{cite web |last1=Kimes |first1=Mina |title=Luka Doncic Is No Darko Milicic |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/feature/story/_/id/23051130/will-luka-doncic-next-star-nba-player-europe |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=June 10, 2018 |date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> In his second season, LA Clippers coach, [[Doc Rivers]], when asked about Don\u010di\u0107 stated that \"there's a lot of people in him.\" He likened Don\u010di\u0107\u2019s stepback 3-pointers to [[James Harden]], his passing ability to [[Larry Bird]] and his court vision to [[LeBron James]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Townsend |first1=Brad |title=Does Luka Doncic have one true comparison? Mavs star evokes NBA greats past and present while showing \u2018he\u2019s an original\u2019 |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/sports/mavericks/2019/12/13/does-luka-doncic-have-one-true-comparison-mavs-star-is-evoking-nba-greats-past-and-present-while-showing-hes-an-original/ |publisher=dallasnews.com |date=13 December 2019}}</ref> NBA analyst, [[Kendrick Perkins]], called him \"baby LeBron\" due to his overall skill and dominance on the court.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Buford |first1=Landon |title=Mavs\u2019 Luka Doncic Is a \u2018Baby LeBron\u2019 Says NBA Champion |url=https://heavy.com/sports/2019/12/mavericks-luka-doncic-baby-lebron-nba/ |publisher=Heavy.com |date=17 December 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, San Antonio Spurs coach, [[Gregg Popovich]], called Don\u010di\u0107's playing style \"[[Magic Johnson]]-like\" because \"he sees the floor in that same way.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mutoni |first1=Marcel |title=Gregg Popovich: Luka Doncic \u2018Magic Johnson-Like\u2019 |url=https://www.slamonline.com/nba/gregg-popovich-luka-doncic-magic-johnson-like/ |publisher=SLAM |accessdate=28 December 2019 |date=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Euroleague player statistics legend}}\n\n===EuroLeague===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#AFE6BA; width:3em;\"|\u2020\n|Denotes season in which Don\u010di\u0107's team won the [[EuroLeague champion|EuroLeague]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#CFECEC; width:1em\"|\n|Led the league\n|}\n\n{{Euroleague player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 Euroleague|2015\u201316]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 Real Madrid Baloncesto season|Real Madrid]]\n| 12 || 0 || 11.1 || .407 || .313 || '''.882''' || 2.3 || 2.0 || .2 || '''.3''' || 3.5 || 6.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2016\u201317 EuroLeague|2016\u201317]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2016\u201317 Real Madrid Baloncesto season|Real Madrid]]\n| '''35''' || 15 || 19.9 || .433 || '''.371 || .844 || 4.5 || 4.2 || .9 || .2 || 7.8 || 13.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:#AFE6BA;\"| [[2017\u201318 EuroLeague|2017\u201318]]\u2020\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Real Madrid Baloncesto season|Real Madrid]]\n| 33 || '''17''' || '''25.9''' || '''.451''' || .329 || .816 || '''4.8''' || '''4.3''' || '''1.1''' || '''.3''' || '''16.0''' || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"|'''21.5'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| Career\n| 80 || 32 || 21.0 || .443 || .344 || .828 || 4.3 || 3.9 || .9 || .3 || 10.6 || 15.6\n{{S-end}}\n\n===Liga ACB===\n:''Cited from ACB.com''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acb.com/stsacumjug.php?cod_jugador=460|title=Historial estad\u00edstico Doncic, Luka|language=Spanish|website=Liga ACB|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626182110/http://www.acb.com/stsacumjug.php?cod_jugador=460|archive-date=June 26, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#AFE6BA; width:3em;\"|\n|Denotes season in which Don\u010di\u0107's team won the [[Liga ACB]]\n|}\n\n{{Euroleague player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:#AFE6BA;\"| [[2014\u201315 ACB season|2014\u201315]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]]\n| 5 || 0 || 4.8 || .427 || .333 || .750 || 1.2 || .0 || .0 || .0 || 1.6 || 1.8\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:#AFE6BA;\"| [[2015\u201316 ACB season|2015\u201316]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 Real Madrid Baloncesto season|Real Madrid]]\n| 39 || 0 || 12.9 || '''.526''' || '''.392''' || .708 || 2.6 || 1.7 || .4 || .3 || 4.5 || 5.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2016\u201317 ACB season|2016\u201317]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2016\u201317 Real Madrid Baloncesto season|Real Madrid]]\n| '''42''' || 11 || 19.8 || .441 || .295 || '''.785''' || 4.4 || 3.0 || .6 || .3 || 7.5 || 11.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:#AFE6BA;\"| [[2017\u201318 ACB season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Real Madrid Baloncesto season|Real Madrid]]\n| 37 || '''21''' || '''24.3''' || .462 || .293 || .752 || '''5.7''' || '''4.7''' || '''1.1''' || '''.4''' || '''12.5''' || '''18.4'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\"| Career\n| 123 || 32 || 18.3 || .463 || .310 || .754 || 4.1 || 3.0 || .7 || .3 || 7.8 || 11.6\n{{S-end}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas]]\n| 72 || 72 || 32.2 || .427 || .327 || .713 || 7.8 || 6.0 || 1.1 || .3 || 21.2\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 72 || 72 || 32.2 || .427 || .327 || .713 || 7.8 || 6.0 || 1.1 || .3 || 21.2\n{{S-end}}\n\n==NBA records and accomplishments==\n*First teenager to record a 30-point triple-double (35 points, 12 rebounds, 10 assists).<ref>https://thesmokingcuban.com/2019/02/28/dallas-mavericks-2019-luka-doncic-achievements-before-20/4/</ref>\n*Second player in NBA history to post 2,000+ points, 750+ rebounds and 500+ assists in their first 100 career games (alongside [[Oscar Robertson]]).<ref>https://twitter.com/MavsPR/status/1211513815810134016</ref>\n*NBA record of 20 straight games with at least 20 points, 5 rebounds, and 5 assists. Previously held by [[Michael Jordan]] with 18 consecutive games.<ref>https://www.talkbasket.net/60560-luka-doncic-breaks-michael-jordans-record</ref>\n*Youngest player in NBA history to record three triple-doubles.<ref>{{cite web |title=NBA: Doncic nets triple-double in Mavs' win over Hornets |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/sports/02/07/19/nba-doncic-nets-triple-double-in-mavs-win-over-hornets |website=news.abs-cbn.com |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*Only player in NBA history to record two triple-doubles before the age of 20.<ref>https://spainsnews.com/luka-doncic-breaks-another-record-in-the-nba/</ref>\n*Don\u010di\u0107 has four of the five triple-doubles recorded by teenagers in NBA history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic has 4 of the 5 triple-doubles recorded by teenagers in NBA history |url=https://clutchpoints.com/mavs-news-luka-doncic-has-4-of-the-5-triple-doubles-recorded-by-teenagers-in-nba-history/ |website=clutchpoints.com |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*Youngest player to have 35-point triple-doubles in succession, breaking [[Oscar Robertson]]'s record.<ref> youngest player to have 35-point triple-doubles in succession, breaking Oscar Robertson's record</ref>\n*First player in NBA history to record 30+ points, 12+ rebounds, and 15+ assists in a game with 30 minutes or fewer played.\n*First player in NBA history to record multiple 30-point triple-doubles in games with 30 minutes or fewer played.<ref>https://heavy.com/sports/2019/12/mavericks-luka-doncic-warriors-nba/</ref>\n*At 19 years and 327 days old he recorded his first-ever triple-double, just ten days older than the youngest player ever, [[Markelle Fultz]].<ref>https://thesmokingcuban.com/2019/02/28/dallas-mavericks-2019-luka-doncic-achievements-before-20/3/</ref>\n* Fifth player in NBA history to average at least 20 points, 5 rebounds and 5 assists in his rookie year, joining [[Oscar Robertson]] ([[1960\u201361 NBA season|1960\u201361]]), Michael Jordan ([[1984\u201385 NBA season|1984\u201385]]), [[LeBron James]] ([[2003\u201304 NBA season|2003\u201304]]), and [[Tyreke Evans]] ([[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic: A Rookie Year in Context|url=https://hashtagbasketball.com/dallas-mavericks/content/luka-doncic-rookie-year-context|website=Hashtag Basketball|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* Youngest player in NBA history with 20 points, 15 rebounds and 15 assists in a game<ref>https://twitter.com/SportsCenter/status/1217681265618571265</ref>\n*Don\u010di\u0107 broke [[Jason Kidd]]'s Mavericks franchise record (21) of most triple doubles with 22 in just 122 NBA games.<ref>https://www.aa.com.tr/en/sports/luka-doncic-sets-triple-double-record-in-mavericks-win/1755424</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDon\u010di\u0107 can speak four languages: Slovenian, Serbian, English, and Spanish.<ref name=\"linked\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Michael |title=After being part of the draft's biggest splash, Luka Doncic, Trae Young now linked forever |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/part-drafts-biggest-splash-luka-doncic-trae-young-now-linked-forever-151154289.html |work=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |date=June 22, 2018}}</ref> He learned Spanish after joining Real Madrid.<ref name=\"turns18\">{{cite web |last1=Bueno |first1=Edu |title=Doncic turns 18 |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2017/02/doncic-turns-18 |publisher=[[Real Madrid C.F.]] |accessdate=October 2, 2018 |date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, while playing at Real Madrid, Don\u010di\u0107 signed a two-year deal with [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic, de Mavericks, firma acuerdo de calzado con marca Jordan |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/basquetbol/nota/_/id/6460500/luka-doncic-de-mavericks-firma-acuerdo-de-calzado-con-marca-jordan |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=12 January 2020 |language=Spanish |date=26 December 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, it was announced that Don\u010di\u0107 had signed a multi-year endorsement deal with [[Air Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Doncic Officially Agrees To A Shoe Deal With Jordan Brand |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/doylerader/2019/12/26/luka-doncic-jordan-brand-shoe-deal-official/#56e89c1f3055 |work=Forbes|accessdate=30 December 2019|first=Doyle|last=Rader|date=26 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mavericks star Luka Doncic signs endorsement deal with Jordan Brand: Three things to know |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/mavericks-star-luka-doncic-signs-endorsement-deal-with-jordan-brand-three-things-to-know/ |website=cbssports.com |accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Sports}}\n* [[List of youngest EuroLeague players since the 2000\u201301 season|List of youngest EuroLeague players]]\n* [[List of European basketball players in the United States]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{basketballstats|nba=luka_doncic|bbr=d/doncilu01}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151215220709/http://acb.com/jugador.php?id=460 Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at acb.com {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://basketball.eurobasket.com/player/Luka-Doncic/Spain/Real_Madrid/333799 Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at eurobasket.com\n*[http://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?pcode=005929 Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at euroleague.net\n*[http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/q/luka%20doncic/pid//_//players.html Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at fiba.com\n*[http://www.realmadrid.com/en/basketball/team/luka-doncic Luka Don\u010di\u0107] at realmadrid.com\n\n{{Dallas Mavericks current roster}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{2018 NBA Draft}}\n{{NBA Rookies of the Year}}\n{{Slovenia Squad EuroBasket 2017}}\n{{Real Madrid Baloncesto 2017\u201318 EuroLeague champions}}\n{{Euroleague 2010\u201320 All-Decade}}\n{{Euroleague MVP Award}}\n{{Euroleague Final Four MVP Award}}\n{{Euroleague Rising Star Award}}\n{{ACB MVP Award}}\n{{ACB Best Young Player Award}}\n{{Euroleague NGT MVP}}\n{{Slovenian Sportsman of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doncic, Luka}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Hawks draft picks]]\n[[Category:Dallas Mavericks players]]\n[[Category:FIBA EuroBasket-winning players]]\n[[Category:Liga ACB players]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association players from Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Baloncesto players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Slovenian expatriate basketball people in Spain]]\n[[Category:Slovenian expatriate basketball people in the United States]]\n[[Category:Slovenian men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Slovenian people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ljubljana]]\n", "name_user": "IndexAccount", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEuroLeague 2010\u201320 All-Decade Team", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luka_Don%C4%8Di%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "G\u00fclen movement", "text_new": "{{short description|Transnational civic movement}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox militant organization\n| name             = G\u00fclen movement\n| image            =\n| image_border     =\n| alt              =\n|caption           =  [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]] at home in Saylorsburg, Pennsylvania, in 2018\n| native_name      = G\u00fclen hareketi\n| native_name_lang = tr\n| other_name       = {{plainlist|\n* the ''hizmet''\n* \"[the] ''[[cemaat]]''\"}}\n| country          = [[Turkey]], [[United States]], [[European Union]]\n| language         =\n| leader_title     =\n| leader_name      = [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]]\n| main_organ       =\n| parent_organization =\n| affiliations     =\n| num_staff        =\n| num_volunteers   =\n| headquarters     =\n| location         =\n| coords           =\n| foundation       =\n| dissolved        =\n| merger           =\n| split            =\n| predecessor      =\n| merged           =\n| successor        =\n| motives          =\n| area             =  Worldwide\n| region_served    =\n| membership       =\n| ideology         = '''G\u00fclenism'''\n* [[Islamic democracy]]\n* [[Liberalism and progressivism within Islam|Progressive Islam]]\n* [[Islamism]] ([[moderate]])\n* [[Conservative democracy]]\n* [[Interfaith dialogue]]\n| position         =\n| status           =\n* Collection of schools, associations and media outlets with no centralised executive leadership\n* Banned by [[Republic of Turkey]]\n| size             = Formerly 200,000 to 4 million<br>Presently unknown.\n70,000 in [[Germany]] (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/germany-signals-tougher-stance-on-feto/1172010|title=Germany signals tougher stance on FETO|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n| revenue          =\n| financing        =\n| budget           =\n| flag             =\n| website          =\n* [https://fgulen.com/en/gulen-movement/questions-and-answers FGulen.com: Gulen movement questions and answers]\n* [https://afsv.org/ afsv.org]\n|designated_as_terror_group_by={{PAK}}<br />{{TUR}}<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus.svg}} [[Northern Cyprus|Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]]<br />{{flagicon image|GCC Flag.svg}} [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]<br />{{flagicon image|}} [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]]}}{{quote box|width = 34%|quote = \"''Dar al-hizmet'' is a relatively new term used to describe a new Islamic worldview that does not divide the globe between Islamic and un-Islamic spheres but regards the whole world as the locus of serving humanity at large and through this service attaining the good pleasure of God. Thus, ''dar al-hizmet'' as an Islamic term does not have its basis in geopolitical calculations and considerations[...]but has its basis in the social and spiritual concepts of ''ihsan'' (God-consciouness), ''di\u011fergaml\u0131k'' (altruism) and ultimately ''hizmet'' (service). Thus, ''dar al-hizmet'' has the potential to mobilise Muslims towards becoming more socially responsible in their communities and their host countries, regardless of the dominant faith or ideology, or the form of governance where they live.\"|source=[https://www.hizmetstudies.org/commentary/dar-al-hizmet-abode-of-service-in-a-globalized-world/ \"''Dar al-Hizmet'' &ndash; Abode of Service in a Globalized World],\" Will Taylor, Center for Hizmet Studies (London), January 7, 2015<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hizmetstudies.org/commentary/dar-al-hizmet-abode-of-service-in-a-globalized-world/ |title = Dar al-Hizmet / Abode of Service in a Globalized World}}</ref>}}\n\nThe '''G\u00fclen movement''' ({{lang-tr|G\u00fclen hareketi}}), referred as '''FETO''' by the current [[Government of Turkey]] and as '''Hizmet''' by its participants, is a transnational [[social movement|socially-conscious]] Islamic movement with political overtones, inspired by the writings and preachings of [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]], a Turkish [[Islam]]ic preacher who has lived in the [[United States]] since 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/fethullah-gulens-pennsylvania-home-2013-12|title=Fethullah G\u00fclen's Pennsylvania Home - Business Insider|author=Adam Taylor|date=18 December 2013|work=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/vg/video-gallery/what-is-feto-an-overview-of-the-terrorist-organization/0|title=Anadolu Agency|website=Anadolu Agency}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/what-is-feto--8654|title=What is FETO?}}</ref> The movement is [[List of designated terrorist groups|designated as a terrorist organization]] by [[Turkey]],<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-gulen-idUSKCN0YM167|title=Turkey officially designates Gulen religious group as terrorists|date=31 May 2016|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> [[Pakistan]],<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistanis-laud-landmark-verdict-on-feto-terror-group-/1351082|title=Pakistanis laud \u2018landmark\u2019 verdict on FETO terror group|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref> and the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]].<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161014-gcc-declare-feto-a-terrorist-organisation/|title=GCC declare Gulen group a 'terrorist organisation'|date=14 October 2016}}</ref> However, their purported terror activities are not recognized as such by the [[United States]], nor the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turkeypurge.com/|title=Turkey Purge &#124; Monitoring human rights abuses in Turkey's post-coup crackdown}}</ref> Owing to the outlawed status of the G\u00fclen movement in Turkey, some observers refer to the movement's volunteers who are Turkish Muslims as effectively a sub-[[Islamic schools and branches|sect of Sunni Islam]];<ref>{{cite web|author=By THE NEW YORK TIMESMARCH 9, 2018 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/09/world/europe/turkey-journalists-prison-terrorism.html |title=Turkey Sentences 24 Journalists to Prison, Claiming Terrorism Ties - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2018-03-09 |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/over-half-million-suspected-gulenists-investigated-coup |title=Over half a million suspected G\u00fclenists investigated since coup &#124; Ahval |publisher=Ahvalnews.com |date=2018-03-16 |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=<!----><!---->Kenneth Rapoza<!----> |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2015/12/20/in-sunni-cult-fight-turkey-guns-for-americas-richest-and-most-politically-connected-cleric/ |title=In Sunni 'Cult' Fight, Turkey Guns For America's Richest And Most Politically Connected Cleric |publisher=Forbes.com |date= |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref> these volunteers generally hold their religious tenets as generically Turkish [[Sunni Islam]]. The movement also includes participants from other nationalities and religious affiliations.\n\nA U.S.-based umbrella foundation which is affiliated with the movement is the [[Alliance for Shared Values]]. The movement has attracted supporters and drawn the attention of critics in Turkey, [[Central Asia]], and other parts of the world. It is active in education and operates private schools and universities in over 180 countries. It has initiated forums for interfaith dialogue. It has substantial investments in media, finance, and for-profit health clinics.<ref name=ABC>{{cite web |url= http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/encounter/turkey-gallipoli-gulen-capitalism/4853162#transcript|title= The Turkish exception: Gallipoli, G\u00fclen, and capitalism|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 31 August 2013|website= Australia's ABC|publisher= Radio National|accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"jbwhite\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJ8S_wG06MEC|title=Islamist Mobilization in Turkey: A Study in Vernacular Politics|first=Jenny Barbara|last=White|date=1 January 2002|publisher=University of Washington Press|via=Google Books|isbn=9780295982236}}</ref> Despite its teachings which are stated conservative even in Turkey, some have praised the movement as a pacifist, modern-oriented version of Islam, and an alternative to more extreme schools of Islam such as [[Salafism]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21578113-muslim-cleric-america-wields-surprising-political-power-turkey-gulenists-fight-back|title=The Gulenists fight back|journal=The Economist|date=18 May 2013}}</ref> But it has also been reported of having \"global, apocalyptic ambition\", a \"cultish hierarchy\"<ref name=\"NYT-23-7-16\">{{cite news|last1=Akyol|first1=Mustafa|title=Who Was Behind the Coup Attempt in Turkey?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/22/opinion/who-was-behind-the-coup-attempt-in-turkey.html?|accessdate=23 July 2016|agency=New York Times|date=July 22, 2016}}</ref> and of being a secretive [[Islamic sect]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21703186-president-erdogan-blames-gulenists-putsch-and-has-launched-massive-purges-most-turks|title=Most Turks believe a secretive Muslim sect was behind the failed coup|journal=The Economist|date=28 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/guelen-movement-accused-of-being-a-sect-a-848763.html|title=Altruistic Society or Sect? The Shadowy World of the Islamic G\u00fclen Movement - SPIEGEL ONLINE - International|first=SPIEGEL ONLINE, Hamburg|last=Germany|newspaper=Spiegel Online|date=8 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe G\u00fclen movement is a former ally of the Turkish [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP). When the AKP came to [[Government of Turkey|power]] in 2002 the two formed, despite their differences, a tactical alliance against military tutelage and the [[Secularism in Turkey|Turkish secular]] elite.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-to-add-gulen-movement-to-list-of-terror-groups-president-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=99762&NewsCatID=338|title=Turkey to add G\u00fclen movement to list of terror groups: President|last=|first=|date=27 May 2016|work=Hurriyet Daily News|access-date=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.turkishminute.com/2016/06/03/eu-expresses-concern-declaration-gulen-movement-terrorist-without-due-process/|title=EU expresses concern over declaration of G\u00fclen movement as terrorist without due process|last=|first=|date=3 June 2016|work=Turkish Minute|access-date=|via=}}</ref> It was through this alliance that the AKP had accomplished an unprecedented feat in Turkish republican history by securing national electoral victories sufficient to form three consecutive majority governments in 2002, 2007, and 2011. The G\u00fclen movement gained influence on the Turkish police force and the judiciary during its alliance with conservative President Erdo\u011fan, which saw hundreds of G\u00fclen supporters appointed to positions within the Turkish government.<ref>{{cite news |title= Turkey as a model of democracy and Islam |url= https://www.opendemocracy.net/arab-awakening/sami-zubaida/turkey-as-model-of-democracy-and-islam |date= 30 May 2011 | accessdate = 22 September 2016 }}</ref> Once the old establishment was defeated around 2010 to 2011 disagreements emerged between the AKP and the G\u00fclen movement. The first breaking point was the so-called \u2033[[National Intelligence Organization (Turkey)|MIT]] crisis\u2033 of February 2012, it was also interpreted as a power struggle between pro-G\u00fclen police and judiciary and the AKP.<ref>Halil M. Karaveli: [http://www.turkeyanalyst.org/publications/turkey-analyst-articles/item/395-the-coalition-crumbles-erdogan-the-g%C3%BClenists-and-turkish-democracy.html The Coalition Crumbles: Erdogan, the G\u00fclenists, and Turkish Democracy], The Turkey Analyst, vol. 5, no. 4, Feb. 20, 2012</ref><ref>Sebnem Arsu: [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/11/world/europe/turkey-intelligence-chief-must-testify.html Intelligence Chief Must Testify], nytimes.com, Feb. 10, 2012</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/25/world/middleeast/turkey-feels-sway-of-fethullah-gulen-a-reclusive-cleric.html Turkey Feels Sway of Reclusive Cleric in the U.S.], nytimes.com, April 24, 2012</ref> After the [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|2013 corruption investigations in Turkey]] into stated corrupt practices by several bureaucrats, ministers, mayors, and family members of the ruling AKP of Turkey was uncovered,<ref name=\"Journal-28Dec2013\">{{cite news |title= Turkey: Erdogan faces new protests over corruption scandal |url= http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/erdogan-faces-new-protests-over-corruption-scandal/article/364759 |newspaper= Digital Journal |date= 28 December 2013 |accessdate= 31 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hurriyet2013\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/ekonomi/25378685.asp |title=\u0130stanbul'da yolsuzluk ve r\u00fc\u015fvet operasyonu| date=17 December 2013}}</ref> President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] blamed the movement for initiating<ref name=\"BBCprofile-Dec2013\">{{cite news | title = Profile: Fethullah Gulen's Hizmet movement | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-13503361 |newspaper= [[BBC News]] |date= 18 December 2013 | accessdate = 31 December 2013 }}</ref> the investigations as a result of a break in previously friendly relations.<ref name=\"csmonitor.com\">{{cite news |title= The Gulen movement: a self-exiled imam challenges Turkey's Erdo\u011fan |url= http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2013/1229/The-Gulen-movement-a-self-exiled-imam-challenges-Turkey-s-Erdogan |newspaper= [[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date= 29 December 2013 |accessdate= 31 December 2013 }}</ref> President Erdo\u011fan said G\u00fclen attempted to overthrow the Turkish government through a judicial coup by the use of corruption investigations and seized the group-owned newspaper (''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]''\u2014 one of the most circulated [[List of newspapers in Turkey|newspapers in Turkey]] before the seizure<ref name=\"bpa\">{{cite web |url= http://www.clickpress.com/releases/Detailed/39645005cp.shtml |title=BPA Audit Figures Reveal Turkish Newspaper As Having One of the Largest Subscriber Bases in Europe |publisher=ClickPress |date=10 Jul 2007|accessdate= 1 August 2009}}</ref>) and several companies that have ties with the group.\n\nSince May 2016, the G\u00fclen movement has been classified as a terrorist organization by Turkey under the assigned names Fethullahist Terrorist Organization ({{lang-tr|Fethullah\u00e7\u0131 Ter\u00f6r \u00d6rg\u00fct\u00fc}}) (FET\u00d6) and [[Parallel state|Parallel State]] Structure ({{lang-tr|Paralel Devlet Yap\u0131lanmas\u0131}}) (PDY).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-gulen/turkey-officially-designates-gulen-religious-group-as-terrorists-idUSKCN0YM167 |title=Turkey officially designates Gulen religious group as terrorists |accessdate=31 May 2016|newspaper=Reuters |date=31 May 2016 }}</ref> After the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|failed coup attempt in 2016]], the government of Turkey blamed the group for the coup and authorities have [[2016 Turkish purges|arrested thousands of soldiers and judges]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36813924 |title=Turkey: Mass arrests after coup bid quashed, says PM \u2013 BBC News |work= BBC News|accessdate=16 July 2016|date=16 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/politics/2016/07/16/turkeys-top-judicial-board-hsyk-orders-detention-of-2745-gulen-linked-judges-over-coup-attempt|title=Turkey's top judicial board HSYK orders detention of 2,745 G\u00fclen-linked judges over coup attempt|access-date=17 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/07/17/asia/turkey-attempted-coup/index.html|title=Turkey coup attempt: Erdogan rounds up suspected plotters|author1=Sheena McKenzie |author2=Ray Sanchez|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Over ten thousand education staff were suspended and the licenses of over 20,000 teachers working at private institutions were revoked for stated affiliation to G\u00fclen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36838347 |title=Turkey coup: Purge widens to education sector |publisher=BBC News |date=19 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/americas/2016/07/16/us-to-help-turkey-investigate-failed-coup-attempt-by-feto|title=US to help Turkey investigate failed coup attempt by FET\u00d6|website=DailySabah}}</ref> Fethullah G\u00fclen condemned the coup and denied any involvement.<ref name=\"H\u00fcrriyet G\u00fclen\">{{cite news |title=194 killed in quashed G\u00fclenist coup attempt: Military |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/204-killed-in-quashed-gulenist-coup-attempt-military.aspx?pageID=238&nid=101669&NewsCatID=341 |date=16 July 2016 |accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bpacdp\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/17/us/fethullah-gulen-turkey-coup-attempt.html|title=An exiled cleric denies playing a leading role in coup attempt|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate= 17 July 2016|date=16 July 2016|last1=Saul|first1=Stephanie}}</ref>\n\n==Description and membership==\nThe movement states that it is based on moral values and advocacy of [[universal access to education]], [[civil society]], tolerance and peace. The emphasis among participants is to perform \"service\" (also the meaning of the Turkish word \"hizmet\" in Turkish) as arising from individuals' personal commitments to righteous imperatives. Along with ''hizmet,'' the movement, which has no official name, is termed the G\u00fclen movement or ''[[cemaat]]'' (the latter also used to describe participants in [[Sufi]] orders, meaning \"congregation,\" \"community,\" or \"assembly.\")The movement has been characterized as a \"moderate blend of Islam\".<ref name=nyt080504>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/04/world/asia/04islam.html?ex=1367640000&en=625b88103a702f94&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink |  first=Sabrina | last=Tavernise | authorlink=Sabrina Tavernise | title=Turkish Schools Offer Pakistan a Gentler Vision of Islam | date=4 May 2008 | work=New York Times}}</ref><ref name=tavernise>{{cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/podcasts/2008/04/25/25worldview.mp3|title=Interview with Sabrina Tavernise, World View Podcasts, New York Times, May 4, 2008}}</ref> G\u00fclen and the G\u00fclen movement are technology-friendly, work within current market and commerce structures, and are savvy users of modern communications and public relations.<ref name=prospect>Ehsan Masood, [http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/features/amodernottoman A modern Ottoman], ''Prospect'', Issue 148, July 2008</ref> In 2008, G\u00fclen was described as \"the modern face of the Sufi Ottoman tradition\", who reassures his followers, including many members of \"Turkey's aspirational middle class\", that \"they can combine the statist-nationalist beliefs of Atat\u00fcrk\u2019s republic with a traditional but flexible Islamic faith\" and \"Ottoman traditions that had been caricatured as theocratic by [[Atat\u00fcrk]] and his '[[Kemalist]]' heirs\".<ref name=prospect/>\n\nWithin Turkey the G\u00fclen movement keeps its distance from established Islamic political parties.<ref>Clement M. Henry, Rodney Wilson, [https://edinburghuniversitypress.com/book-the-politics-of-islamic-finance.html ''The politics of Islamic Finance''], Edinburgh University Press (2004), p 236. Retrieved 16 July 2016</ref>\n\nSources state that the G\u00fclen movement is vying to be recognized as the world's leading Muslim network, one that is more reasonable than many of its rivals.<ref name=economist10808408>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10808408|title=How far they have travelled|publisher=|via=The Economist}}</ref> The movement builds on the activities of G\u00fclen, who has won praise from non-Muslim quarters for his advocacy of science, [[interfaith dialogue]], and multi-party democracy. It has earned praise as \"the world's most global movement\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-144416-turkish-schools-worlds-most-global-movement-says-sociologist.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219021813/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-144416-turkish-schools-worlds-most-global-movement-says-sociologist.html|url-status=dead|title=Turkish schools World's most global movement, says sociologist|archivedate=19 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n\"It is impossible to calculate the size of the G\u00fclen movement\" since the movement is not a centralized or formal organization with membership rosters, but rather a set of numerous, loosely organized networks of people inspired by G\u00fclen.<ref>Helen Rose Ebaugh, ''The G\u00fclen Movement: A Sociological Analysis of a Civic Movement Rooted in Moderate Islam'' (Springer, 2009), p. 46.</ref> Estimates of the size of the movement vary, with one source stating that between 200,000 supporters and 4 million people are influenced by G\u00fclen's ideas (1997 ''[[Tempo (Turkey magazine)|Tempo]]'' estimate),<ref>Bulent Aras & Omer Caha, [http://www.rubincenter.org/2000/12/aras-and-caha-2000-12-04/ Fethullah Gulen and his Liberal \"Turkish Islam\" Movement], ''[[Middle East Review of International Affairs]]'', Vol. 4, No. 4 (December 2000).</ref> and another stating that G\u00fclen has \"hundreds of thousands of supporters\" (''The Guardian'', 2000).<ref name=guardian>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,4057646,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Turkey accuses popular Islamist of plot against state | date=1 September 2000 | accessdate=4 May 2010 | first=Chris | last=Morris}}</ref> The membership of the movement consists primarily of students, teachers, businessmen, academics, journalists and other professionals.<ref name=\"jbwhite\"/>  Its members have founded schools, universities, an employers' association, charities, real estate trusts, student organizations, radio and television stations, and newspapers.<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\nThe movement's structure has been described as a flexible organizational network.<ref>[http://www.qantara.de/webcom/show_article.php/_c-478/_nr-216/i.html Portrait of Fethullah G\u00fclen, A Modern Turkish-Islamic Reformist]</ref> Movement schools and businesses organize locally and link themselves into informal networks.<ref name=\"Islam in Kazakhstan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amerasianworld.com/islam_in_kazakhstan.php|title=Islam in Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan (The Nurcu Movement and the Hizb ut Tahrir)|first=Kevin Miller|last=Jr.|access-date=12 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213015820/http://www.amerasianworld.com/islam_in_kazakhstan.php|archive-date=13 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Akin to Turkey's Sufi [[tariqa]]s (lay religious orders), banned in Turkey in 1925,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rlp.hds.harvard.edu/faq/sufism-turkey |title=Sufism in Turkey &#124; Religious Literacy Project |publisher=Rlp.hds.harvard.edu |date= |accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> The movement skirted Kemalist Turkey's prohibitions against assembling in non-state sponsored religious meetings. (President-to-be of Turkey Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, when a young man, had belonged to the then-technically-banned-in-Turkey [[Naqshbandi]] tariqa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/re-visioning-religion/media-and-mysticism-erdo%C4%9Fan-and-g%C3%BClen-b7570f672362 |title=Media and Mysticism: Erdo\u011fan vs. G\u00fclen \u2013 Re-visioning Religion \u2013 Medium |publisher=Medium.com |date= 8 December 2016|accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref>)\n\nEach local G\u00fclen movement school and community has a person designated its \"informal\" (in the sense of not being Turkish state-sponsored) prayer leader ([[imam]]). In the G\u00fclen movement, this individual is a [[lay clergy|layman who serves for a stint within this volunteer position]]. His  identity is kept confidential, generally only purposely made known to those with close connections to those participating in decision-making and coordinating councils within the local group. Above a grouping of such \"secret\" (not-publicly-acknowledged) imams is another such volunteer leader. This relationship tree continues on up the laddar to the nation-level imam and to an individuals who consults with G\u00fclen himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulenists/gulen-community-service-feto |title=The 'ally' to 'enemy # 1': G\u00fclen Movement (1) &#124; Ahval |publisher=Ahvalnews.com |date= |accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> (These individuals closest to Gulen, having degrees from theology schools, are offhandedly referred to within the movement as ''[[mullah]]s.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/intellectual-crisis-gulen-movement|title=The Intellectual Crisis of the G\u00fclen Movement &#124; Ahval}}</ref>) G\u00fclen's position, as described in the foregoing, is analogous to that of a [[shaykh]] (master) of a Sufi tariqa. Unlike with traditional tariqas, no-one makes pledges of any sort, upon joining the G\u00fclen movement; one becomes a movement participant simply by working with others to promote and effect the movement's objectives of education and service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fgulen.com/en/home/1310-fgulen-com-english/fethullah-gulen-life/about-fethullah-gulen-and-gulen-movement/31760-is-the-gulen-movement-a-sufi-tariqa|title=Is the G\u00fclen Movement a Sufi tariqa? - Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site|first=Fethullah|last=G\u00fclen|website=fgulen.com}}</ref>\n\nThe G\u00fclen movement works within the given structures of modern secular states; it encourages affiliated members to maximize the opportunities those countries afford rather than engaging in subversive activities.<ref name=forbes0118>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/01/18/turkey-islam-gulen-cx_0121oxford.html |title=Gulen Inspires Muslims Worldwide |publisher=Forbes |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref> In the words of the leader himself and the title of a cornerstone of his philosophy, G\u00fclen promotes \"an Ottoman Empire of the Mind\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fgulen.com/en/home/1324-fgulen-com-english/press/columns/25006-an-ottoman-empire-of-the-mind|title=An Ottoman Empire of the Mind - Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site|last=fgulen.com}}</ref>\n\nDetractors of the movement \"have labeled G\u00fclen community members as secretive missionaries, while those in the Movement and sympathetic observers class it as a [[civil society]] organization\".<ref>David Tittensor, ''The House of Service: The Gulen Movement and Islam's Third Way'' ([[Oxford University Press]], 2014) p. 172.</ref>\n\nCritics have complained that members of the G\u00fclen movement are overly compliant to the directions from its leaders,<ref name=\"Infra note, Berlinski 2012\">Infra note, Berlinski 2012</ref> and G\u00fclen's \"movement is generally perceived by its critics as a religio-political [[cult]]\".<ref>Bulent Temel, Candidacy versus Membership: Is Turkey the Greatest Beneficiary of the European Union\" in ''The Great Catalyst: European Union Project and Lessons from Greece and Turkey'' (ed. B\u00fclent Temel: [[Lexington Books|Lexington]], 2014), p. 375.</ref> The ''Guardian'' editorial board described the movement in 2013 as having \"some of the characteristics of a cult or of an Islamic [[Opus Dei]]\".<ref name=\"GuardianDec2013\">{{cite news | title=Turkey: up from the depths | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/dec/27/turkey-murky-depths | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=27 December 2013 | accessdate = 31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nScholars such as Simon Robinson disagree with the characterization, writing that although \"[t]here is no doubt that G\u00fclen remains a [[charismatic leader]] and that members of the movement hold him in the highest respect\", the movement \"differs markedly  from a cult in several ways\", with G\u00fclen stressing \"the primacy of the scriptures\" and \"the imperative of service\" and consistently avoiding \"attempts to institutionalize power, to perceive him as the source of all truth, or to view him as taking responsibility for the movement\".<ref>Simon Robinson, \"Building Bridges: Gulen Pontifex\" in ''Hizmet Means Service: Perspectives on an Alternative Path within Islam'' (ed. Martin E. Marty: [[University of California Press]], 2015), p. 78.</ref> Zeki Saritoprak says that the view of G\u00fclen as \"a cult leader or a man with ambitions\" is mistaken, and contends that G\u00fclen should be viewed in the context of a long line of Sufi masters who have long been a center of attention \"for their admirers and followers, both historically and currently\".<ref>Zeki Saritoprak, \"Muslim Perception of Fethullah Gulen and the Hizmet Movement: Accommodating or Hindering Modern Turkey?\" in ''Alternative Islamic Discourses and Religious'' (eds. Carool Kersten & Susanne Olsson: [[Ashgate Publishing|Ashgate]], 2013), p. 70.</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2008, the Dutch government investigated the movement's activities in the Netherlands in response to questions from [[Parliament of the Netherlands|Parliament]]. The first two investigations, performed by the [[General Intelligence and Security Service|AIVD]], concluded that the movement did not form a breeding ground for radicalism and found no indications that the movement worked against integration or that it was involved in terrorism or religious radicalization. A further academic study sketched a portrait of a socially conservative, inwardly directed movement with an opaque organizational structure, but said that its members tend to be highly successful in society and thus form no threat to integration.<ref>{{cite news | title = Vormt de G\u00fclen-beweging een bedreiging voor de integratie? | url=https://www.groene.nl/artikel/vormt-de-gulen-beweging-een-bedreiging-voor-de-integratie | newspaper=[[De Groene Amsterdammer]] | date=21 March 2014| accessdate = 24 February 2016 | author = Hassan Bahara}}</ref>\n\nHizmet-affiliated foundations and businesses were estimated as worth $20-to-$50 billion in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=<!----><!---->Kenneth Rapoza<!----> |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2015/12/20/in-sunni-cult-fight-turkey-guns-for-americas-richest-and-most-politically-connected-cleric/#438192fb4f93 |title=In Sunni 'Cult' Fight, Turkey Guns For America's Richest And Most Politically Connected Cleric |publisher=Forbes.com |date= |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Socio-economic activities==\n\n===Schools===\n{{main|G\u00fclen movement schools}}\nThe movement is active in education (kindergarten\u2013university) as well as civic opportunities in other areas such as for interfaith dialogue, humanitarian aid, media, finance, and health.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> Most G\u00fclen Movement schools are private. By 2017 it was estimated 1.2 million Turks have passed through Hizmet schools (including Turkish prime minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan's son in-law, [[Berat Albayrak]]);<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-turkey-coup-gulen-snap-story.html |title=Inside the secretive religious movement that is being blamed for Turkey's attempted coup |publisher=LA Times |date=2016-08-17 |accessdate=2017-09-21}}</ref> and its educational footprint extends to over 160 countries. In 2009 it was estimated that members of the G\u00fclen Movement ran schools around the world in which more than two million students were enrolled.<ref name=\"Behind Turkey's Witch Hunt\">{{Citation | newspaper = News week | url = http://www.newsweek.com/id/197896 | title = Behind Turkey's Witch Hunt| date = 16 May 2009 }}</ref> Estimates of the number of schools and educational institutions vary widely; it appears there are about 300 G\u00fclen Movement schools in Turkey and over 1,000 schools worldwide.<ref>{{Citation  |newspaper = Reuters | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/featuresNews/idUKL0939033920080514?pageNumber=3&virtualBrandChannel=0 | title = Turkish Islamic preacher \u2013 threat or benefactor?|date = 14 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | publisher = Turko kullari | url = http://www.turkokullari.net/index.php?option=com_weblinks&catid=14&Itemid=22 | title = Turkish Schools | access-date = 15 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141006163144/http://www.turkokullari.net/index.php?option=com_weblinks&catid=14&Itemid=22 | archive-date = 6 October 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nBeyond the borders of Turkey, many G\u00fclen schools can be found in countries with large populations of people of Turkish descent. G\u00fclen schools in predominantly non-Turkish Muslim countries provide families with an alternative to [[madrasa]] education.\n\nG\u00fclen schools have received both criticism and praise.<ref name=\"Interfaith Voices: Fethullah G\u00fclen\">{{cite web|url=http://interfaithradio.org/node/491/|title=Interfaith Voices: Fethullah G\u00fclen}}</ref>\n\n====Charter schools in the United States====\n{{see also|G\u00fclen movement schools}}\nIn 2011, it was estimated that over 120 [[charter schools in the United States]] in 25 states were operated by participants of the G\u00fclen movement.<ref name=\"NYtimes2011\">{{cite news | title = Charter Schools Tied to Turkey's Gulen Movement Grow in Texas | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/education/07charter.html?pagewanted=all | date = 6 June 2011 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | author = Stephanie Saul | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160717180813/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/education/07charter.html | archive-date=17 July 2016| access-date = 18 Jul 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/2011-03-20/news/29148147_1_gulen-schools-gulen-followers-charter-schools|title=U.S. charter-school network with Turkish link draws federal attention | work=Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=18 Jul 2016}}</ref> The largest numbers of such schools were in Texas (33 schools, [[Harmony schools]], run by the Cosmos Foundation); Ohio (19 schools, known as Horizon Science Academies and operated by [[Concept Schools]] Inc.); and California (14 schools, operated by the Magnolia Foundation).<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/> The ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' reported at the time that G\u00fclen schools were one of the largest users of [[H1B visa]]s, receiving approval for 684 such visas in 2009.<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/> The ''Inquirer'' reported that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], [[United States Department of Labor|Labor Department]], and [[United States Department of Labor|Education Department]] were investigating whether some charter school employees employed via H1B visas misused funds by kicking back a portion of their salaries to movement groups.<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/> The investigation had no tie to terrorism, and there was \"no indication the American charter network has a religious agenda in the classroom\".<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/>\n\nA ''[[60 Minutes]]'' episode profiled G\u00fclen movement-operated charter schools in the U.S. in May 2012.<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/us-charter-schools-tied-to-powerful-turkish-imam/ | title=U.S. charter schools tied to powerful Turkish imam | publisher=[[CBS News]] | work=[[60 Minutes]] | date=May 13, 2012 | accessdate=January 17, 2018 | author=Stahl, Lesley| authorlink = Lesley Stahl}}</ref> The profile estimated that there were about 130 affiliated schools nationwide, with about 36 Harmony School in Texas, serving \"mostly underprivileged students\" and all emphasizing math and science.<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\"/> The episode said that the schools generally received high marks for the quality of education, but also said that G\u00fclen's reclusive nature \"invites conspiracy theories that he's running Turkey from the Poconos and is bent on global Muslim domination\" and that \"[o]ne statement involves immigration fraud: that the schools are providing work visas for hundreds of G\u00fclen followers from Turkey.\"<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\"/>\n\nProfessor Joshua Hendrick of [[Loyola University Maryland]], who studies the movement, said that G\u00fclen himself \"does not have a direct hand in operating\" the charter schools,<ref name=\"Strum\"/> and it was reported that G\u00fclen has never visited the schools.<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\"/> The Harmony Schools in Texas do not teach religion, and the charter network says that some 7.8% of its teachers are non-Americans.<ref name=\"Strum\"/>\n\nThe ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reported in 2016 that around 150 U.S. charter schools were tied to the G\u00fclen movement, \"ranging from networks in Texas, Illinois and Florida to stand-alone academies in Maryland\".<ref name=\"Strum\">Beckie Strum, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/gulen-movements-charter-schools-may-be-caught-up-in-turkey-u-s-standoff-1468967536 Gulen Movement's Charter Schools May Be Caught Up in Turkey-U.S. Standoff], ''Wall Street Journal'' (July 19, 2016).</ref> The ''Journal'' stated that like other charter schools \"blacks and Hispanics in underserved neighborhoods\" made up the majority of the student body, with common themes including \"an emphasis on math and science education, [[Turkish language]] classes and sponsored trips to Turkey\".<ref name=\"Strum\"/> Hendrick said that in the upheaval following the 2016 Turkish coup attempt, proposed new charter schools and charters up for renewal \"that are run by [[Turkish-Americans]] and are said to be connected with the cleric\" could run into increased opposition, as the Turkish government has sought \"to bring down Mr. Gulen through U.S. charter schools they claim are connected to him\".<ref name=\"Strum\"/>\n\n===Dialogue===\n[[File:Fethullah G\u00fclen visiting Ioannes Paulus II.jpg|thumb|G\u00fclen and [[Pope John Paul II]]]]\n\nThe movement's avowal of interfaith dialogue grew out of G\u00fclen's personal engagement in interfaith dialogue, largely inspired by the example of one of his influences, [[Said Nursi]]. G\u00fclen has met with leaders of other religions, including [[Pope John Paul II]], the [[Bartholomew I of Constantinople|Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I]], and Israeli Sephardic Head Rabbi [[Eliyahu Bakshi-Doron]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Advocate of Dialogue: Fethullah Gulen|first=Ali|last=Unal|date=1 October 2000|publisher=Fountain Pub|isbn=978-0970437013|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/advocateofdialog00aliu}}</ref> G\u00fclen advocates cooperation between followers of different religions as well as those practicing different forms of Islam (such as Sunnism or [[Alevi]]sm).\n\nG\u00fclen's call for interfaith dialogue has influenced three generations of movement followers.<ref name=\"Interfaith Voices: Fethullah G\u00fclen\"/>\n\nG\u00fclen movement participants have founded a number of institutions across the World that promote [[Interfaith dialogue|interfaith]] and [[Interculturalism|intercultural]] dialogue activities. Among these are the ''Journalists and Writers Foundation'' in Istanbul, the ''Rumi Forum'' in Washington and the ''Indialogue Foundation'' in New Delhi.\n\n=== Media ===\nMovement participants have set up a number of media organizations to promote its core values such as love, tolerance, hope, dialogue, activism, mutual acceptance and respect. These media organs include TV stations ([[Samanyolu TV]], [[Mehtap TV]]), ([[Ebru TV]]) (English), the newspapers ''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]'', ''[[Today's Zaman]]'' (English), magazines and journals in Turkish like ''[[Aksiyon]]'', ''[[S\u0131z\u0131nt\u0131]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=G\u00fcnter Seufert|title=Is the Fethullah G\u00fclen Movement Overstretching Itself?|url=https://www.swp-berlin.org/fileadmin/contents/products/research_papers/2014_RP02_srt.pdf|publisher=Stiftung Wissenschaft und Politik|accessdate=2 August 2016|format=Research Paper|date=January 2014}}</ref> ''[[Yeni \u00dcmit]]'', ''[[The Fountain Magazine]]'' (English), ''[[Hira (magazine)|Hira]]'' (Arabic), ''The International [[Cihan News Agency]]'' and the radio station {{Interlanguage link multi|Bur\u00e7 FM|tr}}.\n\n=== Humanitarian aid ===\nThe movement runs charity and humanitarian aid organizations which are transnationally active. The leading one among them is the Istanbul-based [[Kimse Yok Mu Association]] (KYM). KYM organizes charity campaigns to help those in need in different parts of the world. Like any other activities of the G\u00fclen-movement, KYM runs local projects responding to specific needs. KYM holds UN Ecosoc Special status.\n\nAnother charity organization [[Embrace Relief]] was established in [[New Jersey]] and is active in the Americas, Asia and Africa.\n\n=== Professional associations ===\nWhile being both praised and criticized for being market friendly, the G\u00fclen movement has established various professional associations and business networks. Among them Istanbul based [[TUSKON]] is the major non-profit business confederation which states to promote economic solutions as well as social and political ones. Another one called TUCSIAD is based in China, in addition to DTIK's Asia-Pacific Group which supports the G\u00fclen movement outside of Turkey in China, hoping to influence Turkish politics from the outside.\n\n==Criticism==\n{{expand section | small  = no | talksection=Criticism|date=December 2016}}\n[[Fethullah G\u00fclen]]'s and the G\u00fclen movement's views and practices have been discussed in international [[Academic conference|conferences]]. In October 2007 in London a conference was sponsored by the [[University of Birmingham]], the Dialogue Society, the [[Irish School of Ecumenics]], [[Leeds Metropolitan University]], the London Middle East Institute, the [[Middle East Institute]] and the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]], University of London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.fgulen.com/conference-papers/contributions-of-the-gulen-movement |title=Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site - Contributions of the G\u00fclen Movement |publisher=En.fgulen.com |date=27 October 2007 |accessdate=18 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204120035/http://en.fgulen.com/conference-papers/contributions-of-the-gulen-movement |archive-date=4 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Niagara Foundation]] of Chicago, together with several academic institutions, organized \"The G\u00fclen Movement: Paradigms, Projects and Aspirations\" conference, which was held at [[University of Chicago]] on 11\u201313 November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Core Design Production, Web designers; Fatih YAZAR, Yunus USLU, Ismail ABAY |url=http://www.niagarafoundation.org/the-international-gulen-conference-2010-in-chicago-2/ |title=Gulen Movement & Fethullah Gulen |publisher=Niagara Foundation |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Assassination of Andrei Karlov===\n{{main|Assassination of Andrei Karlov}}\nTurkish and Russian officials declared the G\u00fclen movement to be responsible for the [[Assassination of Andrei Karlov|assassination]] of [[List of ambassadors of Russia to Turkey|Russian ambassador]] [[Andrei Karlov]], and accused the movement of aiming to damage [[Russia\u2013Turkey relations]] that had been normalizing since the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Karlov suikast\u0131 davas\u0131 devam ediyor: Alt\u0131nta\u015f'\u0131 FET\u00d6 evinde g\u00f6rd\u00fcm |url=https://tr.sputniknews.com/turkiye/201901081036988171-karlov-altintas-feto-evi/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |publisher=Sputnik T\u00fcrkiye |date=8 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Prosecutors seek life sentence for defendants in Russian ambassador's killing |url=https://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/prosecutors-seek-life-sentence-for-defendants-in-russian-ambassadors-killing-152732 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |publisher=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Borger |first1=Julian |title=Why killing of Russian diplomat may well bring Turkey and Russia closer |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/19/why-killing-of-russian-diplomat-is-likely-to-bring-turkey-and-russia-closer |accessdate=3 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |date=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Designation as a terrorist group==\nG\u00fclen movement is deemed a [[List of designated terrorist groups|designated terrorist group]] by the following countries and international organizations:\n* {{flagicon image|GCC Flag.svg}} [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|}} [[Organization of Islamic Cooperation]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/war-on-terror/2016/10/19/organization-of-islamic-cooperation-declares-feto-a-terrorist-group|title=Organization of Islamic Cooperation declares FET\u00d6 a terrorist group|website=DailySabah}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161019-oic-lists-gulen-network-as-terror-group/|title=OIC lists Gulen network as 'terror group'|date=19 October 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Pakistan}}<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/turkey-welcomes-pakistan-s-ruling-on-feto-terror-group/1350959|title=Turkey welcomes Pakistan\u2019s ruling on FETO terror group|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Northern Cyprus}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/northern-cyprus-designates-feto-as-terror-group/613113|title=Northern Cyprus designates FETO as terror group|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Turkey}}<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n==Political involvement==\nAccording to academic researcher Svante E. Cornell, director of the [[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] & Silk Road Studies Program, \"With only slight exaggeration, the ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) as well as the government it has led could be termed a coalition of religious orders.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/secret-diyanet-report-gauges-threat-posed-turkeys-islamists|title=Secret Diyanet report gauges threat posed by Turkey\u2019s Islamists|website=Ahval|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> \"[...T]he G\u00fclen movement stayed away from electoral politics, focusing instead on increasing its presence in the state bureaucracy. The Hizmet movement\u2019s stated success in this regard would initially make it Erdo\u011fan\u2019s main partner, but also his eventual nemesis.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hudson.org/research/11601-the-naqshbandi-khalidi-order-and-political-islam-in-turkey|title=The Naqshbandi-Khalidi Order and Political Islam in Turkey - by Svante E. Cornell|last=Cornell|first=Svante E.|website=hudson.org|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u20132013 collaboration with the AKP===\nFrom 2002 to 2013, the G\u00fclen movement comprehensively collaborated with the [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP) and [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] in obtaining political power in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/akps-problematic-relations-with-gulen.aspx?pageID=449&nID=115586&NewsCatID=409|title=AKP's problematic relations with G\u00fclen|date=17 July 2017|publisher=Hurriyet Daily News.}}</ref>\n\nQuestions have arisen about the G\u00fclen movement's possible involvement in the ongoing [[Ergenekon (allegation)|Ergenekon investigation]],<ref name=Jenkins/> which critics have characterized as \"a pretext\" by the government \"to neutralize dissidents\" in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagaptay.com/5593/ergenekon-behind-turkey-witch-hunt|title=Behind Turkey's Witch Hunt|first=Soner|last=Cagaptay}}</ref> In March 2011, seven Turkish journalists were arrested, including [[Ahmet \u015e\u0131k]], who had been writing a book, \"Imamin Ordusu\" (''[[The Imam's Army]]''),<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/05/turkey-censorship-ahmet-sik-perrier Turkish authorities launch raids to censor book before publication] in the Guardian of 5 April 2011; accessed on 11 April 2011</ref> which states that the G\u00fclen movement has infiltrated the country's security forces. As \u015e\u0131k was taken into police custody, he shouted, \"Whoever touches it [the movement] gets burned!\".<ref>{{cite news |  url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/04/world/europe/04turkey.htmll?_r=1%20 | work=The New York Times | first=\u015eebnem | last=Arsu | title=7 More Journalists Detained in Turkey | date=3 March 2011}}</ref> Upon his arrest, drafts of the book were confiscated and its possession was banned. \u015e\u0131k has also been charged with being part of the stated Ergenekon plot, despite being an investigator of the plot before his arrest.<ref>Details can be found in English on the site of [http://www.tuerkeiforum.net/enw/index.php/Ahmet_%C5%9E%C4%B1k:_The_Army_of_the_Imam the Democratic Turkey Forum]; accessed on 5 April 2001. In the footnotes to translated passages of the book you can find other works on the subject.</ref>\n\nIn a reply, Abdullah Bozkurt, from the G\u00fclen movement newspaper ''[[Today's Zaman]]'', said Ahmet \u015e\u0131k was not being an investigative journalist conducting \"independent research\", but was hatching \"a plot designed and put into action by the terrorist network itself\".<ref>The alleged terrorist network is the [[Ergenekon (organization)|Ergenekon organization]]; see [http://www.todayszaman.com/columnist-239479-ergenekon-gulen-and-media-freedom.html Article of 29 March 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201055315/http://www.todayszaman.com/columnist-239479-ergenekon-gulen-and-media-freedom.html |date=1 February 2016 }}; accessed on 5 April 2011</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Gareth H. Jenkins]], a Senior Fellow of the [[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute & Silk Road Studies Joint Center]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]]:\n{{quote|From the outset, the pro-AKP media, particularly the newspapers and television channels run by the G\u00fclen Movement such as ''Zaman'', ''Today's Zaman'' and Samanyolu TV, have vigorously supported the Ergenekon investigation. This has included the illegal publication of \"evidence\" collected by the investigators before it has been presented in court, misrepresentations and distortions of the content of the indictments and smear campaigns against both the accused and anyone who questions the conduct of the investigations.\n\nThere have long been allegations that not only the media coverage but also the Ergenekon investigation itself is being run by G\u00fclen's supporters. In August 2010, [[Hanefi Avc\u0131]], a right-wing police chief who had once been sympathetic to the G\u00fclen Movement, published a book in which he alleged that a network of G\u00fclen's supporters in the police were manipulating judicial processes and fixing internal appointments and promotions. On September 28, 2010, two days before he was due to give a press conference to present documentary evidence to support his allegations, Avc\u0131 was arrested and charged with membership of an extremist leftist organization. On March 14, 2011, Avc\u0131 was also formally charged with being a member of the alleged Ergenekon gang.<ref name=Jenkins>{{cite web |url=http://www.silkroadstudies.org/new/inside/turkey/2011/110404B.html |title=Central Asia-Caucasus Institute and Silk Road Studies Program |publisher=Silkroadstudies.org |accessdate=18 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427163058/http://www.silkroadstudies.org/new/inside/turkey/2011/110404B.html |archivedate=27 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nThe G\u00fclen movement has also been implicated in what the opposition [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP) - and after 2013 also President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] - have said were illegal court decisions against members of the [[Turkish military]], including many during the Ergenekon investigation.<ref name=\"NYtimes2-27-2014\">{{cite news | title = Turkish Leader Disowns Trials That Helped Him Tame Military | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/world/europe/turkish-leader-disowns-trials-that-helped-him-tame-military.html?hpw&rref=world | last = Arango | first = Tim | date = 26 February 2014 | accessdate = 27 February 2014 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | quote = In 2005, years before the trials, a man affiliated with the Gulen movement approached Eric S. Edelman, then the American ambassador, at a party in Istanbul and handed him an envelope containing a handwritten document that supposedly laid out a plan for an imminent coup. But as Edelman recounted, he gave the documents to his colleagues and they were determined to be forgeries. }}</ref>\n\n===2013 AKP corruption scandal===\n{{Main|2013 corruption scandal in Turkey}}\nOn 17 December 2013, an [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|investigation]] into stated corrupt practices by several bureaucrats, ministers, mayors, and family members of the ruling [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP) of Turkey was uncovered, resulting in widespread protests and calls for the resignation of the government led by Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]].<ref name=\"Journal-28Dec2013\"/><ref name=\"Hurriyet2013\"/> Due to the high level of political influence by the G\u00fclen movement in Turkey, it is rumored to be facilitated by the movement's influence on the Turkish police force and the judiciary,<ref name=\"BBCprofile-Dec2013\"/> the investigation was said to be a result of a break in previously friendly relations between the Islamist-rooted government and the movement.<ref name=\"csmonitor.com\"/>\n\nPresident [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]] and the [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]] (the ruling party of Turkey) have targeted the movement since December 2013. Immediately after the [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|corruption statements]], the government subjugated the judiciary, media and civil society which were critical of the government's authoritarian trend in recent years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/special-report/21689871-under-recep-tayip-erdogan-and-his-ak-party-turkey-has-become-richer-and-more-confident|title=Erdogan\u2019s new sultanate|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/under-erdogan-turkey-is-moving-away-from-democracy/article29281164/|title=Under Erdogan, Turkey is moving away from democracy|website=The Globe and Mail|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/turkey/12195534/EU-Turkey-deal-Recep-Tayyip-Erdogan-Where-did-it-all-go-wrong-for-Turkey.html|title=Where did it all go wrong for Turkey?|website=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=25 April 2016|date=17 March 2016|last1=Akkoc|first1=Raziye}}</ref> After the corruption statements surfaced, Erdogan labelled it as a \"civilian coup\" against his government. Since then, Erdogan has shuffled, dismissed or jailed hundreds of police officers, judges, prosecutors and journalists in the name of fighting against a \"Parallel State\" within the Turkish state.\n\n===Crackdown against the G\u00fclen movement from 2014===\n{{main|Turkish government\u2013G\u00fclen movement conflict}}\n\nOn 14 December 2014 Turkish police arrested more than two dozen senior journalists and media executives connected with the G\u00fclen movement on various charges.\n\nA statement by the [[US State Department]] cautioned Turkey not to violate its \"own democratic foundations\" while drawing attention to raids against media outlets \"openly critical of the current Turkish government\".<ref>{{cite news|title=In Turkey, police arrest journalists and executives|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/12/14/world/europe/turkey-media-crackdown/|accessdate=19 December 2014|newspaper=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Court rules for release of Zaman chief editor, Samanyolu manager arrested|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/national_court-rules-for-release-of-zaman-chief-editor-samanyolu-manager-arrested_367441.html|accessdate=19 December 2014|newspaper=Today's Zaman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219133859/http://www.todayszaman.com/national_court-rules-for-release-of-zaman-chief-editor-samanyolu-manager-arrested_367441.html|archivedate=19 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy|EU Foreign Affairs]] chief [[Federica Mogherini]] and [[European Commissioner for Enlargement and European Neighbourhood Policy|EU Enlargement]] Commissioner [[Johannes Hahn]] said that the arrests went \"against European values\" and \"are incompatible with the freedom of media, which is a core principle of democracy\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey media arrests: Mogherini leads EU criticism|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30471996|accessdate=19 December 2014|newspaper=BBC}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2015, Turkish police launched raids in [[Ankara]] and three other cities, detaining some 20 people suspected of illegally eavesdropping on President Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan and other senior officials. The suspects are linked to Turkey's telecommunications authority and to its scientific and technological research center [[TUBITAK]]. Local media said the move was aimed at the \"parallel structure\" \u2014 the term Erdogan uses to refer to G\u00fclen's supporters in the judiciary, police and other institutions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey arrests dozens suspected of eavesdropping on president|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/1/20/turkey-wiretappingarrests.html|accessdate=20 January 2015| newspaper=Aljazeera}}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish government took over the G\u00fclenist ''Zaman Daily'', on 4 March 2016. Turkish police entered the Zaman's headquarters by force and fired tear gas at the protesting journalists and civilians. Hundreds of protestors were injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2016/03/turkey-fears-of-zaman-newspaper-takeover/|title=Turkey: Zaman newspaper taken over as government steamrolls press freedom|website=amnesty.org|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/05/world/middleeast/recep-tayyip-erdogan-government-seizes-zaman-newspaper.html|title=Turkey Seizes Newspaper, Zaman, as Press Crackdown Continues|last=Timur|first=Safak|date=4 March 2016|last2=Arango|first2=Tim|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref> In his efforts to eradicate the movement within the country the [[Turkish National Security Council]] has identified the movement as the \"G\u00fclenist Terror Organisation\" (\"Fethullah\u00e7\u0131 Ter\u00f6r \u00d6rg\u00fct\u00fc\", FET\u00d6).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trtworld.com/in-depth/turkey-challenged-by-terror-in-2015-17588|title=Turkey challenged by terror in 2015|website=TRT World|language=tr-TR|access-date=6 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203060054/http://www.trtworld.com/in-depth/turkey-challenged-by-terror-in-2015-17588|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The government has also been targeting individuals and businessmen who have supported the movement's organizations and activities.\n\n===Purge of movement in Turkey after July 2016===\n{{see also|Turkish government\u2013G\u00fclen movement conflict|2016\u201317 purges in Turkey}}\n\nIn reaction to the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|15 July 2016 coup attempt]], led by a military faction operating outside the chain of command, the Turkish government quickly stated the coup's leader to be G\u00fclen. In following days and weeks, a massive crackdown affected all entities affiliated to the G\u00fclen movements, from individuals to businesses, newspapers to schools and universities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Ahmet Erdi|date=2019-02-26|title=An alternative reading of religion and authoritarianism: the new logic between religion and state in the AKP's New Turkey|journal=Southeast European and Black Sea Studies|volume=0|pages=79\u201398|doi=10.1080/14683857.2019.1576370|issn=1468-3857}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[assassination of Andrey Karlov]], the Turkish government was reportedly investigating the assassin's links to the \"G\u00fclenist Terrorist Organisation\" (FET\u00d6); in a speech, [[President of Turkey|Turkish President]] [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] said that the perpetrator was a member of FET\u00d6.<ref name=\"ABCNews20Dec\">{{cite news|title=Who was the Ankara assassin?|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-12-20/ankara-russian-ambassador-shooting-who-is-mevlut-mert-aydintas/8135510|work=ABC News|date=20 December 2016|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/cumhurbaskani-erdogan-ankara-da-siyaset-2365707/|title=Erdo\u011fan resmen a\u00e7\u0131klad\u0131: Suikast\u00e7\u0131 FET\u00d6 mensubu|trans-title=Erdo\u011fan officially announces: Assassin is FET\u00d6 member|work=Milliyet Haber|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Extraditions to Turkey; political asylums granted ===\n{{as of|2020}}, Turkey had successfully pressured a number of countries, especially those in Africa and the [[former Soviet Union]], to extradite \nover 80 alleged g\u00fclenists to Turkey.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkey-gathered-information-in-the-u-s-against-its-critics-11573654247?reflink=share_mobilewebshare#_=_</ref><ref>https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/broken-gulen-movement-faces-existential-crisis</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was reported that [[Interpol]] had denied Turkey's appeals of the agency's rejections of Turkey's [[red notice]] requests regarding 464 fugitives, citing Interpol's legal definition of the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] as not [[terrorism]] but a failed military [[putsch]].<ref>https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/turkey-poised-rescind-fethullah-gulens-citizenship</ref>\n\nIn 2018, bout 25,000 Turkish [[political asylum|asylum]] requests were filed by alleged g\u00fclenists in the European Union (a rise of 50 per cent from 2017), with Germany's share 10,000 and Greece's about 5,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/11/22/turks-persecuted-over-alleged-links-to-the-gulen-movement-find-a-safe-haven-in-greece|title=Greece: A safe haven for Turks threatened over G\u00fclen movement links|first=Katy|last=Dartford|date=22 November 2019|website=euronews}}</ref> Within the U.S., according to news reports, a number of G\u00fclenists successfully receiving political asylum status are resettled in New Jersey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/10/17/turkish-gulen-supporters-fleeing-crackdown-seek-asylum-new-jersey/4006257002/|title=Labeled terrorists in their homeland, hundreds of Turks seek asylum in New Jersey|first=Hannan|last=Adely|website=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n* 1941&nbsp;\u2013 [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]] is born in Korucuk, near [[Erzurum]], Turkey\n* 1950s&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen's first meeting with people from the [[Nur Movement]]<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Unal & Williams|editor1-first=Ali & Alphonse|title=Advocate of Dialogue: Fethullah Gulen|date=2000|publisher=The Fountain|location=Fairfax, VA|page=15}}</ref>\n* 1960&nbsp;\u2013 death of [[Said Nurs\u00ee]]<ref>Ian Markham, Engaging with Bediuzzaman Said Nursi: A Model of Interfaith Dialogue, p 4. {{ISBN|0754669319}}</ref>\n* 1960s&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen begins attracting disciples while a state preacher in [[Izmir]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1971&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen arrested for a stated crime of organizing and/or participating in activities to change the basis of the constitutional system but is released seven months later.{{Citation needed | date=August 2010}}\n* late 1970s&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen establishes himself independently of other Nurju organizations; first ''\u0131\u015f\u0131k evleri'' (\"houses of light\", i.e., student residences){{Citation needed|date=March 2013}} established{{Citation needed | date=August 2010}}\n* 1978&nbsp;\u2013 First ''dershane'' (study center for university exams) opens{{Citation needed | date=August 2010}}\n* 1979&nbsp;\u2013 Science journal ''S\u0131z\u0131nt\u0131'' begins publication<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tr.fgulen.com/content/view/10747/3/|title=Son Karakol|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827033058/http://tr.fgulen.com/content/view/10747/3/|archivedate=27 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 1981&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen retires{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1982&nbsp;\u2013 First \"G\u00fclen school\" opens.<ref name=\"turkhaber16042010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.haberturk.com/polemik/haber/515415-100-soruda-fethullah-gulen-ve-hareketi |title= \"100 soruda Fethullah G\u00fclen ve Hareketi\" (Gulen and its movement in 100 questions) |publisher= HaberTurk |date= 16 April 2010 |accessdate= 18 April 2014}}</ref>\n* 1986&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]'', a daily newspaper in Turkey,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medyatava.com/tiraj/ |title=Tiraj |publisher=Medyatava |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref> begins publication, later becoming one of Turkey's top selling newspapers\n* 1988\u20131991&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen gives lectures in Istanbul and Izmir{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1991&nbsp;\u2013 Fall of Soviet Union permits establishment of G\u00fclen schools in [[Central Asia]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1994&nbsp;\u2013 The (Turkish) Journalists and Writers Foundation (Gazeteciler ve Yazarlar Vakfi) established, with G\u00fclen as honorary president<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fuchs Ebaugh|first1=Helen Rose|title=The Gulen Movement: A Sociological Analysis of a Civic Movement Rooted in Moderate Islam|publisher=Springer|page=89|year=2009}}</ref>\n* 1996&nbsp;\u2013 Creation of [[Bank Asya|Asya Finans]] (investment bank aimed at former Soviet Central Asia), with [[Tansu \u00c7iller]] as an investor{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1998&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen meets with [[Pope John Paul II]] in the Vatican<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Salih|first1=Yucel|title=Muslim-Christian Dialogue: Nostra Aetated and Fethullah Gulen's Philosophy of Dialogue|journal=Australian eJournal of Theology|date=Dec 2013|page=200}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Michel S.J.|first1=Thomas|title=\"Fethullah Gulen and Pope John Paul II: \"Two Frontrunners for Peace\"|journal=Dialogue Asia-Pacific|date=Oct\u2013Dec 2007|issue=14|pages=6\u20138}}</ref>\n* 1999&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen movement schools in [[Tashkent]] closed by Uzbekistan government after a rift between Turkish and Uzbek governments{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1999&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen emigrates to [[Pennsylvania]] after the Turkish government charges him with attempting to set up an [[Islamism|Islamist]] state in Turkey<ref name=\"Journal-28Dec2013\"/>\n* 2004&nbsp;\u2013 Establishment of Niagara Foundation<ref>{{cite web|author1=Niagara Foundation|title=History Niagara Foundation|url=http://www.niagarafoundation.org/niagara/history/|website=Niagara Foundation|quote=The Niagara Foundation was created in 2004 by a group of Turkish-American businessmen and educators in order to realize the vision of their spiritual leader, Fethullah Gulen, himself a Turkish Muslim scholar and poet, as well as an educational and humanitarian activist. Today the Niagara Foundation is active in nine Midwestern states with 22 branches.}}</ref>\n* 2004&nbsp;\u2013 Establishment of ''[[Kimse Yok Mu]]'' (Is Anybody There?), a charitable organization;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Michel, S.J.|first1=Thomas|title=Fighting Poverty with Kimse Yok Mu|url=http://fgulen.com/en/gulen-movement/conference-papers/gulen-conference-in-washington/26437-fighting-poverty-with-kimse-yok-mu?hitcount=0|website=Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site.}}</ref> 2010, receives \"special\" NGO status with United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esango.un.org/civilsociety/simpleSearch.do?method=search&searchTypeRedef=simpleSearch&sessionCheck=false&searchType=simpleSearch&organizationNamee=kimse+yok+mu&Submit=Go|title=United Nations Search results for CSos|website=esango.un.org}}</ref>\n* 2005&nbsp;\u2013 Establishment of [[TUSKON]] ([[Turkish Confederation of Businessmen and Industrialists]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuskon.org/?p=content&cl=kurumsal&l=kurumsal |title=Hakk\u0131nda |publisher=TUSKON |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n* 2012&nbsp;\u2013 Journalists and Writers Foundation ([[:tr:Gazeteciler ve Yazarlar Vakf\u0131|Gazeteciler ve Yazarlar Vakfi]]) receives \"general consultative status\" as a Non-Governmental Organization of the Economic and Social Council ([[United Nations Economic and Social Council|ECOSOC]]) of the United Nations.<ref>{{cite web|author1=United Nations Economic and Social Council|title=List of non-governmental organizations in consultative status with the Economic and Social Council as of 1 September 2013|url=http://esango.un.org/civilsociety/documents/E_2013_INF_6.pdf|website=United Nations Economic and Social Council|page=3|date=3 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Common terms==\nExpressions used within the G\u00fclen movement include:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fgulen.com/en/home/1346-fgulen-com-english/conference-papers/gulen-conference-in-indonesia/27013-gulens-educational-philosophy-striving-for-the-golden-generation-of-muslims|title=G\u00fclen's Educational Philosophy: Striving for the Golden Generation of Muslims - Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site|first=Fethullah|last=G\u00fclen|website=fgulen.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ahvalnews.com/gulenists/ally-enemy-1-gulen-movement-1|title=The 'ally' to 'enemy # 1': G\u00fclen Movement (1) - Ahval}}</ref>\n;''[[Risale-i Nur]]''\n:[[Sufism]]-influenced [[Quran]]ic [[exegesis]] written 1910s\u201350s by [[Said Nursi]] (1877\u20131960). Title of this multi-volume compilation translates to \"Treatise of Light\"\n\n;''[[Bedi\u00fczzaman]]''\n: Honorific name, meaning \"light or wonder of time,\" used to refer to Nursi (See above).<ref>http://www.bediuzzamansaidnursi.org/en/icerik/brief-introduction-life-and-thought-bediuzzaman-said-nursi</ref>\n\n;''Nurcu''\n:[Followers] \"of Nursi\". Many of these, but not all, participate in the G\u00fclen movement.\n\n;''[[Hodjaefendi]]''\n: Honorific name, meaning \"respected teacher,\" used to refer to G\u00fclen.<ref>https://fgulen.com/en/gulen-movement/47137-what-does-hodjaefendi-mean</ref>\n\n;''\u015eakird''\n: \"Disciple\". A full participant in the movement.\n\n;''A\u011fabey''\n: \"Elder brother\". Appellation used, within movement etiquette, for any movement brethren of greater age than oneself.\n\n;''Abla''\n: \"Sister\". A female participant.\n\n;''sohbet''\n:\"Discussion\". The movement's Islamic-spirituality study groups.\n\n;''isti\u015fare''\n:\"Consultation\". Pastoral counseling, as, for example, that of a student collective residing in a dorm with the dorm's volunteer lay imam. Any similar consultation anywhere up the organizational ladder.\n\n;''esnaf''\n:\"Artisan\". A tradesman capable of philanthropic support of the movement's societal aims\n\n;''dost''\n:\"Friend\". A person sympathetic to the societal aims of the movement. Need not be Muslim\n\n;''m\u00fcspet''\n:\"Positive\". Those able to invest in, donate to, or provide executive services for independent businesses or foundations owned by collections of individuals participating in the movement.\n\n;''ehl-i d\u00fcnya''\n:\"People of the world\" (secular society).\n\n;''himmet''\n:[[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman]]- (pre-Kemalist) Turkish word for \"from a strong spiritual determination and aspiration\" (a term is used in Sufism). Charitable donations toward societal aims of the movement.\n\n;''Hizmet''\n:\" Service\" Another term for the movement.\n\n;''[[cemaat]]\n:\"Fellow local members in the movement\" (or, the movement as a whole). Turkish form of Arabic ''[[Jamiya]]'' ('congregation') and related to Turkish ''cuma'' ('Friday') the day of congregational prayers (Arabic: ''[[Jumu'ah]]'').\n\n;''I\u015f\u0131k evler''\n:\"Light houses\". Informal appellation for communal houses such as students' dorms.\n\n;''\u0130lgilenmek''\n:\"[To] be interested in [someone]\". An individual akin to a godfather who encourages piety, hard work, service, etc.\n\n;''Kafalamak''\n:\"Head\" (verb). Occasional humorous term for someone such as the above (with the idiomatic meaning: \"[to] convince [someone of something]\")\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Islam|Turkey}}\n* [[Interfaith dialogue]]\n* [[Fethullah Gulen]]\n* [[Sunni Islam]]\n* [[Sufism]]\n\n==Further information==\n* {{cite book|url = https://uofupress.lib.utah.edu/turkeys-july-15th-coup/|author = M Hakan Yavuz & Bayram Balci|year = 2018|title = Turkey's July 15th Coup: What Happened and Why|series = Utah Series in Middle East Studies|publisher = [[University of Utah Press]]|isbn = 9781607816065}}\n* {{cite book|editors = [http://www.fountainmagazine.com/ ''The Fountain: Of Life, Knowledge, and Belief'']|url = https://fgulen.com/en/what-went-wrong-with-turkey|date = 2017|title = What Went Wrong with Turkey? ''(special issue)''|type = bi-monthly journal of interfaith dialogue, intercultural studies, art, and history|publisher= Blue Dome Press (affiliated with the [[Hizmet]] movement)|place = [[Clifton, New Jersey]]|version = Engl. lang.|asin = B0032FPQKE}}\n* {{cite book|author = Faruk Mercan|publisher = Blue Dome Press|year = 2017|title = No Return from Democracy: A Survey of Interviews with Fethullah Gulen|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5jAgMQAACAAJ&dq=|isbn = 978-1682060179}}\n* {{cite book|title = Toward an Islamic Enlightenment: The G\u00fclen Movement|author = M. Hakan Yavuz|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2013|url = https://books.google.com/?id=qsTdpmviIQ4C|isbn = 9780199927999}}\n* {{cite journal|url = http://www.ecfr.eu/publications/summary/the_good_the_bad_and_the_gulenists7131 |title = The good, the bad and the G\u00fclenists: The Role of the Gulen Movement in Turkey's Coup Attempt|publisher = ecfr.eu|journal = [[European Council on Foreign Relations]]|author = Asli Ayd\u0131nta\u015fba\u015f|date = September 2016|isbn = 978-1-910118-88-7}}\n* {{cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hc7QAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2014|title = The House of Service: The G\u00fclen Movement and Islam's Third Way|isbn = 9780199336418|author = David Tittensor}}\n* {{cite web |title= G\u00fclen movement: Creating an elite to lead the state |date= November 26, 2017 |author= Timur Tin\u00e7url |url= https://www.dandc.eu/en/article/turkish-guelen-movement-expanding-worldwide-opinions-differ-reasons-why |publisher= [[D+C Development and Cooperation]]}}\n* {{cite web|title = Creating an elite to lead the state: The Gulen movement in Turkey|url = http://en.qantara.de/node/29833|publisher = [[Qantara.de]]|author = Timur Tin\u00e7|date = December 27, 2017}}\n* {{cite journal|url = https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2017/12/turkey-finally-some-gulenists-speak-out.html|title = Gulenists Speak Out at Last|author = Mustafa Akyol|date = December 7, 2017|journal = [[Al-Monitor]]|postscript = &nbsp;(a review of former Hizmet participants' scholarly commentary about the movement)}}\n* {{cite news|url =https://ahvalnews.com/turkey/loathed-hunted-down-gulen-movement-finished-turkey |publisher = [[Ahval]]|date = February 28, 2018|title = Loathed, hunted down, G\u00fclen Movement finished in Turkey|author = Nick Ashdown}}\n* {{cite web|author = Ali Moore |publisher = [[Jakarta Post]]|title = The rise, fall and future of Turkey's G\u00fclen movement|date = October 31, 2019|type = audio of roundtable discussion with academics David Tittensor & Tezcan G\u00fcm\u00fc\u015f at [[University of Melbourne]]'s Asia Institute|url = https://www.thejakartapost.com/multimedia/2019/10/14/the-rise-fall-and-future-of-turkey-s-gulen-movement.html}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=https://fgulen.com/}}\n* [http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/guelen-movement-accused-of-being-a-sect-a-848763.html ''Altruistic Society or Sect? The Shadowy World of the Islamic G\u00fclen Movement'']\n* {{cite news|newspaper = [[USA Today]]|url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/10/17/turkish-gulen-supporters-fleeing-crackdown-seek-asylum-new-jersey/4006257002/|title = Labeled terrorists in their homeland, hundreds of Turks seek asylum in New Jersey|author = Hannan Adely|date = October 17, 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gulen Movement}}\n[[Category:G\u00fclen movement| ]]\n[[Category:Islam and politics]]\n[[Category:Islamism in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Sunni Islamic branches]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Turkey]]\n[[Category:Political movements in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Sufi organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Transnational civic movement}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox militant organization\n| name             = G\u00fclen movement\n| image            =\n| image_border     =\n| alt              =\n|caption           =  [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]] at home in Saylorsburg, Pennsylvania, in 2018\n| native_name      = G\u00fclen hareketi\n| native_name_lang = tr\n| other_name       = {{plainlist|\n* the ''hizmet''\n* \"[the] ''[[cemaat]]''\"}}\n| country          = [[Turkey]], [[United States]], [[European Union]]\n| language         =\n| leader_title     =\n| leader_name      = [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]]\n| main_organ       =\n| parent_organization =\n| affiliations     =\n| num_staff        =\n| num_volunteers   =\n| headquarters     =\n| location         =\n| coords           =\n| foundation       =\n| dissolved        =\n| merger           =\n| split            =\n| predecessor      =\n| merged           =\n| successor        =\n| motives          =\n| area             =  Worldwide\n| region_served    =\n| membership       =\n| ideology         = '''G\u00fclenism'''\n* [[Islamic democracy]]\n* [[Liberalism and progressivism within Islam|Progressive Islam]]\n* [[Islamism]] ([[moderate]])\n* [[Conservative democracy]]\n* [[Interfaith dialogue]]\n| position         =\n| status           =\n* Collection of schools, associations and media outlets with no centralised executive leadership\n* Banned by [[Republic of Turkey]]\n| size             = Formerly 200,000 to 4 million<br>Presently unknown.\n70,000 in [[Germany]] (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/germany-signals-tougher-stance-on-feto/1172010|title=Germany signals tougher stance on FETO|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n| revenue          =\n| financing        =\n| budget           =\n| flag             =\n| website          =\n* [https://fgulen.com/en/gulen-movement/questions-and-answers FGulen.com: Gulen movement questions and answers]\n* [https://afsv.org/ afsv.org]\n|designated_as_terror_group_by={{PAK}}<br />{{TUR}}<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus.svg}} [[Northern Cyprus|Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]]<br />{{flagicon image|GCC Flag.svg}} [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]<br />{{flagicon image|}} [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]]}}{{quote box|width = 34%|quote = \"''Dar al-hizmet'' is a relatively new term used to describe a new Islamic worldview that does not divide the globe between Islamic and un-Islamic spheres but regards the whole world as the locus of serving humanity at large and through this service attaining the good pleasure of God. Thus, ''dar al-hizmet'' as an Islamic term does not have its basis in geopolitical calculations and considerations[...]but has its basis in the social and spiritual concepts of ''ihsan'' (God-consciouness), ''di\u011fergaml\u0131k'' (altruism) and ultimately ''hizmet'' (service). Thus, ''dar al-hizmet'' has the potential to mobilise Muslims towards becoming more socially responsible in their communities and their host countries, regardless of the dominant faith or ideology, or the form of governance where they live.\"|source=[https://www.hizmetstudies.org/commentary/dar-al-hizmet-abode-of-service-in-a-globalized-world/ \"''Dar al-Hizmet'' &ndash; Abode of Service in a Globalized World],\" Will Taylor, Center for Hizmet Studies (London), January 7, 2015<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hizmetstudies.org/commentary/dar-al-hizmet-abode-of-service-in-a-globalized-world/ |title = Dar al-Hizmet / Abode of Service in a Globalized World}}</ref>}}\n\nThe '''G\u00fclen movement''' ({{lang-tr|G\u00fclen hareketi}}), referred as '''FETO''' by the current [[Government of Turkey]] and as '''Hizmet''' by its participants, is a transnational [[social movement|socially-conscious]] Islamic movement with political overtones, inspired by the writings and preachings of [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]], a Turkish [[Islam]]ic preacher who has lived in the [[United States]] since 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/fethullah-gulens-pennsylvania-home-2013-12|title=Fethullah G\u00fclen's Pennsylvania Home - Business Insider|author=Adam Taylor|date=18 December 2013|work=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/vg/video-gallery/what-is-feto-an-overview-of-the-terrorist-organization/0|title=Anadolu Agency|website=Anadolu Agency}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/what-is-feto--8654|title=What is FETO?}}</ref> The movement is [[List of designated terrorist groups|designated as a terrorist organization]] by [[Turkey]],<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-gulen-idUSKCN0YM167|title=Turkey officially designates Gulen religious group as terrorists|date=31 May 2016|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> [[Pakistan]],<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/pakistanis-laud-landmark-verdict-on-feto-terror-group-/1351082|title=Pakistanis laud \u2018landmark\u2019 verdict on FETO terror group|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref> and the [[Gulf Cooperation Council|GCC]].<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161014-gcc-declare-feto-a-terrorist-organisation/|title=GCC declare Gulen group a 'terrorist organisation'|date=14 October 2016}}</ref> However, their purported terror activities are not recognized as such by the [[United States]], nor the [[European Union]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turkeypurge.com/|title=Turkey Purge &#124; Monitoring human rights abuses in Turkey's post-coup crackdown}}</ref> Owing to the outlawed status of the G\u00fclen movement in Turkey, some observers refer to the movement's volunteers who are Turkish Muslims as effectively a sub-[[Islamic schools and branches|sect of Sunni Islam]];<ref>{{cite web|author=By THE NEW YORK TIMESMARCH 9, 2018 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/09/world/europe/turkey-journalists-prison-terrorism.html |title=Turkey Sentences 24 Journalists to Prison, Claiming Terrorism Ties - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=2018-03-09 |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/over-half-million-suspected-gulenists-investigated-coup |title=Over half a million suspected G\u00fclenists investigated since coup &#124; Ahval |publisher=Ahvalnews.com |date=2018-03-16 |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=<!----><!---->Kenneth Rapoza<!----> |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2015/12/20/in-sunni-cult-fight-turkey-guns-for-americas-richest-and-most-politically-connected-cleric/ |title=In Sunni 'Cult' Fight, Turkey Guns For America's Richest And Most Politically Connected Cleric |publisher=Forbes.com |date= |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref> these volunteers generally hold their religious tenets as generically Turkish [[Sunni Islam]]. The movement also includes participants from other nationalities and religious affiliations.\n\nA U.S.-based umbrella foundation which is affiliated with the movement is the [[Alliance for Shared Values]]. The movement has attracted supporters and drawn the attention of critics in Turkey, [[Central Asia]], and other parts of the world. It is active in education and operates private schools and universities in over 180 countries. It has initiated forums for interfaith dialogue. It has substantial investments in media, finance, and for-profit health clinics.<ref name=ABC>{{cite web |url= http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/encounter/turkey-gallipoli-gulen-capitalism/4853162#transcript|title= The Turkish exception: Gallipoli, G\u00fclen, and capitalism|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 31 August 2013|website= Australia's ABC|publisher= Radio National|accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"jbwhite\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJ8S_wG06MEC|title=Islamist Mobilization in Turkey: A Study in Vernacular Politics|first=Jenny Barbara|last=White|date=1 January 2002|publisher=University of Washington Press|via=Google Books|isbn=9780295982236}}</ref> Despite its teachings which are stated conservative even in Turkey, some have praised the movement as a pacifist, modern-oriented version of Islam, and an alternative to more extreme schools of Islam such as [[Salafism]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21578113-muslim-cleric-america-wields-surprising-political-power-turkey-gulenists-fight-back|title=The Gulenists fight back|journal=The Economist|date=18 May 2013}}</ref> But it has also been reported of having \"global, apocalyptic ambition\", a \"cultish hierarchy\"<ref name=\"NYT-23-7-16\">{{cite news|last1=Akyol|first1=Mustafa|title=Who Was Behind the Coup Attempt in Turkey?|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/22/opinion/who-was-behind-the-coup-attempt-in-turkey.html?|accessdate=23 July 2016|agency=New York Times|date=July 22, 2016}}</ref> and of being a secretive [[Islamic sect]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21703186-president-erdogan-blames-gulenists-putsch-and-has-launched-massive-purges-most-turks|title=Most Turks believe a secretive Muslim sect was behind the failed coup|journal=The Economist|date=28 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/guelen-movement-accused-of-being-a-sect-a-848763.html|title=Altruistic Society or Sect? The Shadowy World of the Islamic G\u00fclen Movement - SPIEGEL ONLINE - International|first=SPIEGEL ONLINE, Hamburg|last=Germany|newspaper=Spiegel Online|date=8 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe G\u00fclen movement is a former ally of the Turkish [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP). When the AKP came to [[Government of Turkey|power]] in 2002 the two formed, despite their differences, a tactical alliance against military tutelage and the [[Secularism in Turkey|Turkish secular]] elite.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-to-add-gulen-movement-to-list-of-terror-groups-president-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=99762&NewsCatID=338|title=Turkey to add G\u00fclen movement to list of terror groups: President|last=|first=|date=27 May 2016|work=Hurriyet Daily News|access-date=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.turkishminute.com/2016/06/03/eu-expresses-concern-declaration-gulen-movement-terrorist-without-due-process/|title=EU expresses concern over declaration of G\u00fclen movement as terrorist without due process|last=|first=|date=3 June 2016|work=Turkish Minute|access-date=|via=}}</ref> It was through this alliance that the AKP had accomplished an unprecedented feat in Turkish republican history by securing national electoral victories sufficient to form three consecutive majority governments in 2002, 2007, and 2011. The G\u00fclen movement gained influence on the Turkish police force and the judiciary during its alliance with conservative President Erdo\u011fan, which saw hundreds of G\u00fclen supporters appointed to positions within the Turkish government.<ref>{{cite news |title= Turkey as a model of democracy and Islam |url= https://www.opendemocracy.net/arab-awakening/sami-zubaida/turkey-as-model-of-democracy-and-islam |date= 30 May 2011 | accessdate = 22 September 2016 }}</ref> Once the old establishment was defeated around 2010 to 2011 disagreements emerged between the AKP and the G\u00fclen movement. The first breaking point was the so-called \u2033[[National Intelligence Organization (Turkey)|MIT]] crisis\u2033 of February 2012, it was also interpreted as a power struggle between pro-G\u00fclen police and judiciary and the AKP.<ref>Halil M. Karaveli: [http://www.turkeyanalyst.org/publications/turkey-analyst-articles/item/395-the-coalition-crumbles-erdogan-the-g%C3%BClenists-and-turkish-democracy.html The Coalition Crumbles: Erdogan, the G\u00fclenists, and Turkish Democracy], The Turkey Analyst, vol. 5, no. 4, Feb. 20, 2012</ref><ref>Sebnem Arsu: [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/11/world/europe/turkey-intelligence-chief-must-testify.html Intelligence Chief Must Testify], nytimes.com, Feb. 10, 2012</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/25/world/middleeast/turkey-feels-sway-of-fethullah-gulen-a-reclusive-cleric.html Turkey Feels Sway of Reclusive Cleric in the U.S.], nytimes.com, April 24, 2012</ref> After the [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|2013 corruption investigations in Turkey]] into stated corrupt practices by several bureaucrats, ministers, mayors, and family members of the ruling AKP of Turkey was uncovered,<ref name=\"Journal-28Dec2013\">{{cite news |title= Turkey: Erdogan faces new protests over corruption scandal |url= http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/erdogan-faces-new-protests-over-corruption-scandal/article/364759 |newspaper= Digital Journal |date= 28 December 2013 |accessdate= 31 December 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hurriyet2013\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/ekonomi/25378685.asp |title=\u0130stanbul'da yolsuzluk ve r\u00fc\u015fvet operasyonu| date=17 December 2013}}</ref> President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] blamed the movement for initiating<ref name=\"BBCprofile-Dec2013\">{{cite news | title = Profile: Fethullah Gulen's Hizmet movement | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-13503361 |newspaper= [[BBC News]] |date= 18 December 2013 | accessdate = 31 December 2013 }}</ref> the investigations as a result of a break in previously friendly relations.<ref name=\"csmonitor.com\">{{cite news |title= The Gulen movement: a self-exiled imam challenges Turkey's Erdo\u011fan |url= http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2013/1229/The-Gulen-movement-a-self-exiled-imam-challenges-Turkey-s-Erdogan |newspaper= [[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date= 29 December 2013 |accessdate= 31 December 2013 }}</ref> President Erdo\u011fan said G\u00fclen attempted to overthrow the Turkish government through a judicial coup by the use of corruption investigations and seized the group-owned newspaper (''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]''\u2014 one of the most circulated [[List of newspapers in Turkey|newspapers in Turkey]] before the seizure<ref name=\"bpa\">{{cite web |url= http://www.clickpress.com/releases/Detailed/39645005cp.shtml |title=BPA Audit Figures Reveal Turkish Newspaper As Having One of the Largest Subscriber Bases in Europe |publisher=ClickPress |date=10 Jul 2007|accessdate= 1 August 2009}}</ref>) and several companies that have ties with the group.\n\nSince May 2016, the G\u00fclen movement has been classified as a terrorist organization by Turkey under the assigned names Fethullahist Terrorist Organization ({{lang-tr|Fethullah\u00e7\u0131 Ter\u00f6r \u00d6rg\u00fct\u00fc}}) (FET\u00d6) and [[Parallel state|Parallel State]] Structure ({{lang-tr|Paralel Devlet Yap\u0131lanmas\u0131}}) (PDY).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-gulen/turkey-officially-designates-gulen-religious-group-as-terrorists-idUSKCN0YM167 |title=Turkey officially designates Gulen religious group as terrorists |accessdate=31 May 2016|newspaper=Reuters |date=31 May 2016 }}</ref> After the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|failed coup attempt in 2016]], the government of Turkey blamed the group for the coup and authorities have [[2016 Turkish purges|arrested thousands of soldiers and judges]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36813924 |title=Turkey: Mass arrests after coup bid quashed, says PM \u2013 BBC News |work= BBC News|accessdate=16 July 2016|date=16 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/politics/2016/07/16/turkeys-top-judicial-board-hsyk-orders-detention-of-2745-gulen-linked-judges-over-coup-attempt|title=Turkey's top judicial board HSYK orders detention of 2,745 G\u00fclen-linked judges over coup attempt|access-date=17 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/07/17/asia/turkey-attempted-coup/index.html|title=Turkey coup attempt: Erdogan rounds up suspected plotters|author1=Sheena McKenzie |author2=Ray Sanchez|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Over ten thousand education staff were suspended and the licenses of over 20,000 teachers working at private institutions were revoked for stated affiliation to G\u00fclen.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36838347 |title=Turkey coup: Purge widens to education sector |publisher=BBC News |date=19 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/americas/2016/07/16/us-to-help-turkey-investigate-failed-coup-attempt-by-feto|title=US to help Turkey investigate failed coup attempt by FET\u00d6|website=DailySabah}}</ref> Fethullah G\u00fclen condemned the coup and denied any involvement.<ref name=\"H\u00fcrriyet G\u00fclen\">{{cite news |title=194 killed in quashed G\u00fclenist coup attempt: Military |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/204-killed-in-quashed-gulenist-coup-attempt-military.aspx?pageID=238&nid=101669&NewsCatID=341 |date=16 July 2016 |accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"bpacdp\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/17/us/fethullah-gulen-turkey-coup-attempt.html|title=An exiled cleric denies playing a leading role in coup attempt|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate= 17 July 2016|date=16 July 2016|last1=Saul|first1=Stephanie}}</ref>\n\n==Description and membership==\nThe movement states that it is based on moral values and advocacy of [[universal access to education]], [[civil society]], tolerance and peace. The emphasis among participants is to perform \"service\" (also the meaning of the Turkish word \"hizmet\" in Turkish) as arising from individuals' personal commitments to righteous imperatives. Along with ''hizmet,'' the movement, which has no official name, is termed the G\u00fclen movement or ''[[cemaat]]'' (the latter also used to describe participants in [[Sufi]] orders, meaning \"congregation,\" \"community,\" or \"assembly.\")The movement has been characterized as a \"moderate blend of Islam\".<ref name=nyt080504>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/04/world/asia/04islam.html?ex=1367640000&en=625b88103a702f94&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink |  first=Sabrina | last=Tavernise | authorlink=Sabrina Tavernise | title=Turkish Schools Offer Pakistan a Gentler Vision of Islam | date=4 May 2008 | work=New York Times}}</ref><ref name=tavernise>{{cite web|url=http://graphics8.nytimes.com/podcasts/2008/04/25/25worldview.mp3|title=Interview with Sabrina Tavernise, World View Podcasts, New York Times, May 4, 2008}}</ref> G\u00fclen and the G\u00fclen movement are technology-friendly, work within current market and commerce structures, and are savvy users of modern communications and public relations.<ref name=prospect>Ehsan Masood, [http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/features/amodernottoman A modern Ottoman], ''Prospect'', Issue 148, July 2008</ref> In 2008, G\u00fclen was described as \"the modern face of the Sufi Ottoman tradition\", who reassures his followers, including many members of \"Turkey's aspirational middle class\", that \"they can combine the statist-nationalist beliefs of Atat\u00fcrk\u2019s republic with a traditional but flexible Islamic faith\" and \"Ottoman traditions that had been caricatured as theocratic by [[Atat\u00fcrk]] and his '[[Kemalist]]' heirs\".<ref name=prospect/>\n\nWithin Turkey the G\u00fclen movement keeps its distance from established Islamic political parties.<ref>Clement M. Henry, Rodney Wilson, [https://edinburghuniversitypress.com/book-the-politics-of-islamic-finance.html ''The politics of Islamic Finance''], Edinburgh University Press (2004), p 236. Retrieved 16 July 2016</ref>\n\nSources state that the G\u00fclen movement is vying to be recognized as the world's leading Muslim network, one that is more reasonable than many of its rivals.<ref name=economist10808408>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10808408|title=How far they have travelled|publisher=|via=The Economist}}</ref> The movement builds on the activities of G\u00fclen, who has won praise from non-Muslim quarters for his advocacy of science, [[interfaith dialogue]], and multi-party democracy. It has earned praise as \"the world's most global movement\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-144416-turkish-schools-worlds-most-global-movement-says-sociologist.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219021813/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-144416-turkish-schools-worlds-most-global-movement-says-sociologist.html|url-status=dead|title=Turkish schools World's most global movement, says sociologist|archivedate=19 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n\"It is impossible to calculate the size of the G\u00fclen movement\" since the movement is not a centralized or formal organization with membership rosters, but rather a set of numerous, loosely organized networks of people inspired by G\u00fclen.<ref>Helen Rose Ebaugh, ''The G\u00fclen Movement: A Sociological Analysis of a Civic Movement Rooted in Moderate Islam'' (Springer, 2009), p. 46.</ref> Estimates of the size of the movement vary, with one source stating that between 200,000 supporters and 4 million people are influenced by G\u00fclen's ideas (1997 ''[[Tempo (Turkey magazine)|Tempo]]'' estimate),<ref>Bulent Aras & Omer Caha, [http://www.rubincenter.org/2000/12/aras-and-caha-2000-12-04/ Fethullah Gulen and his Liberal \"Turkish Islam\" Movement], ''[[Middle East Review of International Affairs]]'', Vol. 4, No. 4 (December 2000).</ref> and another stating that G\u00fclen has \"hundreds of thousands of supporters\" (''The Guardian'', 2000).<ref name=guardian>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,4057646,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Turkey accuses popular Islamist of plot against state | date=1 September 2000 | accessdate=4 May 2010 | first=Chris | last=Morris}}</ref> The membership of the movement consists primarily of students, teachers, businessmen, academics, journalists and other professionals.<ref name=\"jbwhite\"/>  Its members have founded schools, universities, an employers' association, charities, real estate trusts, student organizations, radio and television stations, and newspapers.<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\nThe movement's structure has been described as a flexible organizational network.<ref>[http://www.qantara.de/webcom/show_article.php/_c-478/_nr-216/i.html Portrait of Fethullah G\u00fclen, A Modern Turkish-Islamic Reformist]</ref> Movement schools and businesses organize locally and link themselves into informal networks.<ref name=\"Islam in Kazakhstan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.amerasianworld.com/islam_in_kazakhstan.php|title=Islam in Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan (The Nurcu Movement and the Hizb ut Tahrir)|first=Kevin Miller|last=Jr.|access-date=12 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213015820/http://www.amerasianworld.com/islam_in_kazakhstan.php|archive-date=13 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Akin to Turkey's Sufi [[tariqa]]s (lay religious orders), banned in Turkey in 1925,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rlp.hds.harvard.edu/faq/sufism-turkey |title=Sufism in Turkey &#124; Religious Literacy Project |publisher=Rlp.hds.harvard.edu |date= |accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> The movement skirted Kemalist Turkey's prohibitions against assembling in non-state sponsored religious meetings. (President-to-be of Turkey Tayyip Erdo\u011fan, when a young man, had belonged to the then-technically-banned-in-Turkey [[Naqshbandi]] tariqa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/re-visioning-religion/media-and-mysticism-erdo%C4%9Fan-and-g%C3%BClen-b7570f672362 |title=Media and Mysticism: Erdo\u011fan vs. G\u00fclen \u2013 Re-visioning Religion \u2013 Medium |publisher=Medium.com |date= 8 December 2016|accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref>)\n\nEach local G\u00fclen movement school and community has a person designated its \"informal\" (in the sense of not being Turkish state-sponsored) prayer leader ([[imam]]). In the G\u00fclen movement, this individual is a [[lay clergy|layman who serves for a stint within this volunteer position]]. His  identity is kept confidential, generally only purposely made known to those with close connections to those participating in decision-making and coordinating councils within the local group. Above a grouping of such \"secret\" (not-publicly-acknowledged) imams is another such volunteer leader. This relationship tree continues on up the laddar to the nation-level imam and to an individuals who consults with G\u00fclen himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulenists/gulen-community-service-feto |title=The 'ally' to 'enemy # 1': G\u00fclen Movement (1) &#124; Ahval |publisher=Ahvalnews.com |date= |accessdate=2018-04-11}}</ref> (These individuals closest to Gulen, having degrees from theology schools, are offhandedly referred to within the movement as ''[[mullah]]s.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/intellectual-crisis-gulen-movement|title=The Intellectual Crisis of the G\u00fclen Movement &#124; Ahval}}</ref>) G\u00fclen's position, as described in the foregoing, is analogous to that of a [[shaykh]] (master) of a Sufi tariqa. Unlike with traditional tariqas, no-one makes pledges of any sort, upon joining the G\u00fclen movement; one becomes a movement participant simply by working with others to promote and effect the movement's objectives of education and service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fgulen.com/en/home/1310-fgulen-com-english/fethullah-gulen-life/about-fethullah-gulen-and-gulen-movement/31760-is-the-gulen-movement-a-sufi-tariqa|title=Is the G\u00fclen Movement a Sufi tariqa? - Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site|first=Fethullah|last=G\u00fclen|website=fgulen.com}}</ref>\n\nThe G\u00fclen movement works within the given structures of modern secular states; it encourages affiliated members to maximize the opportunities those countries afford rather than engaging in subversive activities.<ref name=forbes0118>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/01/18/turkey-islam-gulen-cx_0121oxford.html |title=Gulen Inspires Muslims Worldwide |publisher=Forbes |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref> In the words of the leader himself and the title of a cornerstone of his philosophy, G\u00fclen promotes \"an Ottoman Empire of the Mind\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fgulen.com/en/home/1324-fgulen-com-english/press/columns/25006-an-ottoman-empire-of-the-mind|title=An Ottoman Empire of the Mind - Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site|last=fgulen.com}}</ref>\n\nDetractors of the movement \"have labeled G\u00fclen community members as secretive missionaries, while those in the Movement and sympathetic observers class it as a [[civil society]] organization\".<ref>David Tittensor, ''The House of Service: The Gulen Movement and Islam's Third Way'' ([[Oxford University Press]], 2014) p. 172.</ref>\n\nCritics have complained that members of the G\u00fclen movement are overly compliant to the directions from its leaders,<ref name=\"Infra note, Berlinski 2012\">Infra note, Berlinski 2012</ref> and G\u00fclen's \"movement is generally perceived by its critics as a religio-political [[cult]]\".<ref>Bulent Temel, Candidacy versus Membership: Is Turkey the Greatest Beneficiary of the European Union\" in ''The Great Catalyst: European Union Project and Lessons from Greece and Turkey'' (ed. B\u00fclent Temel: [[Lexington Books|Lexington]], 2014), p. 375.</ref> The ''Guardian'' editorial board described the movement in 2013 as having \"some of the characteristics of a cult or of an Islamic [[Opus Dei]]\".<ref name=\"GuardianDec2013\">{{cite news | title=Turkey: up from the depths | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/dec/27/turkey-murky-depths | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=27 December 2013 | accessdate = 31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nScholars such as Simon Robinson disagree with the characterization, writing that although \"[t]here is no doubt that G\u00fclen remains a [[charismatic leader]] and that members of the movement hold him in the highest respect\", the movement \"differs markedly  from a cult in several ways\", with G\u00fclen stressing \"the primacy of the scriptures\" and \"the imperative of service\" and consistently avoiding \"attempts to institutionalize power, to perceive him as the source of all truth, or to view him as taking responsibility for the movement\".<ref>Simon Robinson, \"Building Bridges: Gulen Pontifex\" in ''Hizmet Means Service: Perspectives on an Alternative Path within Islam'' (ed. Martin E. Marty: [[University of California Press]], 2015), p. 78.</ref> Zeki Saritoprak says that the view of G\u00fclen as \"a cult leader or a man with ambitions\" is mistaken, and contends that G\u00fclen should be viewed in the context of a long line of Sufi masters who have long been a center of attention \"for their admirers and followers, both historically and currently\".<ref>Zeki Saritoprak, \"Muslim Perception of Fethullah Gulen and the Hizmet Movement: Accommodating or Hindering Modern Turkey?\" in ''Alternative Islamic Discourses and Religious'' (eds. Carool Kersten & Susanne Olsson: [[Ashgate Publishing|Ashgate]], 2013), p. 70.</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2008, the Dutch government investigated the movement's activities in the Netherlands in response to questions from [[Parliament of the Netherlands|Parliament]]. The first two investigations, performed by the [[General Intelligence and Security Service|AIVD]], concluded that the movement did not form a breeding ground for radicalism and found no indications that the movement worked against integration or that it was involved in terrorism or religious radicalization. A further academic study sketched a portrait of a socially conservative, inwardly directed movement with an opaque organizational structure, but said that its members tend to be highly successful in society and thus form no threat to integration.<ref>{{cite news | title = Vormt de G\u00fclen-beweging een bedreiging voor de integratie? | url=https://www.groene.nl/artikel/vormt-de-gulen-beweging-een-bedreiging-voor-de-integratie | newspaper=[[De Groene Amsterdammer]] | date=21 March 2014| accessdate = 24 February 2016 | author = Hassan Bahara}}</ref>\n\nHizmet-affiliated foundations and businesses were estimated as worth $20-to-$50 billion in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=<!----><!---->Kenneth Rapoza<!----> |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2015/12/20/in-sunni-cult-fight-turkey-guns-for-americas-richest-and-most-politically-connected-cleric/#438192fb4f93 |title=In Sunni 'Cult' Fight, Turkey Guns For America's Richest And Most Politically Connected Cleric |publisher=Forbes.com |date= |accessdate=2018-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Socio-economic activities==\n\n===Schools===\n{{main|G\u00fclen movement schools}}\nThe movement is active in education (kindergarten\u2013university) as well as civic opportunities in other areas such as for interfaith dialogue, humanitarian aid, media, finance, and health.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> Most G\u00fclen Movement schools are private. By 2017 it was estimated 1.2 million Turks have passed through Hizmet schools (including Turkish prime minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan's son in-law, [[Berat Albayrak]]);<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-turkey-coup-gulen-snap-story.html |title=Inside the secretive religious movement that is being blamed for Turkey's attempted coup |publisher=LA Times |date=2016-08-17 |accessdate=2017-09-21}}</ref> and its educational footprint extends to over 160 countries. In 2009 it was estimated that members of the G\u00fclen Movement ran schools around the world in which more than two million students were enrolled.<ref name=\"Behind Turkey's Witch Hunt\">{{Citation | newspaper = News week | url = http://www.newsweek.com/id/197896 | title = Behind Turkey's Witch Hunt| date = 16 May 2009 }}</ref> Estimates of the number of schools and educational institutions vary widely; it appears there are about 300 G\u00fclen Movement schools in Turkey and over 1,000 schools worldwide.<ref>{{Citation  |newspaper = Reuters | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/featuresNews/idUKL0939033920080514?pageNumber=3&virtualBrandChannel=0 | title = Turkish Islamic preacher \u2013 threat or benefactor?|date = 14 May 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | publisher = Turko kullari | url = http://www.turkokullari.net/index.php?option=com_weblinks&catid=14&Itemid=22 | title = Turkish Schools | access-date = 15 June 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141006163144/http://www.turkokullari.net/index.php?option=com_weblinks&catid=14&Itemid=22 | archive-date = 6 October 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nBeyond the borders of Turkey, many G\u00fclen schools can be found in countries with large populations of people of Turkish descent. G\u00fclen schools in predominantly non-Turkish Muslim countries provide families with an alternative to [[madrasa]] education.\n\nG\u00fclen schools have received both criticism and praise.<ref name=\"Interfaith Voices: Fethullah G\u00fclen\">{{cite web|url=http://interfaithradio.org/node/491/|title=Interfaith Voices: Fethullah G\u00fclen}}</ref>\n\n====Charter schools in the United States====\n{{see also|G\u00fclen movement schools}}\nIn 2011, it was estimated that over 120 [[charter schools in the United States]] in 25 states were operated by participants of the G\u00fclen movement.<ref name=\"NYtimes2011\">{{cite news | title = Charter Schools Tied to Turkey's Gulen Movement Grow in Texas | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/education/07charter.html?pagewanted=all | date = 6 June 2011 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | author = Stephanie Saul | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160717180813/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/education/07charter.html | archive-date=17 July 2016| access-date = 18 Jul 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/2011-03-20/news/29148147_1_gulen-schools-gulen-followers-charter-schools|title=U.S. charter-school network with Turkish link draws federal attention | work=Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=18 Jul 2016}}</ref> The largest numbers of such schools were in Texas (33 schools, [[Harmony schools]], run by the Cosmos Foundation); Ohio (19 schools, known as Horizon Science Academies and operated by [[Concept Schools]] Inc.); and California (14 schools, operated by the Magnolia Foundation).<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/> The ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' reported at the time that G\u00fclen schools were one of the largest users of [[H1B visa]]s, receiving approval for 684 such visas in 2009.<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/> The ''Inquirer'' reported that the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]], [[United States Department of Labor|Labor Department]], and [[United States Department of Labor|Education Department]] were investigating whether some charter school employees employed via H1B visas misused funds by kicking back a portion of their salaries to movement groups.<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/> The investigation had no tie to terrorism, and there was \"no indication the American charter network has a religious agenda in the classroom\".<ref name=\"Inquirer_20_March_2011\"/>\n\nA ''[[60 Minutes]]'' episode profiled G\u00fclen movement-operated charter schools in the U.S. in May 2012.<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/us-charter-schools-tied-to-powerful-turkish-imam/ | title=U.S. charter schools tied to powerful Turkish imam | publisher=[[CBS News]] | work=[[60 Minutes]] | date=May 13, 2012 | accessdate=January 17, 2018 | author=Stahl, Lesley| authorlink = Lesley Stahl}}</ref> The profile estimated that there were about 130 affiliated schools nationwide, with about 36 Harmony School in Texas, serving \"mostly underprivileged students\" and all emphasizing math and science.<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\"/> The episode said that the schools generally received high marks for the quality of education, but also said that G\u00fclen's reclusive nature \"invites conspiracy theories that he's running Turkey from the Poconos and is bent on global Muslim domination\" and that \"[o]ne statement involves immigration fraud: that the schools are providing work visas for hundreds of G\u00fclen followers from Turkey.\"<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\"/>\n\nProfessor Joshua Hendrick of [[Loyola University Maryland]], who studies the movement, said that G\u00fclen himself \"does not have a direct hand in operating\" the charter schools,<ref name=\"Strum\"/> and it was reported that G\u00fclen has never visited the schools.<ref name=\"60MinsEpisode\"/> The Harmony Schools in Texas do not teach religion, and the charter network says that some 7.8% of its teachers are non-Americans.<ref name=\"Strum\"/>\n\nThe ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reported in 2016 that around 150 U.S. charter schools were tied to the G\u00fclen movement, \"ranging from networks in Texas, Illinois and Florida to stand-alone academies in Maryland\".<ref name=\"Strum\">Beckie Strum, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/gulen-movements-charter-schools-may-be-caught-up-in-turkey-u-s-standoff-1468967536 Gulen Movement's Charter Schools May Be Caught Up in Turkey-U.S. Standoff], ''Wall Street Journal'' (July 19, 2016).</ref> The ''Journal'' stated that like other charter schools \"blacks and Hispanics in underserved neighborhoods\" made up the majority of the student body, with common themes including \"an emphasis on math and science education, [[Turkish language]] classes and sponsored trips to Turkey\".<ref name=\"Strum\"/> Hendrick said that in the upheaval following the 2016 Turkish coup attempt, proposed new charter schools and charters up for renewal \"that are run by [[Turkish-Americans]] and are said to be connected with the cleric\" could run into increased opposition, as the Turkish government has sought \"to bring down Mr. Gulen through U.S. charter schools they claim are connected to him\".<ref name=\"Strum\"/>\n\n===Dialogue===\n[[File:Fethullah G\u00fclen visiting Ioannes Paulus II.jpg|thumb|G\u00fclen and [[Pope John Paul II]]]]\n\nThe movement's avowal of interfaith dialogue grew out of G\u00fclen's personal engagement in interfaith dialogue, largely inspired by the example of one of his influences, [[Said Nursi]]. G\u00fclen has met with leaders of other religions, including [[Pope John Paul II]], the [[Bartholomew I of Constantinople|Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I]], and Israeli Sephardic Head Rabbi [[Eliyahu Bakshi-Doron]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Advocate of Dialogue: Fethullah Gulen|first=Ali|last=Unal|date=1 October 2000|publisher=Fountain Pub|isbn=978-0970437013|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/advocateofdialog00aliu}}</ref> G\u00fclen advocates cooperation between followers of different religions as well as those practicing different forms of Islam (such as Sunnism or [[Alevi]]sm).\n\nG\u00fclen's call for interfaith dialogue has influenced three generations of movement followers.<ref name=\"Interfaith Voices: Fethullah G\u00fclen\"/>\n\nG\u00fclen movement participants have founded a number of institutions across the World that promote [[Interfaith dialogue|interfaith]] and [[Interculturalism|intercultural]] dialogue activities. Among these are the ''Journalists and Writers Foundation'' in Istanbul, the ''Rumi Forum'' in Washington and the ''Indialogue Foundation'' in New Delhi.\n\n=== Media ===\nMovement participants have set up a number of media organizations to promote its core values such as love, tolerance, hope, dialogue, activism, mutual acceptance and respect. These media organs include TV stations ([[Samanyolu TV]], [[Mehtap TV]]), ([[Ebru TV]]) (English), the newspapers ''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]'', ''[[Today's Zaman]]'' (English), magazines and journals in Turkish like ''[[Aksiyon]]'', ''[[S\u0131z\u0131nt\u0131]]'',<ref>{{cite web|author=G\u00fcnter Seufert|title=Is the Fethullah G\u00fclen Movement Overstretching Itself?|url=https://www.swp-berlin.org/fileadmin/contents/products/research_papers/2014_RP02_srt.pdf|publisher=Stiftung Wissenschaft und Politik|accessdate=2 August 2016|format=Research Paper|date=January 2014}}</ref> ''[[Yeni \u00dcmit]]'', ''[[The Fountain Magazine]]'' (English), ''[[Hira (magazine)|Hira]]'' (Arabic), ''The International [[Cihan News Agency]]'' and the radio station {{Interlanguage link multi|Bur\u00e7 FM|tr}}.\n\n=== Humanitarian aid ===\nThe movement runs charity and humanitarian aid organizations which are transnationally active. The leading one among them is the Istanbul-based [[Kimse Yok Mu Association]] (KYM). KYM organizes charity campaigns to help those in need in different parts of the world. Like any other activities of the G\u00fclen-movement, KYM runs local projects responding to specific needs. KYM holds UN Ecosoc Special status.\n\nAnother charity organization [[Embrace Relief]] was established in [[New Jersey]] and is active in the Americas, Asia and Africa.\n\n=== Professional associations ===\nWhile being both praised and criticized for being market friendly, the G\u00fclen movement has established various professional associations and business networks. Among them Istanbul based [[TUSKON]] is the major non-profit business confederation which states to promote economic solutions as well as social and political ones. Another one called TUCSIAD is based in China, in addition to DTIK's Asia-Pacific Group which supports the G\u00fclen movement outside of Turkey in China, hoping to influence Turkish politics from the outside.\n\n==Criticism==\n{{expand section | small  = no | talksection=Criticism|date=December 2016}}\n[[Fethullah G\u00fclen]]'s and the G\u00fclen movement's views and practices have been discussed in international [[Academic conference|conferences]]. In October 2007 in London a conference was sponsored by the [[University of Birmingham]], the Dialogue Society, the [[Irish School of Ecumenics]], [[Leeds Metropolitan University]], the London Middle East Institute, the [[Middle East Institute]] and the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]], University of London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.fgulen.com/conference-papers/contributions-of-the-gulen-movement |title=Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site - Contributions of the G\u00fclen Movement |publisher=En.fgulen.com |date=27 October 2007 |accessdate=18 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204120035/http://en.fgulen.com/conference-papers/contributions-of-the-gulen-movement |archive-date=4 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Niagara Foundation]] of Chicago, together with several academic institutions, organized \"The G\u00fclen Movement: Paradigms, Projects and Aspirations\" conference, which was held at [[University of Chicago]] on 11\u201313 November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Core Design Production, Web designers; Fatih YAZAR, Yunus USLU, Ismail ABAY |url=http://www.niagarafoundation.org/the-international-gulen-conference-2010-in-chicago-2/ |title=Gulen Movement & Fethullah Gulen |publisher=Niagara Foundation |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Assassination of Andrei Karlov===\nTurkish and Russian officials declared the G\u00fclen movement to be responsible for the [[Assassination of Andrei Karlov|assassination]] of [[List of ambassadors of Russia to Turkey|Russian ambassador]] [[Andrei Karlov]], and accused the movement of aiming to damage [[Russia\u2013Turkey relations]] that had been normalizing since the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Karlov suikast\u0131 davas\u0131 devam ediyor: Alt\u0131nta\u015f'\u0131 FET\u00d6 evinde g\u00f6rd\u00fcm |url=https://tr.sputniknews.com/turkiye/201901081036988171-karlov-altintas-feto-evi/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |publisher=Sputnik T\u00fcrkiye |date=8 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Prosecutors seek life sentence for defendants in Russian ambassador's killing |url=https://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/prosecutors-seek-life-sentence-for-defendants-in-russian-ambassadors-killing-152732 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |publisher=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Borger |first1=Julian |title=Why killing of Russian diplomat may well bring Turkey and Russia closer |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/19/why-killing-of-russian-diplomat-is-likely-to-bring-turkey-and-russia-closer |accessdate=3 April 2020 |publisher=The Guardian |date=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Designation as a terrorist group==\nG\u00fclen movement is deemed a [[List of designated terrorist groups|designated terrorist group]] by the following countries and international organizations:\n* {{flagicon image|GCC Flag.svg}} [[Gulf Cooperation Council]]<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|}} [[Organization of Islamic Cooperation]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/war-on-terror/2016/10/19/organization-of-islamic-cooperation-declares-feto-a-terrorist-group|title=Organization of Islamic Cooperation declares FET\u00d6 a terrorist group|website=DailySabah}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20161019-oic-lists-gulen-network-as-terror-group/|title=OIC lists Gulen network as 'terror group'|date=19 October 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Pakistan}}<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/turkey-welcomes-pakistan-s-ruling-on-feto-terror-group/1350959|title=Turkey welcomes Pakistan\u2019s ruling on FETO terror group|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Northern Cyprus}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/europe/northern-cyprus-designates-feto-as-terror-group/613113|title=Northern Cyprus designates FETO as terror group|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Turkey}}<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n==Political involvement==\nAccording to academic researcher Svante E. Cornell, director of the [[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] & Silk Road Studies Program, \"With only slight exaggeration, the ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) as well as the government it has led could be termed a coalition of religious orders.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/secret-diyanet-report-gauges-threat-posed-turkeys-islamists|title=Secret Diyanet report gauges threat posed by Turkey\u2019s Islamists|website=Ahval|language=en|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> \"[...T]he G\u00fclen movement stayed away from electoral politics, focusing instead on increasing its presence in the state bureaucracy. The Hizmet movement\u2019s stated success in this regard would initially make it Erdo\u011fan\u2019s main partner, but also his eventual nemesis.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hudson.org/research/11601-the-naqshbandi-khalidi-order-and-political-islam-in-turkey|title=The Naqshbandi-Khalidi Order and Political Islam in Turkey - by Svante E. Cornell|last=Cornell|first=Svante E.|website=hudson.org|language=en|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u20132013 collaboration with the AKP===\nFrom 2002 to 2013, the G\u00fclen movement comprehensively collaborated with the [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP) and [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] in obtaining political power in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/akps-problematic-relations-with-gulen.aspx?pageID=449&nID=115586&NewsCatID=409|title=AKP's problematic relations with G\u00fclen|date=17 July 2017|publisher=Hurriyet Daily News.}}</ref>\n\nQuestions have arisen about the G\u00fclen movement's possible involvement in the ongoing [[Ergenekon (allegation)|Ergenekon investigation]],<ref name=Jenkins/> which critics have characterized as \"a pretext\" by the government \"to neutralize dissidents\" in Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagaptay.com/5593/ergenekon-behind-turkey-witch-hunt|title=Behind Turkey's Witch Hunt|first=Soner|last=Cagaptay}}</ref> In March 2011, seven Turkish journalists were arrested, including [[Ahmet \u015e\u0131k]], who had been writing a book, \"Imamin Ordusu\" (''[[The Imam's Army]]''),<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/apr/05/turkey-censorship-ahmet-sik-perrier Turkish authorities launch raids to censor book before publication] in the Guardian of 5 April 2011; accessed on 11 April 2011</ref> which states that the G\u00fclen movement has infiltrated the country's security forces. As \u015e\u0131k was taken into police custody, he shouted, \"Whoever touches it [the movement] gets burned!\".<ref>{{cite news |  url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/04/world/europe/04turkey.htmll?_r=1%20 | work=The New York Times | first=\u015eebnem | last=Arsu | title=7 More Journalists Detained in Turkey | date=3 March 2011}}</ref> Upon his arrest, drafts of the book were confiscated and its possession was banned. \u015e\u0131k has also been charged with being part of the stated Ergenekon plot, despite being an investigator of the plot before his arrest.<ref>Details can be found in English on the site of [http://www.tuerkeiforum.net/enw/index.php/Ahmet_%C5%9E%C4%B1k:_The_Army_of_the_Imam the Democratic Turkey Forum]; accessed on 5 April 2001. In the footnotes to translated passages of the book you can find other works on the subject.</ref>\n\nIn a reply, Abdullah Bozkurt, from the G\u00fclen movement newspaper ''[[Today's Zaman]]'', said Ahmet \u015e\u0131k was not being an investigative journalist conducting \"independent research\", but was hatching \"a plot designed and put into action by the terrorist network itself\".<ref>The alleged terrorist network is the [[Ergenekon (organization)|Ergenekon organization]]; see [http://www.todayszaman.com/columnist-239479-ergenekon-gulen-and-media-freedom.html Article of 29 March 2011] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201055315/http://www.todayszaman.com/columnist-239479-ergenekon-gulen-and-media-freedom.html |date=1 February 2016 }}; accessed on 5 April 2011</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Gareth H. Jenkins]], a Senior Fellow of the [[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute & Silk Road Studies Joint Center]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]]:\n{{quote|From the outset, the pro-AKP media, particularly the newspapers and television channels run by the G\u00fclen Movement such as ''Zaman'', ''Today's Zaman'' and Samanyolu TV, have vigorously supported the Ergenekon investigation. This has included the illegal publication of \"evidence\" collected by the investigators before it has been presented in court, misrepresentations and distortions of the content of the indictments and smear campaigns against both the accused and anyone who questions the conduct of the investigations.\n\nThere have long been allegations that not only the media coverage but also the Ergenekon investigation itself is being run by G\u00fclen's supporters. In August 2010, [[Hanefi Avc\u0131]], a right-wing police chief who had once been sympathetic to the G\u00fclen Movement, published a book in which he alleged that a network of G\u00fclen's supporters in the police were manipulating judicial processes and fixing internal appointments and promotions. On September 28, 2010, two days before he was due to give a press conference to present documentary evidence to support his allegations, Avc\u0131 was arrested and charged with membership of an extremist leftist organization. On March 14, 2011, Avc\u0131 was also formally charged with being a member of the alleged Ergenekon gang.<ref name=Jenkins>{{cite web |url=http://www.silkroadstudies.org/new/inside/turkey/2011/110404B.html |title=Central Asia-Caucasus Institute and Silk Road Studies Program |publisher=Silkroadstudies.org |accessdate=18 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427163058/http://www.silkroadstudies.org/new/inside/turkey/2011/110404B.html |archivedate=27 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nThe G\u00fclen movement has also been implicated in what the opposition [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP) - and after 2013 also President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] - have said were illegal court decisions against members of the [[Turkish military]], including many during the Ergenekon investigation.<ref name=\"NYtimes2-27-2014\">{{cite news | title = Turkish Leader Disowns Trials That Helped Him Tame Military | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/world/europe/turkish-leader-disowns-trials-that-helped-him-tame-military.html?hpw&rref=world | last = Arango | first = Tim | date = 26 February 2014 | accessdate = 27 February 2014 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | quote = In 2005, years before the trials, a man affiliated with the Gulen movement approached Eric S. Edelman, then the American ambassador, at a party in Istanbul and handed him an envelope containing a handwritten document that supposedly laid out a plan for an imminent coup. But as Edelman recounted, he gave the documents to his colleagues and they were determined to be forgeries. }}</ref>\n\n===2013 AKP corruption scandal===\n{{Main|2013 corruption scandal in Turkey}}\nOn 17 December 2013, an [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|investigation]] into stated corrupt practices by several bureaucrats, ministers, mayors, and family members of the ruling [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP) of Turkey was uncovered, resulting in widespread protests and calls for the resignation of the government led by Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]].<ref name=\"Journal-28Dec2013\"/><ref name=\"Hurriyet2013\"/> Due to the high level of political influence by the G\u00fclen movement in Turkey, it is rumored to be facilitated by the movement's influence on the Turkish police force and the judiciary,<ref name=\"BBCprofile-Dec2013\"/> the investigation was said to be a result of a break in previously friendly relations between the Islamist-rooted government and the movement.<ref name=\"csmonitor.com\"/>\n\nPresident [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]] and the [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]] (the ruling party of Turkey) have targeted the movement since December 2013. Immediately after the [[2013 corruption scandal in Turkey|corruption statements]], the government subjugated the judiciary, media and civil society which were critical of the government's authoritarian trend in recent years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/special-report/21689871-under-recep-tayip-erdogan-and-his-ak-party-turkey-has-become-richer-and-more-confident|title=Erdogan\u2019s new sultanate|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/editorials/under-erdogan-turkey-is-moving-away-from-democracy/article29281164/|title=Under Erdogan, Turkey is moving away from democracy|website=The Globe and Mail|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/turkey/12195534/EU-Turkey-deal-Recep-Tayyip-Erdogan-Where-did-it-all-go-wrong-for-Turkey.html|title=Where did it all go wrong for Turkey?|website=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=25 April 2016|date=17 March 2016|last1=Akkoc|first1=Raziye}}</ref> After the corruption statements surfaced, Erdogan labelled it as a \"civilian coup\" against his government. Since then, Erdogan has shuffled, dismissed or jailed hundreds of police officers, judges, prosecutors and journalists in the name of fighting against a \"Parallel State\" within the Turkish state.\n\n===Crackdown against the G\u00fclen movement from 2014===\n{{main|Turkish government\u2013G\u00fclen movement conflict}}\n\nOn 14 December 2014 Turkish police arrested more than two dozen senior journalists and media executives connected with the G\u00fclen movement on various charges.\n\nA statement by the [[US State Department]] cautioned Turkey not to violate its \"own democratic foundations\" while drawing attention to raids against media outlets \"openly critical of the current Turkish government\".<ref>{{cite news|title=In Turkey, police arrest journalists and executives|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/12/14/world/europe/turkey-media-crackdown/|accessdate=19 December 2014|newspaper=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Court rules for release of Zaman chief editor, Samanyolu manager arrested|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/national_court-rules-for-release-of-zaman-chief-editor-samanyolu-manager-arrested_367441.html|accessdate=19 December 2014|newspaper=Today's Zaman|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219133859/http://www.todayszaman.com/national_court-rules-for-release-of-zaman-chief-editor-samanyolu-manager-arrested_367441.html|archivedate=19 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy|EU Foreign Affairs]] chief [[Federica Mogherini]] and [[European Commissioner for Enlargement and European Neighbourhood Policy|EU Enlargement]] Commissioner [[Johannes Hahn]] said that the arrests went \"against European values\" and \"are incompatible with the freedom of media, which is a core principle of democracy\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey media arrests: Mogherini leads EU criticism|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30471996|accessdate=19 December 2014|newspaper=BBC}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2015, Turkish police launched raids in [[Ankara]] and three other cities, detaining some 20 people suspected of illegally eavesdropping on President Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan and other senior officials. The suspects are linked to Turkey's telecommunications authority and to its scientific and technological research center [[TUBITAK]]. Local media said the move was aimed at the \"parallel structure\" \u2014 the term Erdogan uses to refer to G\u00fclen's supporters in the judiciary, police and other institutions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turkey arrests dozens suspected of eavesdropping on president|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/1/20/turkey-wiretappingarrests.html|accessdate=20 January 2015| newspaper=Aljazeera}}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish government took over the G\u00fclenist ''Zaman Daily'', on 4 March 2016. Turkish police entered the Zaman's headquarters by force and fired tear gas at the protesting journalists and civilians. Hundreds of protestors were injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2016/03/turkey-fears-of-zaman-newspaper-takeover/|title=Turkey: Zaman newspaper taken over as government steamrolls press freedom|website=amnesty.org|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/05/world/middleeast/recep-tayyip-erdogan-government-seizes-zaman-newspaper.html|title=Turkey Seizes Newspaper, Zaman, as Press Crackdown Continues|last=Timur|first=Safak|date=4 March 2016|last2=Arango|first2=Tim|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=25 April 2016}}</ref> In his efforts to eradicate the movement within the country the [[Turkish National Security Council]] has identified the movement as the \"G\u00fclenist Terror Organisation\" (\"Fethullah\u00e7\u0131 Ter\u00f6r \u00d6rg\u00fct\u00fc\", FET\u00d6).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trtworld.com/in-depth/turkey-challenged-by-terror-in-2015-17588|title=Turkey challenged by terror in 2015|website=TRT World|language=tr-TR|access-date=6 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203060054/http://www.trtworld.com/in-depth/turkey-challenged-by-terror-in-2015-17588|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The government has also been targeting individuals and businessmen who have supported the movement's organizations and activities.\n\n===Purge of movement in Turkey after July 2016===\n{{see also|Turkish government\u2013G\u00fclen movement conflict|2016\u201317 purges in Turkey}}\n\nIn reaction to the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|15 July 2016 coup attempt]], led by a military faction operating outside the chain of command, the Turkish government quickly stated the coup's leader to be G\u00fclen. In following days and weeks, a massive crackdown affected all entities affiliated to the G\u00fclen movements, from individuals to businesses, newspapers to schools and universities.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Ahmet Erdi|date=2019-02-26|title=An alternative reading of religion and authoritarianism: the new logic between religion and state in the AKP's New Turkey|journal=Southeast European and Black Sea Studies|volume=0|pages=79\u201398|doi=10.1080/14683857.2019.1576370|issn=1468-3857}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[assassination of Andrey Karlov]], the Turkish government was reportedly investigating the assassin's links to the \"G\u00fclenist Terrorist Organisation\" (FET\u00d6); in a speech, [[President of Turkey|Turkish President]] [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] said that the perpetrator was a member of FET\u00d6.<ref name=\"ABCNews20Dec\">{{cite news|title=Who was the Ankara assassin?|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-12-20/ankara-russian-ambassador-shooting-who-is-mevlut-mert-aydintas/8135510|work=ABC News|date=20 December 2016|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/cumhurbaskani-erdogan-ankara-da-siyaset-2365707/|title=Erdo\u011fan resmen a\u00e7\u0131klad\u0131: Suikast\u00e7\u0131 FET\u00d6 mensubu|trans-title=Erdo\u011fan officially announces: Assassin is FET\u00d6 member|work=Milliyet Haber|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Extraditions to Turkey; political asylums granted ===\n{{as of|2020}}, Turkey had successfully pressured a number of countries, especially those in Africa and the [[former Soviet Union]], to extradite \nover 80 alleged g\u00fclenists to Turkey.<ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkey-gathered-information-in-the-u-s-against-its-critics-11573654247?reflink=share_mobilewebshare#_=_</ref><ref>https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/broken-gulen-movement-faces-existential-crisis</ref>\n\nIn 2019 it was reported that [[Interpol]] had denied Turkey's appeals of the agency's rejections of Turkey's [[red notice]] requests regarding 464 fugitives, citing Interpol's legal definition of the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] as not [[terrorism]] but a failed military [[putsch]].<ref>https://ahvalnews.com/gulen-movement/turkey-poised-rescind-fethullah-gulens-citizenship</ref>\n\nIn 2018, bout 25,000 Turkish [[political asylum|asylum]] requests were filed by alleged g\u00fclenists in the European Union (a rise of 50 per cent from 2017), with Germany's share 10,000 and Greece's about 5,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/11/22/turks-persecuted-over-alleged-links-to-the-gulen-movement-find-a-safe-haven-in-greece|title=Greece: A safe haven for Turks threatened over G\u00fclen movement links|first=Katy|last=Dartford|date=22 November 2019|website=euronews}}</ref> Within the U.S., according to news reports, a number of G\u00fclenists successfully receiving political asylum status are resettled in New Jersey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/10/17/turkish-gulen-supporters-fleeing-crackdown-seek-asylum-new-jersey/4006257002/|title=Labeled terrorists in their homeland, hundreds of Turks seek asylum in New Jersey|first=Hannan|last=Adely|website=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n* 1941&nbsp;\u2013 [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]] is born in Korucuk, near [[Erzurum]], Turkey\n* 1950s&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen's first meeting with people from the [[Nur Movement]]<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Unal & Williams|editor1-first=Ali & Alphonse|title=Advocate of Dialogue: Fethullah Gulen|date=2000|publisher=The Fountain|location=Fairfax, VA|page=15}}</ref>\n* 1960&nbsp;\u2013 death of [[Said Nurs\u00ee]]<ref>Ian Markham, Engaging with Bediuzzaman Said Nursi: A Model of Interfaith Dialogue, p 4. {{ISBN|0754669319}}</ref>\n* 1960s&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen begins attracting disciples while a state preacher in [[Izmir]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1971&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen arrested for a stated crime of organizing and/or participating in activities to change the basis of the constitutional system but is released seven months later.{{Citation needed | date=August 2010}}\n* late 1970s&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen establishes himself independently of other Nurju organizations; first ''\u0131\u015f\u0131k evleri'' (\"houses of light\", i.e., student residences){{Citation needed|date=March 2013}} established{{Citation needed | date=August 2010}}\n* 1978&nbsp;\u2013 First ''dershane'' (study center for university exams) opens{{Citation needed | date=August 2010}}\n* 1979&nbsp;\u2013 Science journal ''S\u0131z\u0131nt\u0131'' begins publication<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tr.fgulen.com/content/view/10747/3/|title=Son Karakol|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827033058/http://tr.fgulen.com/content/view/10747/3/|archivedate=27 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 1981&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen retires{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1982&nbsp;\u2013 First \"G\u00fclen school\" opens.<ref name=\"turkhaber16042010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.haberturk.com/polemik/haber/515415-100-soruda-fethullah-gulen-ve-hareketi |title= \"100 soruda Fethullah G\u00fclen ve Hareketi\" (Gulen and its movement in 100 questions) |publisher= HaberTurk |date= 16 April 2010 |accessdate= 18 April 2014}}</ref>\n* 1986&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[Zaman (newspaper)|Zaman]]'', a daily newspaper in Turkey,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medyatava.com/tiraj/ |title=Tiraj |publisher=Medyatava |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref> begins publication, later becoming one of Turkey's top selling newspapers\n* 1988\u20131991&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen gives lectures in Istanbul and Izmir{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1991&nbsp;\u2013 Fall of Soviet Union permits establishment of G\u00fclen schools in [[Central Asia]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1994&nbsp;\u2013 The (Turkish) Journalists and Writers Foundation (Gazeteciler ve Yazarlar Vakfi) established, with G\u00fclen as honorary president<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fuchs Ebaugh|first1=Helen Rose|title=The Gulen Movement: A Sociological Analysis of a Civic Movement Rooted in Moderate Islam|publisher=Springer|page=89|year=2009}}</ref>\n* 1996&nbsp;\u2013 Creation of [[Bank Asya|Asya Finans]] (investment bank aimed at former Soviet Central Asia), with [[Tansu \u00c7iller]] as an investor{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1998&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen meets with [[Pope John Paul II]] in the Vatican<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Salih|first1=Yucel|title=Muslim-Christian Dialogue: Nostra Aetated and Fethullah Gulen's Philosophy of Dialogue|journal=Australian eJournal of Theology|date=Dec 2013|page=200}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Michel S.J.|first1=Thomas|title=\"Fethullah Gulen and Pope John Paul II: \"Two Frontrunners for Peace\"|journal=Dialogue Asia-Pacific|date=Oct\u2013Dec 2007|issue=14|pages=6\u20138}}</ref>\n* 1999&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen movement schools in [[Tashkent]] closed by Uzbekistan government after a rift between Turkish and Uzbek governments{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n* 1999&nbsp;\u2013 G\u00fclen emigrates to [[Pennsylvania]] after the Turkish government charges him with attempting to set up an [[Islamism|Islamist]] state in Turkey<ref name=\"Journal-28Dec2013\"/>\n* 2004&nbsp;\u2013 Establishment of Niagara Foundation<ref>{{cite web|author1=Niagara Foundation|title=History Niagara Foundation|url=http://www.niagarafoundation.org/niagara/history/|website=Niagara Foundation|quote=The Niagara Foundation was created in 2004 by a group of Turkish-American businessmen and educators in order to realize the vision of their spiritual leader, Fethullah Gulen, himself a Turkish Muslim scholar and poet, as well as an educational and humanitarian activist. Today the Niagara Foundation is active in nine Midwestern states with 22 branches.}}</ref>\n* 2004&nbsp;\u2013 Establishment of ''[[Kimse Yok Mu]]'' (Is Anybody There?), a charitable organization;<ref>{{cite web|last1=Michel, S.J.|first1=Thomas|title=Fighting Poverty with Kimse Yok Mu|url=http://fgulen.com/en/gulen-movement/conference-papers/gulen-conference-in-washington/26437-fighting-poverty-with-kimse-yok-mu?hitcount=0|website=Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site.}}</ref> 2010, receives \"special\" NGO status with United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esango.un.org/civilsociety/simpleSearch.do?method=search&searchTypeRedef=simpleSearch&sessionCheck=false&searchType=simpleSearch&organizationNamee=kimse+yok+mu&Submit=Go|title=United Nations Search results for CSos|website=esango.un.org}}</ref>\n* 2005&nbsp;\u2013 Establishment of [[TUSKON]] ([[Turkish Confederation of Businessmen and Industrialists]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuskon.org/?p=content&cl=kurumsal&l=kurumsal |title=Hakk\u0131nda |publisher=TUSKON |date= |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref>\n* 2012&nbsp;\u2013 Journalists and Writers Foundation ([[:tr:Gazeteciler ve Yazarlar Vakf\u0131|Gazeteciler ve Yazarlar Vakfi]]) receives \"general consultative status\" as a Non-Governmental Organization of the Economic and Social Council ([[United Nations Economic and Social Council|ECOSOC]]) of the United Nations.<ref>{{cite web|author1=United Nations Economic and Social Council|title=List of non-governmental organizations in consultative status with the Economic and Social Council as of 1 September 2013|url=http://esango.un.org/civilsociety/documents/E_2013_INF_6.pdf|website=United Nations Economic and Social Council|page=3|date=3 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Common terms==\nExpressions used within the G\u00fclen movement include:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fgulen.com/en/home/1346-fgulen-com-english/conference-papers/gulen-conference-in-indonesia/27013-gulens-educational-philosophy-striving-for-the-golden-generation-of-muslims|title=G\u00fclen's Educational Philosophy: Striving for the Golden Generation of Muslims - Fethullah G\u00fclen's Official Web Site|first=Fethullah|last=G\u00fclen|website=fgulen.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ahvalnews.com/gulenists/ally-enemy-1-gulen-movement-1|title=The 'ally' to 'enemy # 1': G\u00fclen Movement (1) - Ahval}}</ref>\n;''[[Risale-i Nur]]''\n:[[Sufism]]-influenced [[Quran]]ic [[exegesis]] written 1910s\u201350s by [[Said Nursi]] (1877\u20131960). Title of this multi-volume compilation translates to \"Treatise of Light\"\n\n;''[[Bedi\u00fczzaman]]''\n: Honorific name, meaning \"light or wonder of time,\" used to refer to Nursi (See above).<ref>http://www.bediuzzamansaidnursi.org/en/icerik/brief-introduction-life-and-thought-bediuzzaman-said-nursi</ref>\n\n;''Nurcu''\n:[Followers] \"of Nursi\". Many of these, but not all, participate in the G\u00fclen movement.\n\n;''[[Hodjaefendi]]''\n: Honorific name, meaning \"respected teacher,\" used to refer to G\u00fclen.<ref>https://fgulen.com/en/gulen-movement/47137-what-does-hodjaefendi-mean</ref>\n\n;''\u015eakird''\n: \"Disciple\". A full participant in the movement.\n\n;''A\u011fabey''\n: \"Elder brother\". Appellation used, within movement etiquette, for any movement brethren of greater age than oneself.\n\n;''Abla''\n: \"Sister\". A female participant.\n\n;''sohbet''\n:\"Discussion\". The movement's Islamic-spirituality study groups.\n\n;''isti\u015fare''\n:\"Consultation\". Pastoral counseling, as, for example, that of a student collective residing in a dorm with the dorm's volunteer lay imam. Any similar consultation anywhere up the organizational ladder.\n\n;''esnaf''\n:\"Artisan\". A tradesman capable of philanthropic support of the movement's societal aims\n\n;''dost''\n:\"Friend\". A person sympathetic to the societal aims of the movement. Need not be Muslim\n\n;''m\u00fcspet''\n:\"Positive\". Those able to invest in, donate to, or provide executive services for independent businesses or foundations owned by collections of individuals participating in the movement.\n\n;''ehl-i d\u00fcnya''\n:\"People of the world\" (secular society).\n\n;''himmet''\n:[[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman]]- (pre-Kemalist) Turkish word for \"from a strong spiritual determination and aspiration\" (a term is used in Sufism). Charitable donations toward societal aims of the movement.\n\n;''Hizmet''\n:\" Service\" Another term for the movement.\n\n;''[[cemaat]]\n:\"Fellow local members in the movement\" (or, the movement as a whole). Turkish form of Arabic ''[[Jamiya]]'' ('congregation') and related to Turkish ''cuma'' ('Friday') the day of congregational prayers (Arabic: ''[[Jumu'ah]]'').\n\n;''I\u015f\u0131k evler''\n:\"Light houses\". Informal appellation for communal houses such as students' dorms.\n\n;''\u0130lgilenmek''\n:\"[To] be interested in [someone]\". An individual akin to a godfather who encourages piety, hard work, service, etc.\n\n;''Kafalamak''\n:\"Head\" (verb). Occasional humorous term for someone such as the above (with the idiomatic meaning: \"[to] convince [someone of something]\")\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Islam|Turkey}}\n* [[Interfaith dialogue]]\n* [[Fethullah Gulen]]\n* [[Sunni Islam]]\n* [[Sufism]]\n\n==Further information==\n* {{cite book|url = https://uofupress.lib.utah.edu/turkeys-july-15th-coup/|author = M Hakan Yavuz & Bayram Balci|year = 2018|title = Turkey's July 15th Coup: What Happened and Why|series = Utah Series in Middle East Studies|publisher = [[University of Utah Press]]|isbn = 9781607816065}}\n* {{cite book|editors = [http://www.fountainmagazine.com/ ''The Fountain: Of Life, Knowledge, and Belief'']|url = https://fgulen.com/en/what-went-wrong-with-turkey|date = 2017|title = What Went Wrong with Turkey? ''(special issue)''|type = bi-monthly journal of interfaith dialogue, intercultural studies, art, and history|publisher= Blue Dome Press (affiliated with the [[Hizmet]] movement)|place = [[Clifton, New Jersey]]|version = Engl. lang.|asin = B0032FPQKE}}\n* {{cite book|author = Faruk Mercan|publisher = Blue Dome Press|year = 2017|title = No Return from Democracy: A Survey of Interviews with Fethullah Gulen|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5jAgMQAACAAJ&dq=|isbn = 978-1682060179}}\n* {{cite book|title = Toward an Islamic Enlightenment: The G\u00fclen Movement|author = M. Hakan Yavuz|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2013|url = https://books.google.com/?id=qsTdpmviIQ4C|isbn = 9780199927999}}\n* {{cite journal|url = http://www.ecfr.eu/publications/summary/the_good_the_bad_and_the_gulenists7131 |title = The good, the bad and the G\u00fclenists: The Role of the Gulen Movement in Turkey's Coup Attempt|publisher = ecfr.eu|journal = [[European Council on Foreign Relations]]|author = Asli Ayd\u0131nta\u015fba\u015f|date = September 2016|isbn = 978-1-910118-88-7}}\n* {{cite book|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hc7QAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2014|title = The House of Service: The G\u00fclen Movement and Islam's Third Way|isbn = 9780199336418|author = David Tittensor}}\n* {{cite web |title= G\u00fclen movement: Creating an elite to lead the state |date= November 26, 2017 |author= Timur Tin\u00e7url |url= https://www.dandc.eu/en/article/turkish-guelen-movement-expanding-worldwide-opinions-differ-reasons-why |publisher= [[D+C Development and Cooperation]]}}\n* {{cite web|title = Creating an elite to lead the state: The Gulen movement in Turkey|url = http://en.qantara.de/node/29833|publisher = [[Qantara.de]]|author = Timur Tin\u00e7|date = December 27, 2017}}\n* {{cite journal|url = https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2017/12/turkey-finally-some-gulenists-speak-out.html|title = Gulenists Speak Out at Last|author = Mustafa Akyol|date = December 7, 2017|journal = [[Al-Monitor]]|postscript = &nbsp;(a review of former Hizmet participants' scholarly commentary about the movement)}}\n* {{cite news|url =https://ahvalnews.com/turkey/loathed-hunted-down-gulen-movement-finished-turkey |publisher = [[Ahval]]|date = February 28, 2018|title = Loathed, hunted down, G\u00fclen Movement finished in Turkey|author = Nick Ashdown}}\n* {{cite web|author = Ali Moore |publisher = [[Jakarta Post]]|title = The rise, fall and future of Turkey's G\u00fclen movement|date = October 31, 2019|type = audio of roundtable discussion with academics David Tittensor & Tezcan G\u00fcm\u00fc\u015f at [[University of Melbourne]]'s Asia Institute|url = https://www.thejakartapost.com/multimedia/2019/10/14/the-rise-fall-and-future-of-turkey-s-gulen-movement.html}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|1=https://fgulen.com/}}\n* [http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/guelen-movement-accused-of-being-a-sect-a-848763.html ''Altruistic Society or Sect? The Shadowy World of the Islamic G\u00fclen Movement'']\n* {{cite news|newspaper = [[USA Today]]|url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/10/17/turkish-gulen-supporters-fleeing-crackdown-seek-asylum-new-jersey/4006257002/|title = Labeled terrorists in their homeland, hundreds of Turks seek asylum in New Jersey|author = Hannan Adely|date = October 17, 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gulen Movement}}\n[[Category:G\u00fclen movement| ]]\n[[Category:Islam and politics]]\n[[Category:Islamism in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Sunni Islamic branches]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Turkey]]\n[[Category:Political movements in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Sufi organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Mehmet Y\u0131lmaz1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAssassination of Andrei Karlov:Link main)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%BClen_movement"}
